{"term":"1967","caseName":"Federal Power Commission v. Sunray DX Oil Company","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1967/60","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 23, 1968","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren15/oral_argument_audio/14987","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 60, Sunray DX Oil Company et al. and companion cases.","start":0,"stop":14.254,"duration":14.25},{"text":"Mr. Simon, you may proceed with your argument.","start":14.254,"stop":20.869,"duration":6.62}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":20.869,"stop":24.894,"duration":4.02},{"text":"I appear in these cases on behalf of four clients, the Public Service Commission of the State of New York which is a regulatory agency of that state, and three public utilities serving in the Philadelphia, New York area; Philadelphia Electric Company, Brooklyn Union Gas Company, Long Island Lighting Company.","start":24.894,"stop":44.314,"duration":19.42},{"text":"We appear in these cases are representatives of the consumer interest.","start":44.314,"stop":48.923,"duration":4.61},{"text":"In these proceedings before the Commission, the contest was between the producers who are regulated by the Commission and who were the applicants for certificates of public convenience and necessity on the one hand and ourselves with some general support from the staff of the Federal Power Commission on the other.","start":48.923,"stop":67.899,"duration":18.98},{"text":"There are three principal issues in this case; their short form is need, in-line and refund.","start":67.899,"stop":77.31,"duration":9.41},{"text":"On the need issue, the question is whether the Federal Power Commission can grant certificates of public convenience and necessity to the producer applicants authorizing them to make their sales in interstate commerce without first making a finding that there is a public need for the gas proposed to be sold.","start":77.31,"stop":96.724,"duration":19.41},{"text":"On that issue it was our position that the Commission was required to make a finding of need.","start":96.724,"stop":102.439,"duration":5.71},{"text":"The Commission held that it was not.","start":102.439,"stop":105.67,"duration":3.23},{"text":"The District of Columbia Court of Appeals, District of Columbia Circuit in the decision by a Chief Judge Bazelon agreed with us and this Court has granted certiorari on that issue.","start":105.67,"stop":119.638,"duration":13.97},{"text":"On the second question, the so called in-line issue, the question is at what initial price should the Commission certificate these sales to be sold.","start":119.638,"stop":131.931,"duration":12.29},{"text":"In each of the three dockets, the Commission elevated the in-line price that it had previously found for each of the three areas by one cent per Mcf to correspond with a guideline level that it had previously announced.","start":131.931,"stop":147.027,"duration":15.1},{"text":"We challenged that once in escalation.","start":147.027,"stop":151.433,"duration":4.41},{"text":"The Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit has affirmed the Commission's escalation in the District 4 case Amerada.","start":151.433,"stop":160.29,"duration":8.86},{"text":"The District of Columbia Circuit has reversed the Commission's escalation in the Districts 2 and 3 case, Hawkins and Sinclair.","start":160.29,"stop":168.976,"duration":8.69},{"text":"The Commission, I should add, decide at that one against us also as it had decided the need issue.","start":168.976,"stop":175.576,"duration":6.6},{"text":"The final issue in the case is if the sales are certificated, should the producers make refunds of the amounts that they have collected under temporary certificates during the pendency of the litigation to the extent that those collections exceed the in-line price as finally determined by the Commission after hearing.","start":175.576,"stop":196.553,"duration":20.98},{"text":"As indicated by other counsel earlier, the Commission originally held in a prior opinion, the Skelly Oil opinion in August of 1962, that it would not require refunds.","start":196.553,"stop":209.559,"duration":13.01},{"text":"We, along with Mr. Coleman's client, United Gas Improvement Company appealed that decision to the D.C. Circuit.","start":209.559,"stop":216.141,"duration":6.58},{"text":"The D.C. Circuit in January '64 held that the Commission could not excuse refunds merely because there had been no expressed refund condition in the temporary, that this Court denied certiorari after the D.C. Circuit's decision.","start":216.141,"stop":232.237,"duration":16.1},{"text":"And up to that time, the Commission had decided against us.","start":232.237,"stop":234.874,"duration":2.64},{"text":"After that decision, the Commission substantially decided in our favor.","start":234.874,"stop":239.084,"duration":4.21},{"text":"Accordingly, on these three issues we are opposed to the Commission on need and in-line and we in the Commission are now in agreement on the third question, refund, although there is a slight difference which I will get to when I discuss that issue.","start":239.084,"stop":255.675,"duration":16.59},{"text":"Now, it appears to us that one of the reasons that the Commission went wrong here is because it overlooked the very basic elements that are involved in this case.","start":255.675,"stop":270.824,"duration":15.15},{"text":"And I want just for a moment to go back to the basics that are involved in the Natural Gas Act.","start":270.824,"stop":276.658,"duration":5.83},{"text":"These are very elementary matters.","start":276.658,"stop":278.236,"duration":1.58},{"text":"I apologize to the Court for being so basic.","start":278.236,"stop":281.35,"duration":3.11},{"text":"But I think that even as expert a body is the Commission may have jumped in a little too late.","start":281.35,"stop":286.823,"duration":5.47},{"text":"May not have gone back into what the Gas Act is all about.","start":286.823,"stop":291.091,"duration":4.27},{"text":"This Court has reminded that time and time again, that the Natural Gas Act is designed to protect the consumer.","start":291.091,"stop":297.527,"duration":6.44},{"text":"It is a piece of consumer protective legislation.","start":297.527,"stop":300.869,"duration":3.34},{"text":"That is its purpose.","start":300.869,"stop":302.388,"duration":1.52},{"text":"That is its design.","start":302.388,"stop":303.893,"duration":1.5},{"text":"That has been the consistent interpretation given to it by this Court.","start":303.893,"stop":309.263,"duration":5.37},{"text":"This Court has phrased that protection in various ways, at various times but it has always been extremely consistent.","start":309.263,"stop":315.906,"duration":6.64},{"text":"It was to protect the consumer from exploitation of the hands of Natural Gas companies.","start":315.906,"stop":320.306,"duration":4.4},{"text":"It was the phrase that Mr. Justice Douglas used in the Hope case back in the 40s.","start":320.306,"stop":326.239,"duration":5.93},{"text":"That phrase was repeated in a whole series of cases in the late 50s and the early 60s.","start":326.239,"stop":332.3,"duration":6.06},{"text":"Mr. Justice Clark in the CATCO case which is really the lead case so far as this whole area of producer certification under Section 7 is concerned, said that the purpose of the Act was to provide a complete, permanent, and effective bond of protection to the consumer from excessive rates and charges.","start":332.3,"stop":353.132,"duration":20.83},{"text":"This then is the purpose of the Act.","start":353.132,"stop":356.479,"duration":3.35},{"text":"And I think that it is interesting both in the Commission's opinion to some extent in its brief and on argument yesterday that Commission counsel has noted that the Commission has taken a middle ground between the consumer contentions and the producer contentions.","start":356.479,"stop":375.15,"duration":18.67},{"text":"Now, that maybe a perfectly accurate description of what the Commission did, and I will come to that later too.","start":375.15,"stop":381.609,"duration":6.46},{"text":"But I don't think that is -- it is any sort of a defense for the Commission to make of its actions here.","start":381.609,"stop":387.218,"duration":5.61},{"text":"It is not charged by statute with adopting a middle ground between contending conditions -- positions.","start":387.218,"stop":393.978,"duration":6.76},{"text":"It is charged with protecting the consumer and that is an affirmative duty.","start":393.978,"stop":398.842,"duration":4.86},{"text":"And when it has failed to discharge that duty, this Court and the Courts of Appeals have found it necessary to remind the Commission of its duty and to reverse the Commission's action.","start":398.842,"stop":410.333,"duration":11.49}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no other duty at all although except every single contentions made by every representative of every consumer.","start":410.333,"stop":415.304,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly not, certainly not.","start":415.304,"stop":416.797,"duration":1.49},{"text":"And I -- let me make perfectly clear, Mr. Justice Stewart that by saying that we are consumer representatives does not relieve us one iota of the burden of making persuasive arguments in the statutory terms to you and to persuade you.","start":416.797,"stop":433.091,"duration":16.29},{"text":"And I meant to obtain no advantage in that sense.","start":433.091,"stop":436.616,"duration":3.52},{"text":"I merely wanted to indicate what our interest was.","start":436.616,"stop":439.469,"duration":2.85},{"text":"The Commission is certainly not bound to accept a contention because we make it.","start":439.469,"stop":443.77,"duration":4.3},{"text":"On the other hand, I don't think that it's discharging its duty to say that it hit somewhere in between the two contentions.","start":443.77,"stop":451.847,"duration":8.08},{"text":"Its obligation is to do what the statute commands it to do, not to mediate to opposing contentions.","start":451.847,"stop":458.91,"duration":7.06},{"text":"It's not a mediation board.","start":458.91,"stop":460.499,"duration":1.59},{"text":"It has affirmative duties.","start":460.499,"stop":462.721,"duration":2.22},{"text":"Now, the section of the statute we're dealing with is Section 7.","start":462.721,"stop":466.854,"duration":4.13},{"text":"That came into the Act in 1942.","start":466.854,"stop":468.919,"duration":2.06},{"text":"The original act was passed in '38.","start":468.919,"stop":470.756,"duration":1.84},{"text":"The original act had -- the heart of the original Act if you will was Sections 4 and 5 which gave the Commission control over rates.","start":470.756,"stop":481.455,"duration":10.7},{"text":"Section 7 came in 1942.","start":481.455,"stop":484.293,"duration":2.84},{"text":"That was the certificate section.","start":484.293,"stop":485.796,"duration":1.5},{"text":"And it says in essence, that no person may sell natural gas for resale in interstate commerce without first obtaining a certificate of public convenience and necessity from the Commission.","start":485.796,"stop":498.301,"duration":12.5},{"text":"When an applicant seeks a certificate, the Commission is charged by statute with giving notice and providing for a hearing.","start":498.301,"stop":506.984,"duration":8.68},{"text":"The hearing is statutorily required; the Commission has no power or authority to waive a hearing on a certificate application.","start":506.984,"stop":514.912,"duration":7.93},{"text":"If at the hearing, it is found among other things, that the certificate is required by the public convenience and necessity.","start":514.912,"stop":524.155,"duration":9.24},{"text":"And I think that required in the context of the need issue certainly is the keyword here.","start":524.155,"stop":530.29,"duration":6.13},{"text":"If the sale proposed to be made is required by the public convenience and necessity, then a certificate shall issue.","start":530.29,"stop":539.529,"duration":9.24},{"text":"Otherwise, it shall be denied.","start":539.529,"stop":541.746,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the complete mandatory basis for your argument on this point?","start":541.746,"stop":545.334,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"On need?","start":545.334,"stop":546.793,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"On this point?","start":546.793,"stop":546.819,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":546.819,"stop":547.714,"duration":0.9},{"text":"Yes it is.","start":547.714,"stop":548.335,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"On need?","start":548.335,"stop":549.632,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Indeed.","start":549.632,"stop":551.116,"duration":1.48},{"text":"There are two other aspects of the statute which should be mentioned.","start":551.116,"stop":556.079,"duration":4.96},{"text":"One is the Commission has a conditioning power to cure a proposal that is largely correct but partially incorrect.","start":556.079,"stop":565.349,"duration":9.27},{"text":"The Commission does not have to deny it in total.","start":565.349,"stop":568.105,"duration":2.76},{"text":"It can condition its approval on deletion of the unsatisfactory aspects.","start":568.105,"stop":572.366,"duration":4.26},{"text":"And it was its conditioning power that led to the in-line conditioning concept in this Court's 1959 CATCO decision.","start":572.366,"stop":581.058,"duration":8.69},{"text":"There is another provision of the Act that provides in cases of emergency, the Commission may during the pendency of a decision on the application for a certificate, grant a temporary certificate without notice and without hearing.","start":581.058,"stop":595.281,"duration":14.22},{"text":"This is an emergency power.","start":595.281,"stop":599.307,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't understand insufficiency proposition that it must consider need.","start":599.307,"stop":605.105,"duration":5.8},{"text":"It says that it doesn't have to consider at the time of the application of certificate.","start":605.105,"stop":613.223,"duration":8.12}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that is its contention, Mr. Justice Harlan.","start":613.223,"stop":617.063,"duration":3.84},{"text":"Our problem essentially is this.","start":617.063,"stop":622.781,"duration":5.72},{"text":"In reading yesterday to you from the decision of the court below and this is in Volume 4 of the appendix -- at appendix page 266, Mr. Schiff read, a large part starting over at 265 and ending on to 266.","start":622.781,"stop":644.864,"duration":22.08},{"text":"This is Judge Bazelon's decision in the District of Columbia Circuit.","start":644.864,"stop":648.509,"duration":3.64},{"text":"He stopped, however, prior to what I think must be agreed as the operative part really of the D.C. Circuit's decision after discussing what the Court was not deciding Judge Bazelon states, “We decide only that when a party makes a non-frivolous claim that there is a -- there is no public need for the gas, the FPC must give considered reasons if it decides otherwise.","start":648.509,"stop":678.357,"duration":29.85},{"text":"Its decision must be made before” and that word is emphasized in the court below.","start":678.357,"stop":684.449,"duration":6.09},{"text":"“Its decision must be made before it grants a permanent certificate to the producer.”","start":684.449,"stop":689.115,"duration":4.67},{"text":"Now, we think that at the time it issues a certificate, it has to make a finding of need.","start":689.115,"stop":694.45,"duration":5.34},{"text":"If it has made a finding of need that is appropriate and applicable in some other proceeding, certainly it can refer to that.","start":694.45,"stop":701.164,"duration":6.71},{"text":"We have no objection to that.","start":701.164,"stop":702.988,"duration":1.82},{"text":"Our problem is that it did not purport to refer to any other finding of need that it had made.","start":702.988,"stop":709.089,"duration":6.1},{"text":"That the orders that it was issue in contemporaneous cases indicated that the pipeline purchasers here involved were in a severe take-or-pay situation in which they had contracted to pay for more gas than they could physically take into their system.","start":709.089,"stop":724.408,"duration":15.32},{"text":"And I think it is agreed that that situation imposes additional cost on the pipeline which will eventually be born by the consumer.","start":724.408,"stop":734.677,"duration":10.27},{"text":"Our problem with a lot of what the Commission has done is that, the cost goes through the consumer that we are being called upon to pay for much of the Commission's action, and we don't feel that its action is appropriate.","start":734.677,"stop":746.396,"duration":11.72},{"text":"Now, the Commission did not make a finding before it issued its certificate.","start":746.396,"stop":753.522,"duration":7.13},{"text":"The thought that it can consider it elsewhere, if you analyze what they say very closely, I think, and I do want to be fair that the Commission here.","start":753.522,"stop":761.934,"duration":8.41},{"text":"But I think that what you are left with is, they're saying they could examine it elsewhere.","start":761.934,"stop":767.938,"duration":6},{"text":"They do not really say that it is examined elsewhere or that as to these dockets, it has been examined elsewhere.","start":767.938,"stop":776.125,"duration":8.19},{"text":"It's remarkable to me that throughout this entire case, they have nowhere pointed to what other orders they were talking about.","start":776.125,"stop":784.834,"duration":8.71},{"text":"Where they decided that there was some need, it would have been very easy to say in August 1963, in such and such an order we considered this problem, we're relying on that.","start":784.834,"stop":794.61,"duration":9.78},{"text":"There has never been --","start":794.61,"stop":795.687,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Where could they tackle it again, in the pipeline distributor's hearing?","start":795.687,"stop":801.83,"duration":6.14}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"They could in the pipeline hearing surely, no question.","start":801.83,"stop":804.875,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it your contention that they no longer have jurisdiction to do that or what -- or just -- what is your contention?","start":804.875,"stop":812.828,"duration":7.95}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, it's too late I -- I think.","start":812.828,"stop":815.924,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Too late what, legally or physically?","start":815.924,"stop":819.208,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Legally and practically.","start":819.208,"stop":820.745,"duration":1.54},{"text":"I suppose physically it's not.","start":820.745,"stop":822.269,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Tell me why it's too late practically?","start":822.269,"stop":826.754,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"What the Commi -- I think that there is a human tendency to ratify what you have done.","start":826.754,"stop":832.578,"duration":5.82},{"text":"And I think that if you have already certificated producers to sell 100,000 Mcf a day to a pipeline and they are selling it, and they have been selling it for two to three years, that when you come to decide whether the pipeline has a need for that gas two or three years later, you're going to find that they do.","start":832.578,"stop":848.964,"duration":16.39},{"text":"You're not going to find that you'll need a silly decision three years ago.","start":848.964,"stop":851.964,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"You suspect through psychology.","start":851.964,"stop":854.753,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Indeed.","start":854.753,"stop":855.145,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"But now, as a matter of fact what will happen now is that the -- at some -- a producer has been certificated.","start":855.145,"stop":864.208,"duration":9.06},{"text":"At some subsequent time, the pipeline will come in and present to the Commission its application to buy the gas, is that right, to end up --","start":864.208,"stop":872.683,"duration":8.48}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Not really.","start":872.683,"stop":874.274,"duration":1.59},{"text":"Not really Mr. Justice Fortas.","start":874.274,"stop":875.594,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of the gas.","start":875.594,"stop":876.554,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"The principle pipeline proceedings are proceedings in which the pipeline is seeking authority to construct facilities, to make sales, and to make sales itself.","start":876.554,"stop":887.342,"duration":10.79},{"text":"And the issue of pipeline need in that kind of a proceeding is, does the pipeline have enough gas to make the sale that it is proposing feasible?","start":887.342,"stop":896.332,"duration":8.99},{"text":"Now, it is true that in some cases perhaps many did, although the figure isn't in the record the Commission council yesterday said about 75% of the gas involved some sort of the future sales, involved some sort of pipeline application.","start":896.332,"stop":912.432,"duration":16.1}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"For a pipeline construction.","start":912.432,"stop":913.891,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Construction, yes.","start":913.891,"stop":915.977,"duration":2.09},{"text":"It is possible that the issue could be raised there but --","start":915.977,"stop":919.831,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then, are you complaining about the balance of the 25%?","start":919.831,"stop":923.559,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I'm complaining about the 100%.","start":923.559,"stop":926.351,"duration":2.79},{"text":"Because (Voice Overlap) the statutory scheme says such a review in Section 7 --","start":926.351,"stop":931.646,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright, I'll --","start":931.646,"stop":932.651,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"At the time you issue a certificate --","start":932.651,"stop":934.576,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but forgive me I'm trying to get to the -- went to my mind rightly or wrongly if the administrative reality of what we're dealing with here is the position as follows, taking these certificates, these producer's certificates with which we're dealing right now.","start":934.576,"stop":955.256,"duration":20.68},{"text":"Is that the position that -- let's say with respect to 75% of the gas involved, there will be subsequent applications to construct pipeline--","start":955.256,"stop":966.311,"duration":11.06}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":966.311,"stop":966.627,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- facilities at which time the need will have to be considered.","start":966.627,"stop":970.252,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there are apparently were some conglomeration of various hearings in which authority for the relatively minor facilities to attach the gas have been held, have been noticed and certificates issued in the past.","start":970.252,"stop":985.708,"duration":15.46},{"text":"There was one case that did go to hearing, the Lone Star Gathering case subsequent to this.","start":985.708,"stop":994.045,"duration":8.34},{"text":"I do want to point -- as I simply, the principal type of pipeline case, the case where the pipeline wants to make sales.","start":994.045,"stop":1000.124,"duration":6.08}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Have I made my question --","start":1000.124,"stop":1001.546,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so.","start":1001.546,"stop":1002.188,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure that I have --","start":1002.188,"stop":1003.642,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I think you have.","start":1003.642,"stop":1004.664,"duration":1.02},{"text":"I want to get to the budget type authority.","start":1004.664,"stop":1008.419,"duration":3.75},{"text":"Each year, several years ago, the Commission adopted a regulation.","start":1008.419,"stop":1012.817,"duration":4.4},{"text":"There had been a contention that for the relatively minor facilities, a pipeline might need to attach to supplies.","start":1012.817,"stop":1020.211,"duration":7.39},{"text":"And in some cases, apparently 25% of the cases, it might mean no facilities at all to attach supplies.","start":1020.211,"stop":1025.602,"duration":5.39},{"text":"The sale might be made out in an existing point on the pipeline's facilities.","start":1025.602,"stop":1032.851,"duration":7.25},{"text":"The pipeline each year will say we would like general blanket authority to construct such facilities as we need to attach such gas as we may buy from time to time.","start":1032.851,"stop":1047.144,"duration":14.29},{"text":"The gas is not identified, the facilities are not identified.","start":1047.144,"stop":1049.989,"duration":2.85},{"text":"The Commission said in adopting this regulation, that it had been proposed to exempt these facilities altogether since they were not sales facilities.","start":1049.989,"stop":1059.614,"duration":9.63},{"text":"And the Act speaks in terms of sales, regulating sales, and the facility is used to make sales.","start":1059.614,"stop":1064.79,"duration":5.18},{"text":"They said, “We won't exempt them altogether.","start":1064.79,"stop":1066.353,"duration":1.56},{"text":"We'll give these blanket authorities.”","start":1066.353,"stop":1068.309,"duration":1.96},{"text":"So I supposed that it is in those proceedings where the pipeline gets whatever authority it needs but there is no study in those proceedings as to whether the pipeline has a need for the gas or not.","start":1068.309,"stop":1080.441,"duration":12.13}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"The point that I'm raising and perhaps somebody else will see, as well see address himself to, perhaps the Commission's counsel on rebuttal.","start":1080.441,"stop":1091.965,"duration":11.52},{"text":"Will there or will there not, come a point of time at which you and other interested persons will have an opportunity as a matter of administrative procedure to object to the -- to object on the grounds that there is no need for these facilities?","start":1091.965,"stop":1115.065,"duration":23.1},{"text":"So that if you prevail at that time, the consumers whom you represent, will not be settled with additional cost.","start":1115.065,"stop":1125.744,"duration":10.68},{"text":"That's my --","start":1125.744,"stop":1127.228,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"At no time in the future.","start":1127.228,"stop":1127.824,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the question I stated as distilled as much as I can do.","start":1127.824,"stop":1136.069,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think I understand here the question, Mr. Justice Fortas.","start":1136.069,"stop":1140.28,"duration":4.21},{"text":"The answer to your question is no.","start":1140.28,"stop":1143.566,"duration":3.29},{"text":"The reason for the answer is that the Commission says that there have been other proceedings at some other times.","start":1143.566,"stop":1149.772,"duration":6.21},{"text":"They are not identified.","start":1149.772,"stop":1151.475,"duration":1.7},{"text":"They say some of them perhaps were before these hearings came on.","start":1151.475,"stop":1154.747,"duration":3.27},{"text":"Some were after these hearings came on but they were not identified in any general sense.","start":1154.747,"stop":1158.853,"duration":4.11},{"text":"They were by and large, this budget applications which there's a one or two-page notice that identifies nothing.","start":1158.853,"stop":1165.281,"duration":6.43},{"text":"Now, there was one proceeding in the Sinclair case about almost half of the gas in the Sinclair case was proposed to be sold to Lone Star Gathering Company for in district two, Lone Star was a short line that would gather the gas, do what processing was necessary, resell it to United Gas Pipeline.","start":1165.281,"stop":1186.809,"duration":21.53},{"text":"The sales to Lone Star were included in the Sinclair proceeding.","start":1186.809,"stop":1192.445,"duration":5.64},{"text":"The applications of Lone Star and United had been filed sometime before we had intervened in that proceeding.","start":1192.445,"stop":1199.723,"duration":7.28},{"text":"The Commission never set it for hearing.","start":1199.723,"stop":1201.921,"duration":2.2},{"text":"It issued temporary certificates to the pipelines.","start":1201.921,"stop":1204.763,"duration":2.84},{"text":"It issued first temporaries then permanent certificates in Sinclair to the producers to make the sale.","start":1204.763,"stop":1210.863,"duration":6.1},{"text":"After it had issued the certificates to Sinclair, it set Lone Star and United applications for hearing.","start":1210.863,"stop":1218.36,"duration":7.5},{"text":"We participated in that hearing.","start":1218.36,"stop":1221.562,"duration":3.2},{"text":"And what happened was very interesting.","start":1221.562,"stop":1225.023,"duration":3.46},{"text":"After it went through the hearing the first time, the Commission found -- the majority of the Commission found that United had a need for the gas and it should be approved.","start":1225.023,"stop":1234.438,"duration":9.42},{"text":"And what they had done in Sinclair was right.","start":1234.438,"stop":1237.315,"duration":2.88},{"text":"And the concurring opinion on that case pointed out that all the Commission really was doing, was ratifying its prior Sinclair opinion.","start":1237.315,"stop":1245.077,"duration":7.76},{"text":"It pointed out that as a human psychological matter if you will, unless need as examined when the producers have their applications pending, it will never be examined at all.","start":1245.077,"stop":1257.629,"duration":12.55},{"text":"In any event, the Commission finally need issued a certificate.","start":1257.629,"stop":1261.273,"duration":3.64},{"text":"We then applied for rehearing, pointing out the numerous legal and factual areas that the Commission had made.","start":1261.273,"stop":1269.405,"duration":8.13},{"text":"The Commission on rehearing concluded that United, the ultimate purchaser from Lone Star Gathering, had not adequately shown need, that there were a number of defects in its presentation, and set the matter rather than denied a certificate.","start":1269.405,"stop":1283.848,"duration":14.44},{"text":"However, it set the matter down so that Lone Star and United could try a second time to prove need.Lone Star and United first ask for postponement, another postponement.","start":1283.848,"stop":1294.859,"duration":11.01},{"text":"Then they said, “We give up.","start":1294.859,"stop":1296.974,"duration":2.12},{"text":"We really don't need the gas if that's what we have to prove.”","start":1296.974,"stop":1301.09,"duration":4.12},{"text":"Their certificates were cancelled or the permanent certificates were simply revoked, that had never become -- the permanent certificates had never become final.","start":1301.09,"stop":1310.596,"duration":9.51},{"text":"And that gas is no longer being sold in interstate commerce, almost half of the gas in the Sinclair proceeding.","start":1310.596,"stop":1318.76,"duration":8.16},{"text":"I think that when you count, if there is a time to test it and particularly if the judgment is not clouded by the fact that the Commission has already granted permanent certification, then I think we will have some very interesting results on whether there is a need for gas and how much of the need.","start":1318.76,"stop":1336.659,"duration":17.9},{"text":"But the statute says before you can issue a certificate, you must find that there's a need.","start":1336.659,"stop":1342.042,"duration":5.38},{"text":"And I really don't understand how it is in answered to say “Well, we'll issue this certificate first and we may find a need a year from now or two years from now or in some other proceeding.”","start":1342.042,"stop":1353.744,"duration":11.7},{"text":"The statute seems to say, and it would be consistent with all statutes filing for certificates of public convenience and necessity that before you issue a certificate you have to find that somebody needs the service or the sale that's proposed.","start":1353.744,"stop":1368.542,"duration":14.8}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you, what is the exact point of relationship between the point you aid as to the need and the fixation of a rate?","start":1368.542,"stop":1380.968,"duration":12.43}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"We would think that the basic question here is, is there a need for a gas?","start":1380.968,"stop":1384.979,"duration":4.01},{"text":"If there is a need for gas -- if there is no need, no certificate.","start":1384.979,"stop":1388.293,"duration":3.31},{"text":"If there is a need, then the question becomes at what price, what initial price should the gas be sold.","start":1388.293,"stop":1393.585,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words if you are right, the whole order would fall?","start":1393.585,"stop":1397.162,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, yes sir.","start":1397.162,"stop":1398.064,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Including the fixing of the rate.","start":1398.064,"stop":1400.07,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- well, substantially yes.","start":1400.07,"stop":1402.621,"duration":2.55},{"text":"There is one purpose I think for which a rate would have to be fixed, and that is caused by the temporary certificates.","start":1402.621,"stop":1408.543,"duration":5.92},{"text":"During the pendency of these proceedings, the Commission permitted the sales to be made at prices, which we believe and we think the Commission believes, are excessive.","start":1408.543,"stop":1417.467,"duration":8.92},{"text":"It would be necessary to determine what was the appropriate rate during that period for purposes of making refunds.","start":1417.467,"stop":1423.357,"duration":5.89},{"text":"But other than that and had there been no temporaries, there would be no need to go to the in-line question at all.","start":1423.357,"stop":1429.863,"duration":6.51},{"text":"And that would terminate it if there's no need.","start":1429.863,"stop":1431.457,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In applying this need here, this need determination, argument has to made at the time of temporary certificates.","start":1431.457,"stop":1441.478,"duration":10.02}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1441.478,"stop":1442.81,"duration":1.33},{"text":"On the other hand, much of the problems of the Commission gets into is because, it issues the temporary so readily.","start":1442.81,"stop":1450.93,"duration":8.12},{"text":"The statute speaks in terms of emergency to justify a temporary.","start":1450.93,"stop":1454.904,"duration":3.97},{"text":"The Commission issues temporaries as a routine matter, and I will address myself to this point right here even though it's slightly out of order.","start":1454.904,"stop":1464.649,"duration":9.74},{"text":"There is no hearing.","start":1464.649,"stop":1466.872,"duration":2.22},{"text":"Application for temporary can be a one or two-page sheet.","start":1466.872,"stop":1470.17,"duration":3.3},{"text":"It is responded to by a letter.","start":1470.17,"stop":1474.867,"duration":4.7},{"text":"The Commission issues temporaries as a matter of routine.","start":1474.867,"stop":1477.438,"duration":2.57},{"text":"Every applicant gets one that there they have it.","start":1477.438,"stop":1481.595,"duration":4.16},{"text":"Now, I don't think the temporaries wherever intended to be issued on that kind of basis, I don't think then that the most generous concept of emergency and this is an emergency power.","start":1481.595,"stop":1491.916,"duration":10.32},{"text":"It has granted the ex parte at the time when the consumer who will be called on to pay these charges on others is absent from the proceeding.","start":1491.916,"stop":1500.208,"duration":8.29},{"text":"I don't see how an emergency power can be expanded to cover routine everyday application.","start":1500.208,"stop":1509.074,"duration":8.87},{"text":"But if there were an emergency, I don't think that there would have to be the type of finding of need that I'm talking about at that time.","start":1509.074,"stop":1515.866,"duration":6.79}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think your -- logically, your need argument would carry back the temporary certificate.","start":1515.866,"stop":1522.618,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I think logically that if there's no public need, the Commission has no business issuing a temporary certificate.","start":1522.618,"stop":1528.323,"duration":5.71},{"text":"I would think that the real emergency situation is one where the public is about to go out of gas and something has to be done pretty quick, and you don't have time for a hearing.","start":1528.323,"stop":1536.267,"duration":7.94},{"text":"So you issue a temporary certificate.","start":1536.267,"stop":1538.809,"duration":2.54},{"text":"The Commission issues a temporary certificate because it takes it a while to get around to deciding it on the basis of the hearing.","start":1538.809,"stop":1544.492,"duration":5.68},{"text":"I don't really think that's an emergency situation.","start":1544.492,"stop":1547.87,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Could there be an emergency from the point of view of conservation?","start":1547.87,"stop":1553.868,"duration":6}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Not at all.","start":1553.868,"stop":1554.724,"duration":0.86},{"text":"No.","start":1554.724,"stop":1555.907,"duration":1.18},{"text":"Could there be an emergency from the point of view, yes.","start":1555.907,"stop":1558.686,"duration":2.78},{"text":"I think that that might be a possible legitimate interest.","start":1558.686,"stop":1562.029,"duration":3.34},{"text":"But I would like to run through very briefly the grounds for an emergency certificate.","start":1562.029,"stop":1567.975,"duration":5.95},{"text":"Their drainage, drainage means you have two wells adjacent to each other.","start":1567.975,"stop":1572.591,"duration":4.62},{"text":"One is being produced and the gas from the second one is migrating below the first one.","start":1572.591,"stop":1578.921,"duration":6.33},{"text":"In the Sunray temporary certificate that Mr. Coleman read to you yesterday, the allegation was, that the adjacent well had been contracted to be sold to Tennessee Gas Pipeline and was being sold.","start":1578.921,"stop":1592.695,"duration":13.77},{"text":"And Sunray wanted to get a temporary to sell to Tennessee.","start":1592.695,"stop":1597.653,"duration":4.96},{"text":"Now, there was no public interest here at all because all of the gas would go to Tennessee Gas Pipeline and its customers.","start":1597.653,"stop":1603.092,"duration":5.44},{"text":"And it would simply -- whether it would go through the Sunray well or the adjacent well.","start":1603.092,"stop":1606.837,"duration":3.74},{"text":"There is --","start":1606.837,"stop":1607.622,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"It might be a little rough on the person who owns -- the company who owns the well that's being drained.","start":1607.622,"stop":1614.991,"duration":7.37}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1614.991,"stop":1616.046,"duration":1.06},{"text":"However, since you -- the statute says you can't make a sale until you get a certificate.","start":1616.046,"stop":1622.513,"duration":6.47},{"text":"The statute says there is a hearing.","start":1622.513,"stop":1624.237,"duration":1.72},{"text":"Now, the delay between the time you filed an application on the hearing which is statutorily created, doesn't seem to me to create an emergency right.","start":1624.237,"stop":1633.552,"duration":9.31},{"text":"There is -- flaring of a gas is a basis.","start":1633.552,"stop":1638.459,"duration":4.91},{"text":"Flaring occurs when you have gas being produced from a well that produces both oil and gas.","start":1638.459,"stop":1643.311,"duration":4.85},{"text":"The producer decides he wants to produce it in order to derive revenues from the oil.","start":1643.311,"stop":1649,"duration":5.69},{"text":"He has no outlet for his gas so it is simply burned off in effect.","start":1649,"stop":1653.992,"duration":4.99},{"text":"The states can control flaring.","start":1653.992,"stop":1656.11,"duration":2.12},{"text":"But the decision on whether or not to produce is a decision made by the producer to derive the oil revenues.","start":1656.11,"stop":1662.977,"duration":6.87},{"text":"There is loss of lease.","start":1662.977,"stop":1664.555,"duration":1.58},{"text":"Some of the leases that the producers have with their lessors provide that the lease shall be on production within a certain time.","start":1664.555,"stop":1671.844,"duration":7.29},{"text":"This is a private contract condition.","start":1671.844,"stop":1675.641,"duration":3.8},{"text":"Then there is the broad catch-all category which I think explains the other three, it renders, the other three really mandatory.","start":1675.641,"stop":1682.497,"duration":6.86},{"text":"And that is an economic hardship.","start":1682.497,"stop":1684.667,"duration":2.17},{"text":"And the Commission has accepted as a definition of economic hardship and this is the basis of perhaps the majority of the temporary applications.","start":1684.667,"stop":1693.516,"duration":8.85},{"text":"The loss of revenue that occurs to the producer during the time he is waiting for permanent certificate.","start":1693.516,"stop":1700.266,"duration":6.75},{"text":"Therefore every time you file an application for a permanent certificate, you have, under the Commission's regulation, created a basis for an emergency because you will have to wait sometime until the hearing can be held.","start":1700.266,"stop":1715.077,"duration":14.81},{"text":"It's a peculiar concept to the emergency, I think.","start":1715.077,"stop":1717.634,"duration":2.56},{"text":"It's an unparalleled one.","start":1717.634,"stop":1721.961,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I gather that the Commission always finds that the public convenience and necessity requires the issuance of this --","start":1721.961,"stop":1730.845,"duration":8.88}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it always makes that finding in the statutory line of --","start":1730.845,"stop":1733.169,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But you know that it did in this case?","start":1733.169,"stop":1734.732,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":1734.732,"stop":1735.228,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And at the same time it said that we think the issue of need, however, should be confined to pipeline cases because of the need for the pipelines to range for advanced supply of gas.","start":1735.228,"stop":1751.258,"duration":16.03},{"text":"Now, you just differ with -- you don't think without considering need they could find public --","start":1751.258,"stop":1756.675,"duration":5.42}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1756.675,"stop":1757.806,"duration":1.13},{"text":"You can't say we've satisfied the statute unless you make the findings that really would (Voice Overlap)","start":1757.806,"stop":1761.18,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) disagrees with you?","start":1761.18,"stop":1762.95,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":1762.95,"stop":1763.317,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commission just disagrees with you on the construction of public convenience and necessities.","start":1763.317,"stop":1767.441,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, that's correct.","start":1767.441,"stop":1769.988,"duration":2.55},{"text":"And --","start":1769.988,"stop":1771.424,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"But theoretically anyway there's no impact on consumer interest until a pipeline arrangement has been made.","start":1771.424,"stop":1783.649,"duration":12.22}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Until -- do you mean until the pipeline begins taking that --","start":1783.649,"stop":1786.171,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1786.171,"stop":1788.55,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's correct but the pipeline can take it under temporary ser -- there was a case in Louisiana.","start":1788.55,"stop":1793.947,"duration":5.4},{"text":"Tennessee Gas Transmission CP 60-57 was filed in 1960.","start":1793.947,"stop":1800.335,"duration":6.39},{"text":"We intervened.","start":1800.335,"stop":1801.049,"duration":0.71},{"text":"It was to take some offshore gas.","start":1801.049,"stop":1803.966,"duration":2.92},{"text":"The Commission granted a temporary in 1961.","start":1803.966,"stop":1808.709,"duration":4.74},{"text":"In the meantime, the producer sales were certificated.","start":1808.709,"stop":1812.065,"duration":3.36},{"text":"In 1964, the Commission noticed it again and said, “Does anybody still object to this?”","start":1812.065,"stop":1817.1,"duration":5.03},{"text":"And we said, “Yes we do.”","start":1817.1,"stop":1818.209,"duration":1.11},{"text":"Because Tennessee is in a take-or-pay situation and we want to examine it.","start":1818.209,"stop":1822.549,"duration":4.34},{"text":"And I said “Oh!”","start":1822.549,"stop":1824.315,"duration":1.77},{"text":"and I put it back on the shelf and that's where it's been.","start":1824.315,"stop":1826.607,"duration":2.29},{"text":"So it's not that easy to get a hearing if the Commission doesn't want to give you a hearing, and the Commission really doesn't.","start":1826.607,"stop":1834.078,"duration":7.47},{"text":"That Tennessee line has been going for seven years under a temporary certificate.","start":1834.078,"stop":1838.754,"duration":4.68},{"text":"There has never been a finding as we've been ready from the date the notice was filed.","start":1838.754,"stop":1843.851,"duration":5.1},{"text":"To go to hearing on whether there was a need.","start":1843.851,"stop":1847.642,"duration":3.79},{"text":"And --","start":1847.642,"stop":1848.26,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me; I thought you said -- what I just wanted to ask you, state as simple as you can what it is the need that they should find, need to do what?","start":1848.26,"stop":1864.686,"duration":16.43}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I think essentially there are two aspects of need.","start":1864.686,"stop":1867.642,"duration":2.96},{"text":"One is, is there a public need for this gas?","start":1867.642,"stop":1870.67,"duration":3.03},{"text":"Does the public needed to receive gas service or does --","start":1870.67,"stop":1874.614,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"To receive any gas service?","start":1874.614,"stop":1879.162,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Well yes, sales being made to the consumer, through the distributor, and through the pipeline.","start":1879.162,"stop":1885.328,"duration":6.17},{"text":"Now, if the public can be adequately served without the addition of this gas, if there is no --","start":1885.328,"stop":1892.065,"duration":6.74}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"For this gas or for this pipeline?","start":1892.065,"stop":1893.923,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"This gas.","start":1893.923,"stop":1894.657,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"This gas.","start":1894.657,"stop":1894.963,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"This particular gas.","start":1894.963,"stop":1896.599,"duration":1.64},{"text":"If the public can be served without the addition of this gas then there is no public need.","start":1896.599,"stop":1902.142,"duration":5.54}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean, if there are other competitors who could sell it.","start":1902.142,"stop":1905.838,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1905.838,"stop":1906.393,"duration":0.56},{"text":"If perhaps this pipeline could sell it, I want to go into this take-or-pay problem because it illuminates I think the whole problem of need.","start":1906.393,"stop":1913.726,"duration":7.33},{"text":"In other words if the pipeline is selling say 800,000 Mcf a day, that's its market demand.","start":1913.726,"stop":1921.145,"duration":7.42},{"text":"And if they presently has contracts that give it 800,000 a day, and then it goes up and buys another 100,000 a day, is there a need for the other 100,000?","start":1921.145,"stop":1933.683,"duration":12.54},{"text":"What are they going to do with it?","start":1933.683,"stop":1935.25,"duration":1.57},{"text":"Now, what has happened is the contracts have minimum take provisions.","start":1935.25,"stop":1938.96,"duration":3.71},{"text":"These are 20-year contracts and they provide for takeover the life normally based on an evaluation of the reserves.","start":1938.96,"stop":1947.899,"duration":8.94},{"text":"They contained minimum provisions.","start":1947.899,"stop":1949.348,"duration":1.45},{"text":"You take so much depending on the reserves.","start":1949.348,"stop":1951.875,"duration":2.53},{"text":"You take 10,000 Mcf a day and if you don't take it, you will pay for it anyway.","start":1951.875,"stop":1955.915,"duration":4.04},{"text":"Now, what has happened and this is why we started to raise the need issue.","start":1955.915,"stop":1959.001,"duration":3.09},{"text":"We found that the pipelines were getting in situations increasingly where they were paying for gas that they could not physically put through their system.","start":1959.001,"stop":1966.973,"duration":7.97},{"text":"They had cut all of their contracts down to the minimum take provision that it provided.","start":1966.973,"stop":1972.692,"duration":5.72},{"text":"And not withstanding that, they were paying for gas they couldn't take and accruing huge balances.","start":1972.692,"stop":1979.678,"duration":6.99},{"text":"United Gas Pipeline paid $22 million for gas that it physically could not put through its system.","start":1979.678,"stop":1986.025,"duration":6.35},{"text":"And United was one of the purchasers in the cases that are before this Court.","start":1986.025,"stop":1990.658,"duration":4.63},{"text":"It came to the Commission on a rate case.","start":1990.658,"stop":1992.241,"duration":1.58},{"text":"Now it says, “We want to capitalize it, include it in our rate base, increase rates over what they would otherwise be to reflect this $22 million for gas that we've paid for but couldn't take.”","start":1992.241,"stop":2002.905,"duration":10.66},{"text":"The New York Commission objected to that.","start":2002.905,"stop":2005.192,"duration":2.29},{"text":"And the Commission said, “Well, that's alright.","start":2005.192,"stop":2007.412,"duration":2.22},{"text":"We'll let United include in its rate base.”","start":2007.412,"stop":2010.954,"duration":3.54},{"text":"There are other problems because once this --","start":2010.954,"stop":2012.777,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any finding that the Commission on that particular point which you have just discussed?","start":2012.777,"stop":2019.851,"duration":7.07}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"In the orders here under review?","start":2019.851,"stop":2021.366,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case?","start":2021.366,"stop":2022.225,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2022.225,"stop":2023.223,"duration":1},{"text":"No findings at all.","start":2023.223,"stop":2024.485,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And is that one of the things you're complaining about?","start":2024.485,"stop":2026.592,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"It certainly is, Mr. Justice Black.","start":2026.592,"stop":2029.01,"duration":2.42},{"text":"It certainly is.","start":2029.01,"stop":2029.177,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You're saying that there should be an issue determined when you raised that someone raised the question that they do not need this gas as simply purchase of something they do not need and they'll have to pay for it and that money will be wasted?","start":2029.177,"stop":2044.261,"duration":15.08}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct and the consumer will be taxed for it.","start":2044.261,"stop":2049.083,"duration":4.82},{"text":"That is the heart of it, yes sir.","start":2049.083,"stop":2051.598,"duration":2.51},{"text":"There are other aspects of take-or-pay.","start":2051.598,"stop":2053.179,"duration":1.58},{"text":"What happens --","start":2053.179,"stop":2054.449,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But why should that not that be handled at first?","start":2054.449,"stop":2057.842,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it should.","start":2057.842,"stop":2059.471,"duration":1.63},{"text":"I think that that was the way the Act was written that in the certificate case, you do not permit improper charges to become embedded in the pipelines cost.","start":2059.471,"stop":2069.395,"duration":9.92}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose it's just a minor thing.","start":2069.395,"stop":2071.565,"duration":2.17},{"text":"You wouldn't say that after they begun with --","start":2071.565,"stop":2073.37,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"It would depend on how minor.","start":2073.37,"stop":2075.868,"duration":2.5},{"text":"But I think that's right.","start":2075.868,"stop":2076.867,"duration":1},{"text":"It's trivial and certainly not.","start":2076.867,"stop":2079.483,"duration":2.62},{"text":"The problem that we have found is that this situation has become very widespread throughout the industry.","start":2079.483,"stop":2085.201,"duration":5.72},{"text":"Mr. Schiff said yesterday that the Commission found that it was decreasing.","start":2085.201,"stop":2088.208,"duration":3.01},{"text":"That's just not so.","start":2088.208,"stop":2089.799,"duration":1.59},{"text":"We quote from there in 1955 and 1960 -- the Commissions 1955 and 1966 annual reports to Congress.","start":2089.799,"stop":2099.949,"duration":10.15},{"text":"In those reports, the Commission shows that the take-or-pay balances was increasing and something like 65 million to 85 million.","start":2099.949,"stop":2109.621,"duration":9.67},{"text":"Subsequent to the filing of our reply brief where that is cited.","start":2109.621,"stop":2116.14,"duration":6.52},{"text":"It was called to my attention that although the Commission has to come up with its 1967 annual report is yet the same figure is available in another commission publications statistics of natural gas pipelines.","start":2116.14,"stop":2127.444,"duration":11.3},{"text":"And that at the latest figure as of the end of 1966 has risen another 10% to some $95 million or prepayments.","start":2127.444,"stop":2136.703,"duration":9.26},{"text":"The situation is getting -- these problems don't go away.","start":2136.703,"stop":2140.197,"duration":3.49},{"text":"They don't go away because the Commission refuses to look at it.","start":2140.197,"stop":2142.937,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Doesn't the Commission have some kind of proceeding going on take-or-pay or not?","start":2142.937,"stop":2148.78,"duration":5.84}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"They closed that out.","start":2148.78,"stop":2149.782,"duration":1},{"text":"It was a -- it might have been a good proceeding.","start":2149.782,"stop":2153.026,"duration":3.24},{"text":"One of the problems with this, it was a rule-making proceeding.","start":2153.026,"stop":2155.671,"duration":2.64},{"text":"It was instituted in 1961 when the Commission first became aware of these problems.","start":2155.671,"stop":2161.036,"duration":5.37},{"text":"Now, what their proposed rule would have done, Mr. Justice White, was essentially two things.","start":2161.036,"stop":2167.837,"duration":6.8},{"text":"It would have limited the type of minimum take provision that could be put in any contract.","start":2167.837,"stop":2173.291,"duration":5.45},{"text":"And the effect of this would have been that pipelines would have not have gotten into take-or-pay situations.","start":2173.291,"stop":2180.301,"duration":7.01},{"text":"The second thing it would do is provide a longer period for them to make up the gas once they got in a take-or-pay situation.","start":2180.301,"stop":2187.17,"duration":6.87},{"text":"The Commission let this sit for some six years until the eve of decision in the Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit.","start":2187.17,"stop":2196.384,"duration":9.21},{"text":"Then they came out with their rule and the rule does nothing about the type of minimum take provision that can be put in a contract.","start":2196.384,"stop":2204.162,"duration":7.78},{"text":"It does nothing to alleviate or to prevent the pipeline from getting into a minimum take -- into a take-or-pay provision.","start":2204.162,"stop":2210.801,"duration":6.64},{"text":"All it did was say, that they shall have five years to make up any prepayments that they have made.","start":2210.801,"stop":2216.564,"duration":5.76}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Commission must feel that as a practical matter necessary to contract to hit for gas and arrange for just because of the uncertainty of the future.","start":2216.564,"stop":2228.211,"duration":11.65},{"text":"And I don't suppose that gas companies just thoughtlessly make improvident purchases of gas that could cost (Voice Overlap) --","start":2228.211,"stop":2237.942,"duration":9.73}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I would --","start":2237.942,"stop":2238.321,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- dollars.","start":2238.321,"stop":2240.005,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"When you make that kind of a contract, Mr. Justice White, I think that your judgment is affected by whose going to pay for it.","start":2240.005,"stop":2249.693,"duration":9.69},{"text":"And I think if you're not going to pay for it certainly it's desirable to go out and preempt as much gas as you can.","start":2249.693,"stop":2256.102,"duration":6.41},{"text":"Don't let your competitor get it, don't let any pipeline get it, I suppose that if a pipeline could tie up all of the gas that there is in Southern Louisiana and the Texas Gulf Coast and if there would be assured that its cost in doing so would be passed on to the consumer, it would like to do it whether it needed it or not.","start":2256.102,"stop":2271.934,"duration":15.83},{"text":"It would then be assured of every market there is.","start":2271.934,"stop":2274.849,"duration":2.91},{"text":"This goes to one of the conservation issues too because what has happened here because the Commission does that considered need is, it leads to wasteful and preemptive buying.","start":2274.849,"stop":2285.051,"duration":10.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Can the pipeline buy without the Commission's consent?","start":2285.051,"stop":2289.783,"duration":4.73},{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2289.783,"stop":2290.945,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"It contracts.","start":2290.945,"stop":2291.679,"duration":0.73},{"text":"That enters into a contract, sales contract.","start":2291.679,"stop":2292.914,"duration":1.24},{"text":"That sales contract comes before the Commission in the Producers Certificate case which is what we have right here.","start":2292.914,"stop":2301.825,"duration":8.91},{"text":"Now, there are other aspects as there are other injuries that are caused by take-or-pay problems.","start":2301.825,"stop":2306.929,"duration":5.1},{"text":"I just want to mention one of them and that is this.","start":2306.929,"stop":2309.888,"duration":2.96},{"text":"The take-or-pay problems became more onerous, more observable in the late, very late 50s perhaps and early 60s.","start":2309.888,"stop":2319.238,"duration":9.35},{"text":"And the earlier contracts did not have either this kind of take-or-pay provisions or strict take-or-pay provisions.","start":2319.238,"stop":2329.045,"duration":9.81},{"text":"What the pipelines first started to do therefore, was to cut back on their older contracts, cut back the takes under the older contracts which did not have a minimum take requirement.","start":2329.045,"stop":2339.142,"duration":10.1},{"text":"So they might have two contracts, one calling for the purchase of gas of 20 cents recently contracted.","start":2339.142,"stop":2344.278,"duration":5.14},{"text":"The other calling for the purchase of gas at 9 cents contracted say 10 or 15 years ago.","start":2344.278,"stop":2349.259,"duration":4.98},{"text":"They're entitled under their 9-cent contract say to take 10,000 Mcf a day, but they can take no gas without any penalty.","start":2349.259,"stop":2357.11,"duration":7.85}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it seems to me Mr. Simons that everything you are saying tends to straighten the position that the place to tackle this problem is in the pipeline hearings.","start":2357.11,"stop":2368.926,"duration":11.82},{"text":"Now, what -- take a step back please.","start":2368.926,"stop":2374.329,"duration":5.4},{"text":"Tell us why this problem should be tackled in the producer hearings apart from the psychological --","start":2374.329,"stop":2383.379,"duration":9.05}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"It should be tackled in the producer hearings because it's the producer -- it should be tackled in the producer hearings because it's the producer that's asking for a certificate of public convenience and necessity.","start":2383.379,"stop":2392.441,"duration":9.06}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that but I mean in reality –-","start":2392.441,"stop":2395.886,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"In reality, the one --","start":2395.886,"stop":2396.828,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the argument you've been making here in response from various questions seems to me to be addressed to the undesirability for the take-or-pay provision in the pipeline contracts.","start":2396.828,"stop":2414.791,"duration":17.96},{"text":"Now, why should that particular problem be tackled in the producer hearing beyond a general finding which the statute requires of public convenience and necessity?","start":2414.791,"stop":2427.742,"duration":12.95},{"text":"But why -- how do all of these considerations that you've been so effectively presenting to us relate to the producer hearings?","start":2427.742,"stop":2440.21,"duration":12.47}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the pipeline is the purchaser in the producer hearing.","start":2440.21,"stop":2444.427,"duration":4.22},{"text":"I suppose in any type of proceeding where an applicant is seeking a certificate, it is the applicant who shows his market although his market is composed of people who are not himself.","start":2444.427,"stop":2453.35,"duration":8.92},{"text":"I suppose that a tracker who is seeking a certificate should bring in shippers to show that the shippers have a need for the service proposed.","start":2453.35,"stop":2465.084,"duration":11.73},{"text":"Certainly, in the pipeline cases, the pipeline proves its market by bringing in its customers.","start":2465.084,"stop":2471.251,"duration":6.17},{"text":"It will bring in the distributing companies who will testify as to what their needs for the gas will be.","start":2471.251,"stop":2476.503,"duration":5.25},{"text":"And this -- the Commission has suggested that it's a difficult administrative problem and it's backed off and said really it isn't.","start":2476.503,"stop":2483.577,"duration":7.07},{"text":"But we had in these proceedings a total of five pipeline purchasers.","start":2483.577,"stop":2488.543,"duration":4.97},{"text":"All that would have been required was to bring a witness from each of the five to explain what their present sales are, what their present minimum and maximum entitlements to are under their existing contracts.","start":2488.543,"stop":2504.186,"duration":15.64},{"text":"It's not that difficult and I don't see how you can make --","start":2504.186,"stop":2508.231,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the certificate that's issued to a producer's say in terms of quantity?Does it say anything about quantity?","start":2508.231,"stop":2516.122,"duration":7.89}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":2516.122,"stop":2517.723,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"The certificate that's issued to a producer in the -- in these proceedings, what does it say?","start":2517.723,"stop":2524.161,"duration":6.44}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"It simply to grant some authority to make the sale as filed.","start":2524.161,"stop":2528.624,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"To make the sale, this sale as filed?","start":2528.624,"stop":2532.144,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":2532.144,"stop":2532.683,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's a producer's certificate.","start":2532.683,"stop":2534.396,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":2534.396,"stop":2534.79,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what you're talking about here?","start":2534.79,"stop":2536.894,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2536.894,"stop":2537.703,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"And what you're saying is that that is the time at which there ought to be an inquiry into the terms of the contract for the -- for its bearing upon me?","start":2537.703,"stop":2550.807,"duration":13.1}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":2550.807,"stop":2553.375,"duration":2.57},{"text":"I would like --","start":2553.375,"stop":2554.039,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"For the things that you say just one more -- if you -- if you would prevail, it would mean that the inquiry or need must consider the pipeline situation as a whole.","start":2554.039,"stop":2566.163,"duration":12.12}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Each pipeline?","start":2566.163,"stop":2567.255,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"In every producer certificate hearing --","start":2567.255,"stop":2569.634,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Where the matter is raised.","start":2569.634,"stop":2570.782,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You're not only would be dealing with the -- the specific quantity of gas but the pipeline's total overall situation in each in the markets that it serves.","start":2570.782,"stop":2580.791,"duration":10.01}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Whether it needed this additional gas in order to satisfy its market, yes sir.","start":2580.791,"stop":2585.791,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"It certainly does expand this hearing into a major --","start":2585.791,"stop":2588.497,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think so.","start":2588.497,"stop":2592.35,"duration":3.85},{"text":"It isn't that much of a pipe -- a pipeline will bring in some 40 or 50 customers in each proceeding to show its market.","start":2592.35,"stop":2599.637,"duration":7.29},{"text":"I do want to move on to the in-line issue.","start":2599.637,"stop":2602.001,"duration":2.36},{"text":"I've spent more on need that I had intended.","start":2602.001,"stop":2604.651,"duration":2.65},{"text":"Now, on the in-line, and the in-line doctrine comes from this Court's CATCO decision which said that in certificating new sales, the Commission must protect the consumer against excessive rates and charges by denying sales that are out of line.","start":2604.651,"stop":2624.537,"duration":19.89},{"text":"It is from this concept that the in-line and the hold of the line language has come.","start":2624.537,"stop":2630.087,"duration":5.55},{"text":"Now what the Commission did here, we're talking about the Texas Gulf Coast.","start":2630.087,"stop":2634.063,"duration":3.98},{"text":"There are a series of events.","start":2634.063,"stop":2636.422,"duration":2.36},{"text":"In September 1960, the Commission established guidelines in each of the three areas at 18 cents per Mcf.","start":2636.422,"stop":2642.57,"duration":6.15},{"text":"There is not the slightest question in the world that that did not conform to this Court's CATCO requirement.","start":2642.57,"stop":2647.926,"duration":5.36},{"text":"I don't think that the Commission would so argue.","start":2647.926,"stop":2650.434,"duration":2.51},{"text":"18 cents was out of line.","start":2650.434,"stop":2651.842,"duration":1.41},{"text":"The Commission subsequently found for each of the three areas that on September 28, 1960 when it promulgated its guidelines, the in-line prices in the three areas were 15 cents in Districts 4 and 2, and 16 cents in District 3.","start":2651.842,"stop":2667.251,"duration":15.41},{"text":"Indeed, those in-line determinations subsequently in 1962 and 1963 had found 15 cents was in-line in District 4 and 2, and 16 cents was in-line in District 3.","start":2667.251,"stop":2680.639,"duration":13.39},{"text":"It amended its guideline levels at that time.","start":2680.639,"stop":2685.7,"duration":5.06},{"text":"Instead of amending its guideline levels to the in-line level that had just found as two of the five Commissioners urged, it fixed the guideline level one cent above the in-line level that had just found 16 cents in Districts 4 and 2, 17 cents in District 3.","start":2685.7,"stop":2702.038,"duration":16.34},{"text":"It then sets the instant cases that we have here for hearing.","start":2702.038,"stop":2707.154,"duration":5.12},{"text":"After hearing, the Commission found that wonderful to relate the in-line level for the period after the policy statement was the elevated by one cent guideline levels that it had fixed at the outset of these hearings.","start":2707.154,"stop":2725.131,"duration":17.98},{"text":"Now, a difference of one cent per Mcf, while it sounds small, when we apply it to the industry as a whole amounts to enormous sums of money.","start":2725.131,"stop":2736.18,"duration":11.05},{"text":"It is true that in this case they are not that large but then the Chairman of the Commission has pointed out that if you applied one cent across the board to all natural gas sales, you're talking about a $150 million a year.","start":2736.18,"stop":2748.638,"duration":12.46},{"text":"If you apply it to all of the estimated known reserves in the ground, you're talking about $2.5 billion.","start":2748.638,"stop":2755.81,"duration":7.17},{"text":"Now, the purpose of finding an in-line level, we submit, was to protect the consumer.","start":2755.81,"stop":2761.539,"duration":5.73},{"text":"The way this works is, once the in-line level is found that is the initial price the producer can charge, he can file up under Section 4 for an increase, but if he can't justify the increase, he has to make refunds.","start":2761.539,"stop":2776.194,"duration":14.65},{"text":"The evil of a high in-line prices that there is no way to catch by refunds or otherwise, the excess in the event that it should be determined that that in-line price is higher than the subsequent just and reasonable rate.","start":2776.194,"stop":2790.372,"duration":14.18},{"text":"We think that the whole concept of in-line pricing as you start with CATCO is to find the line and then hold it.","start":2790.372,"stop":2799.366,"duration":8.99},{"text":"Now, the Commission talks about, it has to go to current conditions and contemporaneous conditions.","start":2799.366,"stop":2806.244,"duration":6.88},{"text":"First of all, there's nothing in the cases that suggests that you have to go to contracts which is what the Commission did.","start":2806.244,"stop":2814.526,"duration":8.28},{"text":"The Commission limited its view here to contracts entered into in Amerada for example between 1960 and 1962.","start":2814.526,"stop":2823.138,"duration":8.61},{"text":"But during this times span, there were enormous volumes of gas being sold under contracts dated prior thereto.","start":2823.138,"stop":2830.532,"duration":7.39},{"text":"The Commission ignored all of those prices, fixed itself only on the contracts entered into between 1960 and '62.","start":2830.532,"stop":2838.262,"duration":7.73},{"text":"Those contracts had been entered into at high prices.","start":2838.262,"stop":2841.056,"duration":2.79},{"text":"We had intervened on the applications to make those sales.","start":2841.056,"stop":2844.44,"duration":3.38},{"text":"The Commission says because we intervened, there are no permanently certificated prices.","start":2844.44,"stop":2849.656,"duration":5.22},{"text":"We will therefore look at the prices we have temporarily certificated.","start":2849.656,"stop":2853.078,"duration":3.42},{"text":"In fact, we looked at the very prices that are before us.","start":2853.078,"stop":2856.304,"duration":3.23},{"text":"The Commission in writing at its 16-cent guideline, it relied on 38 contracts.","start":2856.304,"stop":2863.595,"duration":7.29},{"text":"36 of those contracts were the contracts at issue in the Amerada preceding where we were holding a hearing to determine what the in-line level should be.","start":2863.595,"stop":2872.458,"duration":8.86},{"text":"The Commission said, well we will grant certification on the basis of the temporary certificates we've issued.","start":2872.458,"stop":2879.454,"duration":7},{"text":"As noted, these temporary certificates are issued on an ex parte basis.","start":2879.454,"stop":2883.723,"duration":4.27},{"text":"They are not reviewable.","start":2883.723,"stop":2886.791,"duration":3.07},{"text":"When this whole business started out at the time of Skelly, and the Commission first said that it would not make refunds, we appealed the Skelly decision to the District of Columbia Circuit.","start":2886.791,"stop":2896.884,"duration":10.09},{"text":"At the same time, we appealed some temporary certificates which had just been issued which were issued in our view at out of line prices.","start":2896.884,"stop":2904.386,"duration":7.5},{"text":"The two appeals as McDermott and Skelly were heard before the same panel of the D.C. Circuit, at the same time within a couple of weeks.","start":2904.386,"stop":2911.777,"duration":7.39},{"text":"They were decided within a couple of weeks of each other.","start":2911.777,"stop":2914.248,"duration":2.47},{"text":"Both opinions were written by Judge Fahy.","start":2914.248,"stop":2916.769,"duration":2.52},{"text":"And in essence, what he said was, we cannot make a determination on a temporary certificate whether it's right or wrong.","start":2916.769,"stop":2924.759,"duration":7.99},{"text":"These matters are not foreclosed at the end of the proceeding.","start":2924.759,"stop":2927.19,"duration":2.43},{"text":"However, in Skelly he said, at the end of the proceeding, the Commission has to go back and do what is right, make it right from the beginning.","start":2927.19,"stop":2935.603,"duration":8.41},{"text":"We think that's right.","start":2935.603,"stop":2937.696,"duration":2.09},{"text":"If the Commission doesn't have the power to make it right at the end of the proceeding, then we think that the temporary certificate is wrong, right from its inception because it would then be violating CATCO.","start":2937.696,"stop":2947.072,"duration":9.38},{"text":"And of course this goes to a question that you asked Mr. Justice White yesterday.","start":2947.072,"stop":2951.785,"duration":4.71},{"text":"It was answered by Mr. Coleman and I want to support his answer.","start":2951.785,"stop":2955.482,"duration":3.7},{"text":"Could the Commission say in a temporary certificate, “We're giving you a temporary certificate at 18 cents or 20 cents or any price and we're not going to make you give anything back at the end of the hearing no matter what”?","start":2955.482,"stop":2967.195,"duration":11.71},{"text":"Could it do that?","start":2967.195,"stop":2968.137,"duration":0.94},{"text":"No.","start":2968.137,"stop":2968.655,"duration":0.52},{"text":"We don't think legally it has the power to give that kind of money away to be that generous.","start":2968.655,"stop":2974.273,"duration":5.62},{"text":"CATCO said you have to provide a complete permanent and effective bond of protection.","start":2974.273,"stop":2980.294,"duration":6.02},{"text":"And what was involved in CATCO was the excessive initial price between the time of certification and the time you would catch up to the excess in a Section 5 proceeding.","start":2980.294,"stop":2990.307,"duration":10.01},{"text":"But the same reasoning applies to the excess price in the temporary certificate and the time you catch up with it on permanent certification.","start":2990.307,"stop":2998.215,"duration":7.91},{"text":"There is no gap in the Act.","start":2998.215,"stop":2999.823,"duration":1.61},{"text":"This Court has --","start":2999.823,"stop":2999.838,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Don't we -- don't we just about have to get that question here?","start":2999.838,"stop":3002.534,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":3002.534,"stop":3003.233,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Don't we just about have to --","start":3003.233,"stop":3004.911,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I think you do.","start":3004.911,"stop":3005.623,"duration":0.71},{"text":"I think you should.","start":3005.623,"stop":3006.31,"duration":0.69},{"text":"And I think that what you should say --","start":3006.31,"stop":3007.017,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And now the petition turned down a request --","start":3007.017,"stop":3010.239,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3010.239,"stop":3010.893,"duration":0.65},{"text":"Now, we filed that request.","start":3010.893,"stop":3015.385,"duration":4.49},{"text":"At the -- the Commission had just held in Skelly that at the end of the preceding, it wouldn't order refunds.","start":3015.385,"stop":3021.65,"duration":6.26},{"text":"And the Amerada preceding was pending.","start":3021.65,"stop":3023.446,"duration":1.8},{"text":"We said “Alright, if you don't think it's fair at the end, you've got all of this outstanding at 16, 17, 18 cents.","start":3023.446,"stop":3029.376,"duration":5.93},{"text":"We're litigating.","start":3029.376,"stop":3030.063,"duration":0.69},{"text":"We're saying that 15 is the highest.","start":3030.063,"stop":3031.875,"duration":1.81},{"text":"That at least put in a condition now if you don't think it's fair.”","start":3031.875,"stop":3034.792,"duration":2.92},{"text":"We said this is without prejudice to the appeals we're taking in McDermott that you have no right at the outset to do it.","start":3034.792,"stop":3041.195,"duration":6.4},{"text":"It's without prejudice to the appeal we're taking in Skelly that you can make refunds at the end.","start":3041.195,"stop":3046.114,"duration":4.92},{"text":"And the Commission said,","start":3046.114,"stop":3046.706,"duration":0.59},{"text":"“Oh!","start":3046.706,"stop":3046.923,"duration":0.22},{"text":"Well we won't do it here either.”","start":3046.923,"stop":3048.581,"duration":1.66},{"text":"We didn't appeal that.","start":3048.581,"stop":3051.043,"duration":2.46},{"text":"I agree that left us with our Skelly remedy, but we won Skelly.","start":3051.043,"stop":3054.433,"duration":3.39},{"text":"The Commission has recognized that and that has changed the law.","start":3054.433,"stop":3068.928,"duration":14.49},{"text":"There are certain of the comments that were made by Mr. Schiff.","start":3068.928,"stop":3077.405,"duration":8.48},{"text":"I can't get to them all.","start":3077.405,"stop":3078.571,"duration":1.17},{"text":"I do want to get to one.","start":3078.571,"stop":3080.546,"duration":1.97},{"text":"He said that one of the purposes of in-line pricing was to prevent rate increase filings.","start":3080.546,"stop":3086.095,"duration":5.55},{"text":"Now, that is just dead wrong.","start":3086.095,"stop":3088.532,"duration":2.44},{"text":"You can't find it anywhere in the opinions, and in fact it's illogical.","start":3088.532,"stop":3092.904,"duration":4.37},{"text":"If an applicant comes in for an 18-cent price, if you'll allow him his 18-cent price, and that's all he has the contract for, obviously, he can't file up under this Court's mobile doctrine.","start":3092.904,"stop":3104.389,"duration":11.49},{"text":"If you cut him back and that's what CATCO was talking about, cutting back to the in-line level, certainly, he then has a contract right to file up.","start":3104.389,"stop":3113.095,"duration":8.71},{"text":"But it seems a very strange thing to say that you're preventing a rate increase filing by giving the producer everything that he would get out of a rating for his filing right at the outset.","start":3113.095,"stop":3125.735,"duration":12.64},{"text":"I have -- I'm afraid I spent more time than I intended on need issue and I think I will reserve the rest of my time for rebuttal.","start":3125.735,"stop":3132.227,"duration":6.49},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3132.227,"stop":3132.963,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You may.","start":3132.963,"stop":3139.423,"duration":6.46},{"text":"Mr. Tell.","start":3139.423,"stop":3141.243,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3141.243,"stop":3144.497,"duration":3.25},{"text":"My name is William Tell.","start":3144.497,"stop":3146.352,"duration":1.86},{"text":"I'm counsel for Texaco.","start":3146.352,"stop":3148.605,"duration":2.25},{"text":"I am appearing this morning on behalf of the 12 producer respondents who have filed a joint brief in Number 60, 61, 62, Number 80 and 97.","start":3148.605,"stop":3161.281,"duration":12.68},{"text":"We are respondents from the appeal taken from the Tenth Circuit's decision at a case which is sometimes referred to as the Amerada case, sometimes the Sunray case.","start":3161.281,"stop":3172.774,"duration":11.49},{"text":"The lead docket was Amerada and the proceedings before the Commission; it was Sunray and the Tenth Circuit that's the reason for the varying nomenclature.","start":3172.774,"stop":3182.542,"duration":9.77},{"text":"I will be followed by four other producer counsels.","start":3182.542,"stop":3187.695,"duration":5.15},{"text":"My presentation will be directed solely to the question of the appropriate in-line price for Texas District 4, for the period subsequent to the issuance of the Commission statement of General Policy in September 1960.","start":3187.695,"stop":3202.737,"duration":15.04}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask if you can identify that as your brief?","start":3202.737,"stop":3205.145,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that is my brief, Mr. Justice Black.","start":3205.145,"stop":3208.354,"duration":3.21},{"text":"Mr. Johnson following me will appear on behalf of certain producers who are parties in the appeals from the District of Columbia Circuit's decisions in Sinclair and Hawkins.","start":3208.354,"stop":3220.662,"duration":12.31},{"text":"He will be followed by Mr. Killbourne who is presenting an individual argument on behalf of the Superior Oil Company with respect to the appeal from the District of Columbia Circuit decision in Sinclair and Hawkins.","start":3220.662,"stop":3233.971,"duration":13.31},{"text":"Following Mr. Killbourne will be Mr. Caskin, who is appearing on behalf of the same 12 producer respondents that I am from the Tenth Circuit's opinion in Amerada and Sunray.","start":3233.971,"stop":3247.015,"duration":13.04},{"text":"Mr. Caskin will discuss the question of refunds under the temporary certificates.","start":3247.015,"stop":3253.017,"duration":6},{"text":"That issue appears only in the Tenth Circuit decision.","start":3253.017,"stop":3256.083,"duration":3.07},{"text":"It is not present in the District of Columbia opinion in Sinclair and Hawkins.","start":3256.083,"stop":3260.53,"duration":4.45},{"text":"Following Mr. Caskin will be Mr. Justin Wolf appearing on behalf of the Standard Oil Company of Texas.","start":3260.53,"stop":3266.409,"duration":5.88},{"text":"Mr. Wolf will also direct himself to the question of the propriety of the Commission's ordering of retroactive refunds under the unconditioned temporary certificates that were issued in District 4.","start":3266.409,"stop":3280.38,"duration":13.97},{"text":"If I may, I will turn at this time to the question of the initial price in the Amerada or Sunray cases.","start":3280.38,"stop":3289.355,"duration":8.97},{"text":"As previous counsel have pointed out to you the doctrine of in-line pricing had it's genesis in this Court's CATCO decision rendered in 1959.","start":3289.355,"stop":3300.056,"duration":10.7},{"text":"At that time the Court was faced with a situation particularly on the Southern Louisiana area but not necessarily confined thereto where as a result of the rapid growth and demand for natural gas, there had been an increase in the field price of that product.","start":3300.056,"stop":3317.854,"duration":17.8},{"text":"As it rose from a waste product to a product that had premium value and became an equal partner with crude oil in the end markets.","start":3317.854,"stop":3329.724,"duration":11.87},{"text":"During the period subsequent to the Phillips decision in 1954 when the Commission was told it had jurisdiction over independent producer rates, there was, as a result of this accelerated growth and demand for natural gas, an increase in fuel price levels.","start":3329.724,"stop":3349.283,"duration":19.56},{"text":"The Commission at that time faced with a difficult problem of attempting to determine and develop standards for the regulation of independent producers.","start":3349.283,"stop":3358.021,"duration":8.74},{"text":"As a practical matter, it was not able with the limited staff that it had to pay as much scrutiny, as this Court felt was required to the initial prices that it was certificating under Section 7.","start":3358.021,"stop":3370.946,"duration":12.92},{"text":"The Commission's position at that time was that it would do the best job it could in Section 7 proceedings but would hold until the Section 5 rate investigations, the final determination of just and reasonable rate.","start":3370.946,"stop":3384.771,"duration":13.83},{"text":"In CATCO, this Court directed the Commission to give more scrutiny to the initial price lines.","start":3384.771,"stop":3391.866,"duration":7.09},{"text":"And it remanded a Commission decision which had certificated new producer sales in Southern Louisiana that had established a new price plateau.","start":3391.866,"stop":3403.443,"duration":11.58},{"text":"I submit that upon reading the Court's decision in CATCO, the vice which the Commission -- which the Court found in the Commission's decision was the failure to make fundings upon the record in that case that justified the reason why it was in the public convenience and necessity to approve a new, and at that time, the highest price plateau that had been proposed for that particular pricing area, Southern Louisiana.","start":3403.443,"stop":3436.132,"duration":32.69},{"text":"The Court in its opinion instructed the Commission to hold the line.","start":3436.132,"stop":3442.142,"duration":6.01},{"text":"It did not attempt to spell out any précised formula as to what techniques should be used to hold the line, what was meant by the line, how the line should be found.","start":3442.142,"stop":3456.296,"duration":14.15},{"text":"Within the context of the Court's opinion in CATCO, it would appear that the reference to the line was a reference to the existing level of contract prices in the field at that time.","start":3456.296,"stop":3470.65,"duration":14.35},{"text":"On remand in CATCO, the Commission attempted to implement this Court's directive to hold the line.","start":3470.65,"stop":3477.434,"duration":6.78},{"text":"And it developed a methodology which has subsequently been referred to as in-liners or in-line pricing.","start":3477.434,"stop":3485.824,"duration":8.39},{"text":"This Court first had before it, a review of the Commission's in-line methodology in the Callery case.","start":3485.824,"stop":3494.79,"duration":8.97},{"text":"Unfortunately, the producer respondents in Callery, did not fully briefed the question of the Commission's in-line methodology because the Fifth Circuit had held that the Commission had erred in confining its consideration to in-line evidence, and that broader evidence representations were required.","start":3494.79,"stop":3519.312,"duration":24.52},{"text":"Although the Court's majority opinion did approve the Commission's 20-cent in-line price established in Callery, 47 Louisiana.","start":3519.312,"stop":3529.91,"duration":10.6},{"text":"Mr. Justice Harlan's opinion clearly recognized that the in-line methodology had not been fully developed in Callery, and suggested that the matter would not be foreclosed for further consideration in subsequent cases.","start":3529.91,"stop":3546.159,"duration":16.25},{"text":"Now, we have a situation where the Commission in its review of the price line in Texas Railroad District 4 for the period after September 28th, 1960, the date on which it issued its statement of initial policy, concluded that changed circumstances and current conditions required an increase in its original in-line price established for a period in the 1950s from 15 to 16 cents.","start":3546.159,"stop":3579.904,"duration":33.74},{"text":"I think it is important to recognize in evaluating whether or not the Commission may have erred in concluding the changed circumstances required an increase in the price line.","start":3579.904,"stop":3590.739,"duration":10.84},{"text":"To recognize that when these proceedings were started in 1961 and '62, that it was apparent that there would be a period of a substantial number of years before we would have just and reasonable rates finally established in the Texas Gulf Coast.","start":3590.739,"stop":3610.669,"duration":19.93},{"text":"As a matter of fact, I think that that prognosis has been shown to be correct by the passage of time.","start":3610.669,"stop":3618.995,"duration":8.33},{"text":"We do not as of this date even have the examiners decision recommending just and reasonable rates in the Texas Gulf Coast, although the hearings have been completed.","start":3618.995,"stop":3629.258,"duration":10.26},{"text":"And I think it would be fair to anticipate that at least an examiner's decision would be rendered shortly, possibly a Commission's decision within a year or year-and-a-half from now.","start":3629.258,"stop":3639.887,"duration":10.63},{"text":"But it's certainly fair to say that the in-line price established by the Commission in the Sunray and Amerada proceeding was the price for the decade of the 1960s in the Texas Gulf Coast.","start":3639.887,"stop":3652.316,"duration":12.43},{"text":"That was the price that was going to determine the extent to which interstate pipeline purchasers would be able to effectively compete for new gas supplies from the Texas Gulf Coast.","start":3652.316,"stop":3663.462,"duration":11.15},{"text":"It was well known to the Commission the evidence that had been brought to its attention in many proceedings that the Texas Gulf Coast is one of the most rapidly expanding industrial markets in the country.","start":3663.462,"stop":3676.518,"duration":13.06},{"text":"That it is a giant consumer of intrastate gas for the petrol chemical complexes and other industrial components in the Texas Gulf Coast area.","start":3676.518,"stop":3689.047,"duration":12.53},{"text":"In 1958, approximately two thirds of the new sales made in the Texas Gulf Coast were two interstate pipeline purchasers.","start":3689.047,"stop":3699.388,"duration":10.34},{"text":"By 1961, that volume had dropped to only 50%.","start":3699.388,"stop":3705.164,"duration":5.78},{"text":"And today it is far below that figure.","start":3705.164,"stop":3708.292,"duration":3.13},{"text":"We have been faced with a situation in the Texas Gulf Coast, for a number of years where the new purchasers by the interstate pipelines has been less than their withdrawals.","start":3708.292,"stop":3719.95,"duration":11.66},{"text":"In other words, they are liquidating their present committed reserve inventory in the Texas Gulf Coast Area.","start":3719.95,"stop":3727.283,"duration":7.33},{"text":"These were the circumstances --","start":3727.283,"stop":3728.749,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you say interstate?","start":3728.749,"stop":3730.796,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The interstate pipeline.","start":3730.796,"stop":3732.46,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Not intra?","start":3732.46,"stop":3734.099,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":3734.099,"stop":3734.86,"duration":0.76},{"text":"The interstate pipelines have been unable to acquire new reserved editions equal to their withdrawals in the Texas Gulf Coast.","start":3734.86,"stop":3744.135,"duration":9.28},{"text":"They are liquidating their inventory of committed reserves.","start":3744.135,"stop":3748.442,"duration":4.31},{"text":"We submit that under those circumstances it was clearly appropriate for the Commission not to feel placed in a straitjacket and bound to perpetuate a 15-cent in-line price that it had found for the 1950's and project that into the decade of the 1960's.","start":3748.442,"stop":3765.584,"duration":17.14},{"text":"CATCO just clearly cannot be read to say that the Commission as a matter of law was required to hold the line for an indefinite period into the future regardless of any changes in circumstances that might come to the Commission's attention.","start":3765.584,"stop":3784.094,"duration":18.51},{"text":"Since CATCO, the various circuits and the Commission itself has recognized, that in applying the in-line standard, consideration must be given to current conditions in the industry and changed circumstances.","start":3784.094,"stop":3799.789,"duration":15.7},{"text":"Now, within the context of this case, what were those changed circumstances, what evidence do the Commission look to, to justify its judgment, that change circumstances required an increase in its 1950's price line?","start":3799.789,"stop":3815.215,"duration":15.43},{"text":"The producers, when this hearing was first set, came forward with evidentiary presentation that was 400 pages in length including exhibits.","start":3815.215,"stop":3825.519,"duration":10.3},{"text":"We were conscious of the problems that this Court had recognized and directed the Commission to adopt more streamline procedures to move these producer cases along.","start":3825.519,"stop":3837.242,"duration":11.72},{"text":"Our evidentiary presentation here was not that the individual company cost of service presentation that so dominated the producer evidence that was presented in Callery.","start":3837.242,"stop":3853.713,"duration":16.47},{"text":"There may have been one or two producers who proffered individual company cost to service evidence.","start":3853.713,"stop":3861.467,"duration":7.75},{"text":"But the main producer group came forward with what we considered to be a streamline evidentiary presentation that would show to this Commission graphically what were these changed circumstances.","start":3861.467,"stop":3873.322,"duration":11.86},{"text":"All of the evidence was excluded on motion by the distributors and the Commission staff.","start":3873.322,"stop":3878.644,"duration":5.32},{"text":"They claimed it was irrelevant.","start":3878.644,"stop":3880.598,"duration":1.95},{"text":"We have pending in this Court a conditional cross petition in Number 82 which has not been acted upon, which request this Court to grant certiorari.","start":3880.598,"stop":3894.856,"duration":14.26},{"text":"In the event it concludes that the evidence that Commission did use to justify its increase in price from 15 to 16 cents was inadequate and not substantial.","start":3894.856,"stop":3907.811,"duration":12.95},{"text":"What the distributors have done is put the Commission in a complete vice.","start":3907.811,"stop":3911.857,"duration":4.05},{"text":"They have successfully obtained the exclusion of all of the generalized cost trend and economic evidence, supply and demand consideration evidence that the producer has brought forward.","start":3911.857,"stop":3923.808,"duration":11.95},{"text":"They have confined the evidence of record to a limited area.","start":3923.808,"stop":3929.002,"duration":5.19},{"text":"And now they claim that the Commission's reliance upon the remaining evidence was inadequate that it -- the evidence that's left wasn't substantial enough to support their result.","start":3929.002,"stop":3940.226,"duration":11.22},{"text":"There go less perpetuate the price freeze at 15 cents.","start":3940.226,"stop":3944.965,"duration":4.74},{"text":"Now, the Commission attempted to respond to the difficult position that it was placed in.","start":3944.965,"stop":3951.313,"duration":6.35},{"text":"It wanted to move these cases as long as quickly as it could.","start":3951.313,"stop":3955.76,"duration":4.45},{"text":"Therefore, it rounded the distributor motions, excluded the producer presentations, and relied rather instead upon a price exhibit that was submitted by its staff which did show the trends in contracting patterns in the Texas Gulf Coast during the period from 1955 to 1962.","start":3955.76,"stop":3978.81,"duration":23.05},{"text":"It also looked to its initial price levels that had been approved under temporary certificates and gave consideration to the price levels which it had established in a statement of general policy, which was the product of Commission expertise and based upon six or seven years of experience in handling producer matters since 1954.","start":3978.81,"stop":4003.315,"duration":24.51},{"text":"It concluded on the basis of that evidence that there definitely had been change circumstances in the market.","start":4003.315,"stop":4010.529,"duration":7.21},{"text":"And that an increase in the price from 15 to 16 cents was clearly required by the public convenience and necessity.","start":4010.529,"stop":4019.79,"duration":9.26},{"text":"Now, we submit that what the Commission has done was proper and lawful.","start":4019.79,"stop":4026.444,"duration":6.65},{"text":"That although it may have been more desirable to make a more detailed analysis into these underlying economic trends and changed circumstances which were shown by the evidence that we proffered, that nevertheless certainly a general feeling for the industry problems and developments could be found from the type of evidence which did remain in the record in which the Commission utilized.","start":4026.444,"stop":4053.121,"duration":26.68},{"text":"We do say, however, that if you are unwilling to accept the quality of the evidence which the Commission utilized in this proceeding in supporting its initial price determination, then you cannot leave this agency in the type of straitjacket that is inherent from the distributor position.","start":4053.121,"stop":4071.723,"duration":18.6},{"text":"But you must then, we respectfully submit, grant our conditional cross petition in Number 82 and permit the Commission to enlarge the record to receive the more detailed evidence which we proffered which clearly would have supported and justified the pricing decisions which the Commission reached in this case.","start":4071.723,"stop":4093.323,"duration":21.6},{"text":"I would --","start":4093.323,"stop":4093.692,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Did this area rate proceeding started in the Texas Gulf Coast?","start":4093.692,"stop":4097.569,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Mr. Justice White, the Commission started in area rate proceeding in the Texas Gulf Coast in 1963.","start":4097.569,"stop":4106.988,"duration":9.42},{"text":"The --","start":4106.988,"stop":4107.138,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But it has not been concluded.","start":4107.138,"stop":4108.785,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The hearing has been concluded.","start":4108.785,"stop":4110.514,"duration":1.73},{"text":"Briefs have been filed before the presiding examiner.","start":4110.514,"stop":4113.267,"duration":2.75},{"text":"He has not yet rendered his initial decision.","start":4113.267,"stop":4116.696,"duration":3.43},{"text":"We expect it very shortly.","start":4116.696,"stop":4120.321,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, with those prices above -- what is exactly -- what was the in-line price that he had just --","start":4120.321,"stop":4128.738,"duration":8.42}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"16 cents.","start":4128.738,"stop":4131.711,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, there would be refunds I suppose if the fair and reasonable price is that in the area of proceeding is below the in-line price.","start":4131.711,"stop":4144.618,"duration":12.91}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice White we, first of all, do not contest that there would be refunds due for amounts that have been collected after 1964 under the Court's stay or Commission's stay, I should say.","start":4144.618,"stop":4159.345,"duration":14.73},{"text":"We're talking here about a prospective period.","start":4159.345,"stop":4160.326,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But if the in-line happens to be above -- be above 16, there's nothing to do about the interim?","start":4160.326,"stop":4169.483,"duration":9.16}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commission's rate investigations under Section 4 or 5 deal prospectively.","start":4169.483,"stop":4177.08,"duration":7.6},{"text":"There would not be retroactive adjustments.","start":4177.08,"stop":4179.759,"duration":2.68},{"text":"I might say, however, that one can only speculate as to whether or not the final just and reasonable rate will be greater or lesser than the in-line price.","start":4179.759,"stop":4190.39,"duration":10.63},{"text":"We know in the Permian Basin area, that the new gas rate was higher than the policy statement guideline.","start":4190.39,"stop":4196.866,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well did the -- did the permission limit your ability under this permanent certificate to file increase rates?","start":4196.866,"stop":4204.198,"duration":7.33}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They did above a level of 18 cents.","start":4204.198,"stop":4208.468,"duration":4.27},{"text":"They found that as a matter of fact, that it would take a price higher than 18 cents to have an adverse effect upon the general pricing structure in the area.","start":4208.468,"stop":4216.137,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think that the -- you could go up immediately to 18 cents assuming your contracts permitted you to do so?","start":4216.137,"stop":4225.042,"duration":8.91}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There could have been an alternative approach, Mr. Justice White, but let me show you why that was not an adequate remedy.","start":4225.042,"stop":4232.242,"duration":7.2},{"text":"We are accepting the 16-cent determination although before the Commission on the lower court, we contended that it should have been higher.","start":4232.242,"stop":4240.467,"duration":8.22},{"text":"But certainly we say that the record of evidence was adequate to support 16 cents.","start":4240.467,"stop":4245.548,"duration":5.08}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But even for 15, you could file -- you could make filings to take up to 18?","start":4245.548,"stop":4250.74,"duration":5.19}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We could prospectively but since --","start":4250.74,"stop":4252.496,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- was that the reason?","start":4252.496,"stop":4253.395,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- 1964 we have been making deliveries under the Commission's permanent certificates at 16 cents.","start":4253.395,"stop":4260.107,"duration":6.71},{"text":"We couldn't have made filings from 15 to 16 cents between 1964 and 1968.","start":4260.107,"stop":4266.853,"duration":6.75},{"text":"That would have been exercising redundancy because we already had a filed rated of 16 cents.","start":4266.853,"stop":4272.211,"duration":5.36},{"text":"And yet if you hold for the distributors now and say it should be 15 cents before the mechanism is an adequate protection, there's no way we could retroactively recoup the difference for the past four years.","start":4272.211,"stop":4285.297,"duration":13.09},{"text":"It's just -- it's just not an adequate mechanism.","start":4285.297,"stop":4289.056,"duration":3.76},{"text":"I think it might also be significant to note that the Commission staff rate recommendations in the area rate proceeding for this area.","start":4289.056,"stop":4297.974,"duration":8.92},{"text":"And in the Permian Basin the Commission staff rate recommendations were substantially lower than what the Commission itself approved.","start":4297.974,"stop":4304.646,"duration":6.67},{"text":"The Commission staff recommendations, for 70% of the gas that is involved in these two consolidated cases would be between 16-4 and 16-8, a level higher than the in-line price which the Commission has established.","start":4304.646,"stop":4317.213,"duration":12.57}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't know why right after this Commission's order, you couldn't have filed an increase rate up to 18 cents?","start":4317.213,"stop":4324.947,"duration":7.73}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We could've file from 16 to 18.","start":4324.947,"stop":4327.336,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And it would have been -- that might have been suspended for a few months but then it would have gone into effect.","start":4327.336,"stop":4332.648,"duration":5.31}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We could have, Mr. Justice White.","start":4332.648,"stop":4334.391,"duration":1.74},{"text":"Our position is that where we have had so much uncertainty that where we're willing to accept the 16 cents.","start":4334.391,"stop":4340.785,"duration":6.39},{"text":"We're not seeking levels higher than 16 cents.","start":4340.785,"stop":4343.432,"duration":2.65},{"text":"We're willing to stand on the Commission's order.","start":4343.432,"stop":4346.026,"duration":2.59},{"text":"We certainly could have filed for more under Section 4 (e).","start":4346.026,"stop":4350.54,"duration":4.51},{"text":"Our concern is, how are we going to keep the penny between 15 and 16 cents?","start":4350.54,"stop":4355.854,"duration":5.31},{"text":"The Commission gave it to us.","start":4355.854,"stop":4357.847,"duration":1.99},{"text":"If it's remanded now and later found to be something more, we could never get it back.","start":4357.847,"stop":4362.17,"duration":4.32},{"text":"There's no retroactive mechanism for that.","start":4362.17,"stop":4365.439,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Are the main differences between the producers and the distributors to consumers, the two questions which you have raised in this brief which you were talking about then?","start":4365.439,"stop":4377.54,"duration":12.1}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Basically, there are three issues in the consolidated cases before you.","start":4377.54,"stop":4381.624,"duration":4.08},{"text":"There are two raised in our brief.","start":4381.624,"stop":4383.734,"duration":2.11},{"text":"One is the appropriate initial price.","start":4383.734,"stop":4386.241,"duration":2.51},{"text":"Second is -- 15.","start":4386.241,"stop":4388.821,"duration":2.58},{"text":"The second is whether or not there should be retroactive refunds under the unconditioned temporary certificate.","start":4388.821,"stop":4395.641,"duration":6.82},{"text":"The third issue is not present in my case.","start":4395.641,"stop":4398.561,"duration":2.92},{"text":"It is present in the D.C. Circuit opinion and that is the need issue that Mr. Simons addressed himself to.","start":4398.561,"stop":4404.554,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Those are the three issues?","start":4404.554,"stop":4405.67,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Those are the three issues before the Court today.","start":4405.67,"stop":4407.584,"duration":1.91},{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":4407.584,"stop":4418.004,"duration":10.42},{"text":"Now --","start":4418.004,"stop":4418.114,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You have on your rate the findings of the Commission.","start":4418.114,"stop":4422.315,"duration":4.2},{"text":"You have on your 16 cent rate, the findings of the Commission on your side?","start":4422.315,"stop":4426.22,"duration":3.91}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":4426.22,"stop":4427.198,"duration":0.98},{"text":"Now, Mr. Justice Black, we are here before the Court aligned with the Commission on the initial price issue.","start":4427.198,"stop":4433.691,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you have on the refund?","start":4433.691,"stop":4437.211,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"On the refund issue, the Commission in its February 5th order originally held for the producers.","start":4437.211,"stop":4443.649,"duration":6.44},{"text":"It later reversed itself.","start":4443.649,"stop":4445.331,"duration":1.68},{"text":"And today I regret to say the Commission is aligned with the “seaboard interest” on the refund issue.","start":4445.331,"stop":4452.408,"duration":7.08},{"text":"The Commission is also aligned with us on the need question.","start":4452.408,"stop":4455.833,"duration":3.42},{"text":"We are aligned with the Commission on two of the three issues before the Court this morning.","start":4455.833,"stop":4463.954,"duration":8.12}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The preferences on which they found the 16 cent price?","start":4463.954,"stop":4468.44,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4468.44,"stop":4468.994,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Use of the temporary certificate.","start":4468.994,"stop":4472.409,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Use of the temporary certificates, its policy statement guideline levels and then an examination of trends in the field prices, in the Railroad District during the relevant time period.","start":4472.409,"stop":4483.978,"duration":11.57},{"text":"I want to also say that I think it's important in terms of evaluating what should be done on the initial price issue that as the Commission solicitor told you yesterday, the period of in-line pricing is pretty much water over the dam.","start":4483.978,"stop":4500.132,"duration":16.15},{"text":"We're hopeful that there will be just and reasonable rates established within the next year or so.","start":4500.132,"stop":4504.932,"duration":4.8},{"text":"There are no important policy questions here for the future.","start":4504.932,"stop":4511.154,"duration":6.22},{"text":"A remand of these cases on the initial price issue to start all over again, one of Texaco sales the gas reserves are already depleted, the wells has been -- have been plugged and abandoned.","start":4511.154,"stop":4523.221,"duration":12.07},{"text":"I'm sure that in the case of most of these producer sales the reserves are pretty close to being half depleted.","start":4523.221,"stop":4532.523,"duration":9.3},{"text":"If we have to go back and start all over again for the purpose of trying to set prices for what is basically a lot in period in the past, I submit that that will not be a utilization of the Commission's resources that would be most consistent with the public interest.","start":4532.523,"stop":4553.195,"duration":20.67},{"text":"The Commission and its staff and I think the industry would hope that we could get these just and reasonable rates established and in effect, and have a workable system of regulation that would permit us all to get on about our business.","start":4553.195,"stop":4568.637,"duration":15.44},{"text":"And going back and reopening and attempting to readjust these past retroactive periods, six or eight years ago adjusting rates generating refunds that whether they will ever reach the people that paid the rate differences back in '60 or '61 is highly problematical.","start":4568.637,"stop":4587.398,"duration":18.76},{"text":"It just does not seem to be a satisfactory approach to the problem.","start":4587.398,"stop":4590.617,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does this record show the position taken by the parties in the pending price as fixing permanent rates --","start":4590.617,"stop":4599.911,"duration":9.29}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Black --","start":4599.911,"stop":4600.381,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- by 16 or 15 or what?","start":4600.381,"stop":4603.271,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"By permanent rate you mean just and reasonable rates in the area proceeding?","start":4603.271,"stop":4606.616,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":4606.616,"stop":4607.168,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that is not in the present record Mr. Justice Black.","start":4607.168,"stop":4611.269,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Would our decisions have any affect on that?","start":4611.269,"stop":4615.004,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe that it would.","start":4615.004,"stop":4616.831,"duration":1.83},{"text":"These cases come before you as certificate cases under Section 7 and the permanent rates, the just and reasonable rates are in the rate cases under Section 4 and 5.","start":4616.831,"stop":4630.06,"duration":13.23},{"text":"There, the Commission has agreed to receive and review entirely different types of evidence in these rate cases.","start":4630.06,"stop":4637.753,"duration":7.69}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But the ultimate objective of its finding is the same.","start":4637.753,"stop":4641.677,"duration":3.92},{"text":"What if there is just and reasonable rate?","start":4641.677,"stop":4644.909,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Under Section 5, the rate cases, that would be correct.","start":4644.909,"stop":4648.524,"duration":3.62},{"text":"Under Section 7 we have different statutory language.","start":4648.524,"stop":4651.427,"duration":2.9},{"text":"It may mean the same thing.","start":4651.427,"stop":4653.16,"duration":1.73},{"text":"What is the public convenience and necessity rate is the issue that's before the Court in the certificate procedures.","start":4653.16,"stop":4658.078,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, suppose that means rather different between the two?","start":4658.078,"stop":4664.241,"duration":6.16}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think you have to -- we have an area rates that would be one of the important questions that someday this Court will have to resolve.","start":4664.241,"stop":4673.906,"duration":9.66},{"text":"In new Section 7 proceedings that have been initiated after we have an area rate established, is the area rate automatically the Section 7 rate or will there be perhaps opportunities for the Commission to consider whether a change circumstances may require some revisions there.","start":4673.906,"stop":4689.454,"duration":15.55}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Tell this isn't -- I thought Capital Railroad indicated that just and reasonable rate and public convenience and necessity, there are a lot of different things, isn't it?","start":4689.454,"stop":4701.167,"duration":11.71},{"text":"This is the evidence.","start":4701.167,"stop":4702.25,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, and it might --","start":4702.25,"stop":4703.297,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It really, it's really not too clear that the end results of Section 7 and Section 5 proceeding is the same, isn't it?","start":4703.297,"stop":4712.323,"duration":9.03}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And I hope that I didn't mislead Mr. Justice Black because I think there definitely is a distinction in statutory standard that may lead to two different results.","start":4712.323,"stop":4721.12,"duration":8.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I perhaps misunderstood you.","start":4721.12,"stop":4722.571,"duration":1.45},{"text":"I thought your answer to Mr. Justice Black, they were the same thing.","start":4722.571,"stop":4724.963,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't intend to.","start":4724.963,"stop":4726.755,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that indicate you may have the whole thing up again?","start":4726.755,"stop":4731.987,"duration":5.23}]},{"speakerName":"William K. Tell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's hope the Commission set rates that everybody's happy with it and that won't be necessary.","start":4731.987,"stop":4745.461,"duration":13.47}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Johnson.","start":4745.461,"stop":4746.48,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":4746.48,"stop":4749.304,"duration":2.82},{"text":"My name is Thomas Greene Johnson.","start":4749.304,"stop":4750.965,"duration":1.66},{"text":"I represent Shell Oil Company, the petitioner in case Number 111.","start":4750.965,"stop":4755.091,"duration":4.13},{"text":"And I appear here also on behalf of humble Skelly and the other petitioners in case Number 143.","start":4755.091,"stop":4761.658,"duration":6.57},{"text":"We are aligned with the Commission on two of the three issues involved here.","start":4761.658,"stop":4766.405,"duration":4.75},{"text":"The in-line price which the Commission determined in Railroad Districts 2 and 3, and the Texas Gulf Coast area, we support the Commission's decision.","start":4766.405,"stop":4775.978,"duration":9.57},{"text":"On the need issue, we further support the Commission's decision that the proper place to consider this issue is in a pipeline certificate proceeding and not a producer certificate proceeding.","start":4775.978,"stop":4787.158,"duration":11.18},{"text":"Both of these decisions by the Commission were held beyond abuse of discretion by the District of Columbia Circuit.","start":4787.158,"stop":4793.375,"duration":6.22},{"text":"I would like to address myself first to the in-line issue.","start":4793.375,"stop":4797.445,"duration":4.07},{"text":"And first of all, I would like the Court to direct this attention to the role of the distributor interest in these in-line proceedings.","start":4797.445,"stop":4809.898,"duration":12.45},{"text":"The Commission has discussed at great length the Commission's procedure.","start":4809.898,"stop":4813.967,"duration":4.07},{"text":"The distributors yesterday pointed out the efforts that producers have made to obtain a contract prices.","start":4813.967,"stop":4819.742,"duration":5.78},{"text":"I would request to the Court now direct its attention to the role of the distributors in these cases.","start":4819.742,"stop":4826.958,"duration":7.22},{"text":"First of all, I would like to refer to you, Mr. Justice Harlan's question to Mr. Coleman yesterday.","start":4826.958,"stop":4832.589,"duration":5.63},{"text":"The first of which was, how much money will the distributors receive in refunds?","start":4832.589,"stop":4837.666,"duration":5.08},{"text":"And how much will they pass on to the ultimate consumer?","start":4837.666,"stop":4843.281,"duration":5.61},{"text":"In this connection, Mr. Coleman had pointed out that pipelines are not participants in these proceedings.","start":4843.281,"stop":4850.549,"duration":7.27},{"text":"We disagree with Mr. Coleman's reason for that.","start":4850.549,"stop":4853.832,"duration":3.28},{"text":"But his reason was that the rate increases can be passed along by the pipelines.","start":4853.832,"stop":4860.068,"duration":6.24},{"text":"In our view, the real reason why the pipelines are not here is because, they already have their opportunity when they negotiated the contracts with the producers.","start":4860.068,"stop":4869.543,"duration":9.47},{"text":"And they did not feel on the position to attack those contracts which they themselves negotiated before the Commission.","start":4869.543,"stop":4875.142,"duration":5.6},{"text":"To be that, if I may, I would like to rephrase Mr. Coleman's question and ask why the distributor companies are always such active partners in these proceedings before the Commission on the Courts and if as they contend, they are simply conduits of this line.","start":4875.142,"stop":4890.948,"duration":15.81},{"text":"And it's all passed on to the ultimate consumer.","start":4890.948,"stop":4893.966,"duration":3.02},{"text":"I think the answer is obvious and that answer is that the distributor company to do retain a large amount of the refunds which will be ordered in this case, if the Commission is sustained and larger amounts of refunds, if the distributor position is sustained.","start":4893.966,"stop":4911.231,"duration":17.26}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this shown on the record?","start":4911.231,"stop":4913.321,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Harlan, the record shows this.","start":4913.321,"stop":4917.055,"duration":3.73},{"text":"The Commission undertook in 1962 and 1963 a survey that the distributor companies.","start":4917.055,"stop":4924.438,"duration":7.38},{"text":"And they asked these distributor companies how much refunds they were passing along.","start":4924.438,"stop":4929.078,"duration":4.64},{"text":"This evidence was compiled by a producer witness.","start":4929.078,"stop":4932.963,"duration":3.88},{"text":"And that witness testified that that questionnaire showed that 42% of the refunds received by the distributing companies during the period covered by the Commission's survey which was about -- well, from July 1961 and November 1962, during that period, the distributors retained 42% of the money which they received.","start":4932.963,"stop":4956.837,"duration":23.87},{"text":"Those moneys amounted according to the Commission's record, to $51.9 million.","start":4956.837,"stop":4963.441,"duration":6.6},{"text":"That evidence was excluded by the presiding examiner on the motion of distributing companies.","start":4963.441,"stop":4968.501,"duration":5.06},{"text":"So therefore, it was not before the Commission and unfortunately we have not included there in the joint appendix because our posture here is to support the Commission's decision.","start":4968.501,"stop":4978.408,"duration":9.91},{"text":"Nonetheless, that evidence is in the record I offered proof.","start":4978.408,"stop":4981.613,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you want us to do with it?","start":4981.613,"stop":4984.276,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Fortas, I merely – I'm raising this question in order to point out that the real representative of the consumer in these proceedings is the person that's the -- or the part that the statute has required and represented themselves.","start":4984.276,"stop":5001.074,"duration":16.8},{"text":"And that's the federal partnership.","start":5001.074,"stop":5002.753,"duration":1.68},{"text":"It's not the distributor companies.","start":5002.753,"stop":5004.308,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that would -- that would illegally being shared hard enough.","start":5004.308,"stop":5007.815,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright sir, I like to address myself to that.","start":5007.815,"stop":5013.369,"duration":5.55},{"text":"Aside from the motives of the distributor companies, we would like now to focus on their objectives.","start":5013.369,"stop":5019.402,"duration":6.03},{"text":"And their objective, they have made clear at various points in their briefs but they do not emphasize it in this case.","start":5019.402,"stop":5026.13,"duration":6.73},{"text":"That objective is very simple.","start":5026.13,"stop":5028.209,"duration":2.08},{"text":"The objective is to freeze the price line at the levels that have existed from 1958 to 1960.","start":5028.209,"stop":5035.865,"duration":7.66},{"text":"Now, for some mean, by some means known only to the distributor's interest, they determine that this line should be frozen, somewhere in the area between 14 and 15 cents.","start":5035.865,"stop":5045.95,"duration":10.09},{"text":"They then embark on a program of intervening in all producer certificate cases where the prices exceeded those levels.","start":5045.95,"stop":5055.635,"duration":9.69},{"text":"By this method of intervention, they were able to and by prolonged litigation on these contract prices they were able to place these prices in a suspect category over a long period of time.","start":5055.635,"stop":5069.995,"duration":14.36},{"text":"As a result, the Commission under the rules announced by various circuit courts did not consider these prices when it originally determined the line in these areas.","start":5069.995,"stop":5080.848,"duration":10.85},{"text":"I would like to also point out that during the time that the contracts in these proceedings were made, there were no in-line prices in these areas for any period.","start":5080.848,"stop":5093.035,"duration":12.19},{"text":"These contracts were made in the time period from September 28, 1960 to about the end of 1963.","start":5093.035,"stop":5100.054,"duration":7.02},{"text":"The in-line prices were not determined by the Commission for this same period.","start":5100.054,"stop":5105.527,"duration":5.47},{"text":"For Amerada, the decision came out in August of 1962.","start":5105.527,"stop":5109.925,"duration":4.4},{"text":"For the Hawkins case, the decision in District 3 in the earlier case was decided in March 27, 1963.","start":5109.925,"stop":5121.091,"duration":11.17},{"text":"In District 2, the decision by the Commission covering the earlier of period was in December 9, 1963.","start":5121.091,"stop":5128.022,"duration":6.93},{"text":"In all of the Amerada sales and one of the Hawkins sales and in all but one of the Sinclair sales, there was no in-line price determined by the Commission at the time these sales were made.","start":5128.022,"stop":5141.639,"duration":13.62},{"text":"Yet the distributors continued to intervene in these cases above the level which they had determined, not a Commission determined level.","start":5141.639,"stop":5149.06,"duration":7.42},{"text":"All the industry had to look to was the 18 cent guideline level which the Commission had determined, which the distributors contend cannot be utilized in this case.","start":5149.06,"stop":5160.881,"duration":11.82},{"text":"We have detailed further in our brief the methods which the distributors have followed in attempting to exclude all of the evidences which the Commission could possibly use to find that the price line was higher for the 1960s than it was in the 1950s.","start":5160.881,"stop":5180.695,"duration":19.81},{"text":"I would like to focus now on the question which Mr. Justice White has raised last night and again this morning with reference to the relation between the in-line price which the Commission has determined here in just and reasonable rate.","start":5180.695,"stop":5196.024,"duration":15.33},{"text":"And I believe it is now clear that the in-line price is the level to which refunds will be ordered in this case.","start":5196.024,"stop":5206.293,"duration":10.27},{"text":"And it is the level if it's too high that is if it's above the just and reasonable rate.","start":5206.293,"stop":5213.506,"duration":7.21},{"text":"There would be no way that the producers can retroactively file for this difference correspondingly if in-line price is below the just and reasonable rate.","start":5213.506,"stop":5222.895,"duration":9.39},{"text":"There is no way that refunds can be required for this difference.","start":5222.895,"stop":5226.801,"duration":3.91},{"text":"So really in our view, what the Commission was attempting to do here and they used the terms fair and reasonable.","start":5226.801,"stop":5231.732,"duration":4.93},{"text":"And Mr. Justice Brennan is ultimately correct that these are different sections of the statute.","start":5231.732,"stop":5239.456,"duration":7.72},{"text":"But at least in the Commission's consideration, the standards which they use I think are very closely approached each other to the extent that they can under the limited consideration which the Commission can give the evidence in an in-line proceeding.","start":5239.456,"stop":5254.82,"duration":15.36},{"text":"So I think it's material here to at least consider to the extent that we can whether the in-line price will be above or below the just and reasonable rate.","start":5254.82,"stop":5264.285,"duration":9.47},{"text":"Now Mr. Tell mentioned this briefly in his argument.","start":5264.285,"stop":5268.655,"duration":4.37},{"text":"We do have some guidelines on this.","start":5268.655,"stop":5271.585,"duration":2.93},{"text":"In the Permian case which was argued before this Court last December, one of the findings which the Commission made in that case was the national cost of gas for 1960.","start":5271.585,"stop":5284.145,"duration":12.56},{"text":"Now, of course, the national cost includes the Texas Gulf Coast area here.","start":5284.145,"stop":5288.05,"duration":3.9},{"text":"And that finding was 16.43 cents per Mcf national cost.","start":5288.05,"stop":5294.184,"duration":6.13},{"text":"Now, in the Permian case as Mr. Tell pointed out, the Commission had previously determined an in-line price for that area of the 16 cents.","start":5294.184,"stop":5303.049,"duration":8.86},{"text":"In their price for new gas, in the Permian area, they determined that part level to be 16 1/2 cents, one half cent above the in-line price.","start":5303.049,"stop":5311.642,"duration":8.59},{"text":"Mr. Tell has pointed out that the record is now closed in the Texas Gulf Coast area rate proceeding.","start":5311.642,"stop":5317.182,"duration":5.54},{"text":"And that the Commission staff has recommended a price for new gas and incidentally new gas as defined by the Commission on the Permian case and by the Commission staff in this case as involving all contracts dated after January 1st, 1961.","start":5317.182,"stop":5334.14,"duration":16.96},{"text":"Now, you see there's only three months or two months difference between the dividing line on the policy statement, the definite periods selected for the in-line price, and the dividing line between new and old gas which the Commission has found different rates for in the area rate proceedings.","start":5334.14,"stop":5353.375,"duration":19.23},{"text":"The Commission staff in the Texas Gulf Coast area rate proceeding for gas delivered at a central point which is the predominant method of delivery has recommended that just and reasonable rate of 16.8 cents.","start":5353.375,"stop":5366.702,"duration":13.33},{"text":"And even more significantly a witness for the same -- some of the same distributor companies which are here attacking the in-line price made a recommendation for Texas Railroad District 4 for new gas of 16.25 cents, for Railroad District 2, 16.75 cents, and for Railroad District 3, 17.25 cents.","start":5366.702,"stop":5389.677,"duration":22.97},{"text":"Now, I should add that the cut off date which the distributors recommend is January 1st, 1963 not '61.","start":5389.677,"stop":5398.262,"duration":8.59},{"text":"But if the Commission follows its decision in the Permian case and finds to cut off date for the reasons which they gave in that case to the January 1st, 1961.","start":5398.262,"stop":5409.207,"duration":10.95},{"text":"Even under the distributor recommendations, the in-line price will be below with the just and reasonable rates filed.","start":5409.207,"stop":5419.082,"duration":9.88},{"text":"I would like now to turn to the -- very briefly to point out two things with reference to the use of temporary certificates.","start":5419.082,"stop":5431.661,"duration":12.58},{"text":"First of all, the deliveries are conducted most under these proceedings, under temporary certificates, because of interventions which the distributor companies filed which force contested proceedings, thus required a very lengthy proceeding.","start":5431.661,"stop":5452.262,"duration":20.6},{"text":"And under the circumstances there, the producers there had no alternative but to apply for temporary certificates so they can begin delivering their gas.","start":5452.262,"stop":5461.192,"duration":8.93},{"text":"Secondly, the Commission did not give as I say very clearly their opinion full weight to these temporary certificates.","start":5461.192,"stop":5469.266,"duration":8.07},{"text":"The temporary certificate order does consider the price question to the extent that the Commission can do so at that time under the absence of a record and all of the other situations which exist in the temporary.","start":5469.266,"stop":5481.97,"duration":12.7},{"text":"But they do consider the price question.","start":5481.97,"stop":5484.186,"duration":2.22},{"text":"And they do condition the price down to the guideline levels.","start":5484.186,"stop":5488.215,"duration":4.03},{"text":"Therefore, the Commission thought that they could give some consideration to these temporaries in determining the in-line price.","start":5488.215,"stop":5497.868,"duration":9.65},{"text":"And that's what they did.","start":5497.868,"stop":5498.751,"duration":0.88},{"text":"If they had given full weight to the temporaries, they would have had to found the price line to be higher than that which they did find.","start":5498.751,"stop":5506.329,"duration":7.58},{"text":"Now, we believe that decision is correct.","start":5506.329,"stop":5509.122,"duration":2.79},{"text":"I would like now to turn to the take-or-pay clause.","start":5509.122,"stop":5513.838,"duration":4.72},{"text":"And I believe there's some misunderstanding which may exist which I would like to address myself to.","start":5513.838,"stop":5520.52,"duration":6.68},{"text":"First of all, Mr. Simons stated that the Commission was in error in balancing between the consumer interests, as he terms himself, and the producers.","start":5520.52,"stop":5534.721,"duration":14.2},{"text":"We feel that the balancing which the Commission did here was on the one hand, to determine the weight to be given to the price.","start":5534.721,"stop":5543.91,"duration":9.19},{"text":"In other words they will hold the price down as low as they can but there is one other important consideration and that is, if they force this price too low, they will not be able to obtain a sufficient supply for the consumers.","start":5543.91,"stop":5559.835,"duration":15.93},{"text":"Now, this is just basic economics.","start":5559.835,"stop":5562.252,"duration":2.42},{"text":"It's true in all sections of the economy whether regulated or non-regulated.","start":5562.252,"stop":5567.499,"duration":5.25},{"text":"They have to weigh on the one hand, the supplies which will be brought forth by the price and on the other hand the price to be found.","start":5567.499,"stop":5577.165,"duration":9.67},{"text":"Now, the Commission did consider the supply question in this area.","start":5577.165,"stop":5582.923,"duration":5.76},{"text":"In the Commission's brief to this Court on page 19, the Commission states, “The Commissions essential duty in passing upon the applicant's initial price is to evaluate market conditions.","start":5582.923,"stop":5598.362,"duration":15.44},{"text":"And in this light to a say a reasonable approximation of the fair price for gas.","start":5598.362,"stop":5604.31,"duration":5.95},{"text":"A figure which will presumably elicit continuing supplies for the interstate market yet protect against the danger of excessive and inflationary price proposals by the dominant supplies.”","start":5604.31,"stop":5617.354,"duration":13.04},{"text":"And in the Tenth Circuit's decision in the Sunray case, they referred to this balancing between the supply problem and the price problem.","start":5617.354,"stop":5625.898,"duration":8.54},{"text":"And we submit that that is the function basically of the Federal Power Commission.","start":5625.898,"stop":5631.279,"duration":5.38},{"text":"It's to balances these two issues.","start":5631.279,"stop":5633.088,"duration":1.81},{"text":"Now, let's see what the record shows with reference to supply in the Texas Gulf Coast area --","start":5633.088,"stop":5638.481,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Tenth Circuit, am I right?","start":5638.481,"stop":5640.322,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":5640.322,"stop":5641.155,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That that's the need issue was not raised.","start":5641.155,"stop":5643.934,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, Your Honor.","start":5643.934,"stop":5645.158,"duration":1.22},{"text":"The need issue was not raised in the Amerada case.","start":5645.158,"stop":5647.719,"duration":2.56},{"text":"It was raised by the distributor interest in Districts 2 and 3, the Hawkins and Sinclair Cases in the District of Columbia Circuit Court.","start":5647.719,"stop":5656.072,"duration":8.35}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But why it isn't raised?","start":5656.072,"stop":5658.137,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I don't know why that isn't raised in there.","start":5658.137,"stop":5662.486,"duration":4.35},{"text":"Turning back to the contract to the supply problem, the record does show because the contracts which were entered into during this period.","start":5662.486,"stop":5672.346,"duration":9.86},{"text":"And it shows the volumes which were committed under those contracts.","start":5672.346,"stop":5676.271,"duration":3.93},{"text":"We have a table which is attached to Appendix C to our brief, which shows these volumes which were committed in the interstate commerce.","start":5676.271,"stop":5685.815,"duration":9.54},{"text":"And in District 3, the figures are particularly significant.","start":5685.815,"stop":5689.488,"duration":3.67},{"text":"The new contract volumes in District 3 declined from 33 billion cubic feet per year in 1958 to only 2.7 billion cubic feet in 1963.","start":5689.488,"stop":5702.884,"duration":13.4},{"text":"These new gas reserves committed in Districts 2 and 3 from September 28, 1960 to about the end of 1963 were approximately 1.2 trillion cubic feet.","start":5702.884,"stop":5715.645,"duration":12.76},{"text":"During the same time period, the pipelines in this area withdrew 2.9 trillion cubic feet over twice as much from their existing reserves as they were able to compact for in this supply.","start":5715.645,"stop":5732.134,"duration":16.49},{"text":"We feel that the Commission did consider this in determining that the price line should be where it was.","start":5732.134,"stop":5739.64,"duration":7.51},{"text":"Now, Mr. Simons has raise at some length the take-or-pay problem of the pipeline chemicals.","start":5739.64,"stop":5747.769,"duration":8.13},{"text":"I would like to first focus on that.","start":5747.769,"stop":5750.401,"duration":2.63},{"text":"Now in our view if the take-or-pay problem is a problem, and we deny that it is, it should be -- the emphasis should be in the material facts or the take-or-pay problem existing in the pipelines buying gas in these proceedings and in these areas not in general industry-wide statistics, which is what Mr. Simons quoted to you.","start":5750.401,"stop":5774.174,"duration":23.77},{"text":"Now, I like to give you the figures from the record on the take-or-pay positions of the pipelines in this case.","start":5774.174,"stop":5780.978,"duration":6.8},{"text":"There are five pipelines buying gas from the dockets and Districts 2 and 3.","start":5780.978,"stop":5785.596,"duration":4.62},{"text":"The first one is Tennessee Gas Company.","start":5785.596,"stop":5787.825,"duration":2.23},{"text":"It had a take-or-pay balance as of December 31st, 1963 and this evidence is in the record.","start":5787.825,"stop":5795.419,"duration":7.59},{"text":"$1,322,000m, this compares with an annual throughput of -- in Tennessee system of over 1 trillion cubic feet per year.","start":5795.419,"stop":5807.319,"duration":11.9},{"text":"$1,000.322.00, yes.","start":5807.319,"stop":5811.198,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what do you mean by that?","start":5811.198,"stop":5812.929,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":5812.929,"stop":5813.761,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you mean by that?","start":5813.761,"stop":5814.786,"duration":1.02},{"text":"If that's the amount to pay I have to spend in one year to discharge a take-or-pay obligation?","start":5814.786,"stop":5820.99,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":5820.99,"stop":5822.179,"duration":1.19},{"text":"I think -- let me go into that because I think it's very important.","start":5822.179,"stop":5826.24,"duration":4.06},{"text":"The pipelines have contracts which provide that if they do not take the contract quantity of the gas, they have to pay for it.","start":5826.24,"stop":5835.288,"duration":9.05},{"text":"Now, the figure which I gave you is the total balance, not an annual fee.","start":5835.288,"stop":5839.579,"duration":4.29},{"text":"It's the total balance which Tennessee has for all of its contracts.","start":5839.579,"stop":5845.222,"duration":5.64},{"text":"And I should again emphasize that this balance is not something to take that the Tennessee pipeline and its customers have to pay that the never received any value for it.","start":5845.222,"stop":5857.059,"duration":11.84},{"text":"It is simply like paying rent in advance.","start":5857.059,"stop":5859.989,"duration":2.93},{"text":"The pipeline has the right to make up this gas at no cost to itself in later years.","start":5859.989,"stop":5866.538,"duration":6.55},{"text":"And the Commission --","start":5866.538,"stop":5867.184,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Limited to what?","start":5867.184,"stop":5869.729,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"Limited to certain volumes but the --","start":5869.729,"stop":5872.196,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Time.","start":5872.196,"stop":5873.511,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"Limited in time.","start":5873.511,"stop":5874.845,"duration":1.33},{"text":"And Mr. Justice White, I'm jumping around a little bit here but in response to your question, I would like to point out that the Commission has thoroughly considered the take-or-pay clause in its real making docket R-199.","start":5874.845,"stop":5892.955,"duration":18.11},{"text":"And the certificates in this proceeding were specifically conditioned to that docket.","start":5892.955,"stop":5897.662,"duration":4.71},{"text":"And the Commission found --","start":5897.662,"stop":5898.786,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Are they here?","start":5898.786,"stop":5899.862,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":5899.862,"stop":5900.407,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Argued?","start":5900.407,"stop":5901.127,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":5901.127,"stop":5902.225,"duration":1.1},{"text":"The Commission found in Docket R-199 that it could fully protect the consumer from any forfeiture.","start":5902.225,"stop":5910.342,"duration":8.12},{"text":"And the Commission has repeatedly found and found on the same pages of the annual reports referred to by Mr. Simons that the pipelines have not made any substantial forfeitures of gas under this take-or-pay clause.","start":5910.342,"stop":5924.576,"duration":14.23},{"text":"And the Commission found that if it permitted a minimum of five years for the makeup of the gas under the take-or-pay provision, it would have adequately protected the consumer and the dockets in this proceeding were specifically conditioned to permit such a makeup period where they did it already and most of them did.","start":5924.576,"stop":5943.778,"duration":19.2}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"What year was that Commission decision?","start":5943.778,"stop":5947.087,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commission decision in Docket R-199 came out about a week before the D.C. Circuit decision in this case.","start":5947.087,"stop":5954.739,"duration":7.65},{"text":"And we believe that it's significant that even though the distributors admit that the Commission decided against them in Docket R-199, they did not appeal that decision.","start":5954.739,"stop":5969.539,"duration":14.8},{"text":"And that decision is now final unless it is subject to collateral attack in this case.","start":5969.539,"stop":5973.763,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"How did that affect these dockets?","start":5973.763,"stop":5975.982,"duration":2.22},{"text":"Is it already -- isn't these certificates are already issued?","start":5975.982,"stop":5979.263,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"But the Commission in its order issuing these certificates made it specifically subject to Docket R-199 and its findings in that case, Your Honor.","start":5979.263,"stop":5987.832,"duration":8.57}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you lodge up your -- the rest of those figures --","start":5987.832,"stop":5992.406,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":5992.406,"stop":5993.989,"duration":1.58},{"text":"Natural Gas Pipeline Company had no take-or-pay obligation or whatever.","start":5993.989,"stop":5998.849,"duration":4.86},{"text":"Trunkline Gas Company had no take-or-pay obligation or whatever.","start":5998.849,"stop":6003.106,"duration":4.26},{"text":"Florida Gas Transmission Company had $384,000 in their total system.","start":6003.106,"stop":6009.253,"duration":6.15},{"text":"United Gas Pipeline Company had $19,829,360.","start":6009.253,"stop":6015.524,"duration":6.27},{"text":"Now, that looks like a large figure until it's compared with the annual throughput in United System of 1.3 trillion cubic feet.","start":6015.524,"stop":6025.736,"duration":10.21},{"text":"Now, I don't know what the average price is in United System.","start":6025.736,"stop":6028.81,"duration":3.07},{"text":"But if we assume an average price of 15 cents, that means an annual throughput by United of over a $165 million a year.","start":6028.81,"stop":6037.82,"duration":9.01},{"text":"So it's not a very large figure when the -- when you look at take-or-pay balance of $19 million.","start":6037.82,"stop":6044.289,"duration":6.47},{"text":"Now, we've also looked at the Commission's records and brought these figures up to date.","start":6044.289,"stop":6047.72,"duration":3.43},{"text":"And I'd like to give you those figures, if I may.","start":6047.72,"stop":6050.969,"duration":3.25},{"text":"With reference to Tennessee, the annual take up -- the take-or-pay volumes as of December 31st, 1966 which are the last figures available in the Commission's record was $2,127,742.","start":6050.969,"stop":6065.346,"duration":14.38},{"text":"Natural Gas Pipelines still have none at all, Trunkline still have none at all.","start":6065.346,"stop":6070.152,"duration":4.81},{"text":"Florida Gas Transmission had completely eliminated the balance it had before and showed no balance at all.","start":6070.152,"stop":6076.108,"duration":5.96},{"text":"United Gas Pipeline had reduced their balance by 25% to something over $15 million.","start":6076.108,"stop":6083.03,"duration":6.92},{"text":"So you see this is not a real problem.","start":6083.03,"stop":6085.181,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"These figures that you're giving now are not in this record.","start":6085.181,"stop":6088.819,"duration":3.64}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"The figures for 1966, of course, are obviously not in this record.","start":6088.819,"stop":6092.534,"duration":3.71},{"text":"They are taken from the Form 2 reports filed by the pipelines with the Federal Power Commission which is the same source that Mr. Simons is referring to when he gives the take-or-pay balance figures for the industry.","start":6092.534,"stop":6104.426,"duration":11.89}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I haven't understood precisely what you've meant by the figures here.","start":6104.426,"stop":6108.789,"duration":4.36},{"text":"You're talking about take-or-pay and so did you mean by that that they have not spending contracts for gas, they will not use to the extended $15 million?","start":6108.789,"stop":6122.625,"duration":13.84}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Black, they have paid for gas which they have not received yet.","start":6122.625,"stop":6128.896,"duration":6.27},{"text":"And the yet is the important thing because the pipelines do have the right under their contracts to make up this gas at no cost in subsequent years.","start":6128.896,"stop":6138.846,"duration":9.95},{"text":"And the pipelines have always been able to do this.","start":6138.846,"stop":6141.029,"duration":2.18},{"text":"That's why the Commission found in Docket R-199 that this take-or-pay problem was not a problem to the industry.","start":6141.029,"stop":6148.047,"duration":7.02},{"text":"And that's what the Commission meant when it said that the pipelines normally have to contract to take care of a year when they may not be able to buy it again or another year when they may have a demand which they have not previously anticipated.","start":6148.047,"stop":6162.731,"duration":14.68},{"text":"The pipelines simply cannot under the nature of their operations go out and buy every year all of the gas which they need to replace the supplies which are being consumed together with all the gas they need for growth.","start":6162.731,"stop":6174.803,"duration":12.07},{"text":"It's just not that accurate a projection.","start":6174.803,"stop":6178.948,"duration":4.15},{"text":"The pipelines have to protect themselves.","start":6178.948,"stop":6181.386,"duration":2.44},{"text":"And the Commission realizes this, they continually, as Mr. Schiff pointed out, supervised the pipeline's operations.","start":6181.386,"stop":6189.137,"duration":7.75},{"text":"If the pipelines were out of line on this, the Commission would certainly catch them up.","start":6189.137,"stop":6193.69,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What you are saying in short, as I understand it, whether have agreed to pay this, they may never have to pay.","start":6193.69,"stop":6200.541,"duration":6.85}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":6200.541,"stop":6201.214,"duration":0.67},{"text":"And the com -- yes sir, excuse me.","start":6201.214,"stop":6202.79,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That the Commissions has so found it.","start":6202.79,"stop":6204.844,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, that's correct.","start":6204.844,"stop":6205.929,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commission found they would not have to pay in front of it or --","start":6205.929,"stop":6209.277,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":6209.277,"stop":6210.304,"duration":1.03},{"text":"They don't reach this question because the pipelines continually incur take-or-pay balances on other contracts.","start":6210.304,"stop":6217.821,"duration":7.52},{"text":"And the take-or-pay balances incidentally which I cited to you basically from contracts in South Louisiana.","start":6217.821,"stop":6223.024,"duration":5.2},{"text":"They aren't even contracts in this case.","start":6223.024,"stop":6226.54,"duration":3.52},{"text":"But it's a continuing thing.","start":6226.54,"stop":6228.32,"duration":1.78},{"text":"The pipelines may take more in one contract in South Louisiana than their contract provides for.","start":6228.32,"stop":6234.022,"duration":5.7},{"text":"They incur a small balance in that contract.","start":6234.022,"stop":6237.036,"duration":3.01},{"text":"Then the next year, then may incur a balance over another contract and make this one up.","start":6237.036,"stop":6241.688,"duration":4.65},{"text":"This goes on all the time in the pipeline industry.","start":6241.688,"stop":6244.38,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Are those figures depicted in your briefs?","start":6244.38,"stop":6248.412,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, they are not.","start":6248.412,"stop":6250.497,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":6250.497,"stop":6253.595,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Johnson","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, I'll be happy to lodge them to the Court.","start":6253.595,"stop":6256.952,"duration":3.36},{"text":"I would like to say one thing on the need issue before I close and that is that the producers introduced in these proceedings evidence to show that the need for gas, the supply problem I've been talking about was such that the Commission could certificate their contracts even though they found these contracts to be out of line.","start":6256.952,"stop":6277.872,"duration":20.92},{"text":"This evidence was excluded on the motion of Mr. Simons, the attorney for the distributors.","start":6277.872,"stop":6283.577,"duration":5.7},{"text":"And so the reason why there is not more evidence in this proceeding on the question of need is not because the producers failed to introduce it, it's because it was excluded on distributor mode.","start":6283.577,"stop":6295.595,"duration":12.02},{"text":"Thank you very much, Your Honor.","start":6295.595,"stop":6301.155,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Killbourne.","start":6301.155,"stop":6304.814,"duration":3.66}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":6304.814,"stop":6307.992,"duration":3.18},{"text":"I am William Killbourne, the counsel for the Superior Oil Company, petitioner Number 231.","start":6307.992,"stop":6313.619,"duration":5.63},{"text":"Superior is the only party to these consolidated proceedings that has thought to review on the price findings of the Commission as well as the Court position below, due to a 15-minute time restriction, I shall limit my comments to two areas dealing with the construction of the initial in-line price for the period 1958 to 1960.","start":6313.619,"stop":6334.933,"duration":21.31},{"text":"I refer you to a full discussion of Superior's position on our initial brief in reply briefs filed previously with this Court.","start":6334.933,"stop":6342.707,"duration":7.77},{"text":"The Commission Opinion 475 concluded that the proper initial certificate price for producer applicants in Texas Railroad Commission District Number 3 for the period prior September 28, 1960 was 16 cents per Mcf.","start":6342.707,"stop":6357.116,"duration":14.41},{"text":"Superior challenges this conclusion and the findings there under for the reason that the Commission refused to consider all the record evidence.","start":6357.116,"stop":6365.098,"duration":7.98},{"text":"Specifically, the Superior's protest is the Commission's refusal to include all high volume, non-suspect permanent certificates and a computation of the average weighted price used by this Commission to ultimately determine the in-line price for such period","start":6365.098,"stop":6379.595,"duration":14.5},{"text":"This Court's CATCO decision in 1959 helped delay of the Commission in determining the just and reasonable rates required a most careful scrutiny of initial price proposals of the producers under Section 7.","start":6379.595,"stop":6392.387,"duration":12.79},{"text":"This Commission has since developed the in-line price technique to meet this duty under the Natural Gas Act.","start":6392.387,"stop":6398.531,"duration":6.14},{"text":"The Ninth Circuit is now famous as UGI Case on which the Commission so heavily relies considered the in-line price technique to be a simple, direct, and effective device on which to determine the in-line price.","start":6398.531,"stop":6414.902,"duration":16.37},{"text":"Callery said the proper and only evidence necessary to establish a price line can allow a proper evaluation of all factors bearing on the public convenience and necessity was a field price study.","start":6414.902,"stop":6426.625,"duration":11.72},{"text":"This Court in Callery held that adequate consumer protection under Section 7 was attained through the utilization of the in-line price technique and the related suspect price doctrine.","start":6426.625,"stop":6439.165,"duration":12.54},{"text":"This Court in Callery approved a certification of applications of the highest price level after elimination of suspect prices.","start":6439.165,"stop":6447.128,"duration":7.96},{"text":"Prices tainted by the erroneously issued and remanded CATCO certificates were set aside.","start":6447.128,"stop":6452.981,"duration":5.85},{"text":"Only prices then subject to Court and Commission review as well as like prices in the same area not currently under review will regard as suspect.","start":6452.981,"stop":6462.388,"duration":9.41},{"text":"The general concept of the suspect price doctrine that is prices still subject to Commission in Court review was urged by the Commission and approved by this Court in Callery.","start":6462.388,"stop":6471.857,"duration":9.47},{"text":"And it is now urged in the Commission's initial brief in this proceeding.","start":6471.857,"stop":6475.808,"duration":3.95},{"text":"It is a distorted application of the suspect price doctrine that causes the Commission to commit legal error in the record below and not the definition of the doctrine.","start":6475.808,"stop":6486.143,"duration":10.34},{"text":"Mr. Justice Harlan concurring in the line determination in Callery, said the in-line price was comparatively easy to fix.","start":6486.143,"stop":6493.563,"duration":7.42},{"text":"His statement is correct but I would submit that if the fixing of the line is done improperly, then the whole purpose of the stock gas measure is blunted.","start":6493.563,"stop":6502.835,"duration":9.27},{"text":"Mr. Justice Harlan also expressed great concern for the use of a crooked measuring rod derived from a too broad application of the suspect price doctrine.","start":6502.835,"stop":6512.465,"duration":9.63},{"text":"That would result in too lower price line.","start":6512.465,"stop":6515.078,"duration":2.61},{"text":"The producer and consumer are permanently injured by the uncertainty and the price instability, the results from unduly low price line.","start":6515.078,"stop":6523.231,"duration":8.15},{"text":"The line determination is an artificial approach.","start":6523.231,"stop":6526.342,"duration":3.11},{"text":"And although mechanically easy to compute, the Commission must make full use of the proper inputs to arrive at a proper place line.","start":6526.342,"stop":6534.995,"duration":8.65},{"text":"The Commission has totally ignored nine final non-suspect 20-cent permanent certificates and six other large volume final non-suspect permanent certificates.","start":6534.995,"stop":6545.334,"duration":10.34},{"text":"The Commission Opinion 475 acknowledged the charismatic impact for this nine 20 cents sales, certificated in 1959 the Trunkline Gas Company.","start":6545.334,"stop":6554.157,"duration":8.82},{"text":"But stated or eliminated from the weighted average price determination because such elimination was consistent with an earlier District 3 certificate proceeding, Texaco Seaboard Opinion 383 to which Superior was not a party and to which no appeal was ever taken.","start":6554.157,"stop":6569.66,"duration":15.5},{"text":"The only reason given by the Commission for eliminating these sales was that six of the nine 20-cent sales would have been set aside on the New York Public Service Commission's petition for review of a Commission ordered denying intervention but for the failure to prefect their appeal.","start":6569.66,"stop":6587.79,"duration":18.13},{"text":"This reading --","start":6587.79,"stop":6589.43,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Killbourne your position is that the in-line price supplied to your client was too low?","start":6589.43,"stop":6597.608,"duration":8.18}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct sir.","start":6597.608,"stop":6598.853,"duration":1.24},{"text":"Both periods.","start":6598.853,"stop":6599.296,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Johnson had proceeded here for Shell and some others, are you still talking about Districts 2 and 3?","start":6599.296,"stop":6607.896,"duration":8.6}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, I'm limiting my argument to which Superior was only a party District 3.","start":6607.896,"stop":6612.129,"duration":4.23},{"text":"Mr. Johnson --","start":6612.129,"stop":6612.214,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"District 3, Mr. Johnson talked about 2 and 3.","start":6612.214,"stop":6615.421,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, that's correct.","start":6615.421,"stop":6616.312,"duration":0.89},{"text":"He's representing clients from both districts.","start":6616.312,"stop":6618.988,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"So that there is a difference of opinion among some of the producers represented here?","start":6618.988,"stop":6626.978,"duration":7.99}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"There were some producers who accepted the in-line price determination of the Commission who never sought any appeal whatsoever.","start":6626.978,"stop":6633.17,"duration":6.19},{"text":"There were some producers who sought review to the District of Columbia Circuit Court.","start":6633.17,"stop":6637.861,"duration":4.69},{"text":"And that accepted --","start":6637.861,"stop":6639.555,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's take District 3.","start":6639.555,"stop":6640.843,"duration":1.29},{"text":"I'm trying to find out what the line up for the day, this ball game is.","start":6640.843,"stop":6647.3,"duration":6.46},{"text":"Let's just take District 3.","start":6647.3,"stop":6649.072,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":6649.072,"stop":6651.296,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"May I correctly assume that Mr. Johnson's position for his clients is that they support the in-line prices?","start":6651.296,"stop":6659.694,"duration":8.4}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"Before this Court support the in-line determination of the Commission --","start":6659.694,"stop":6662.667,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's not for this Court.","start":6662.667,"stop":6665.023,"duration":2.36},{"text":"You for Superior Oil I think is too low.","start":6665.023,"stop":6669.479,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":6669.479,"stop":6674.264,"duration":4.78},{"text":"The fact remains at the Trunkline sales were certificated a 20-cent permanent certificate rate after a full hearing in which producer Hawkins, the Commission staff and 16 interveners including the Michigan Public Service Commission, the state of intended consumption of the gas had fully participated, briefs exceptions to the examiner's decision and applications for rehearing were filed.","start":6674.264,"stop":6699.08,"duration":24.82},{"text":"Oral argument was held before the Commission in a fully considered opinion issuing permanent certificates at 20 cents was issued.","start":6699.08,"stop":6706.86,"duration":7.78},{"text":"Clearly there was no price infirmity resulting from the Commission order.","start":6706.86,"stop":6711.719,"duration":4.86},{"text":"The Public Service Commission filed knows of intervention in that proceeding as provided for in the rules of the Commission.","start":6711.719,"stop":6719.117,"duration":7.4},{"text":"In line with the established Commission policy at that time, the Commission found that a denial of intervention was required because allegations of the would-be intervener, the Public Service Commission, failed to show a direct or immediate interest to justify their intervention as a matter of right.","start":6719.117,"stop":6736.019,"duration":16.9},{"text":"However, in deference to Public Service Commission it was offered the status of a limited participant in the proceeding to show to the examiner that the Public Service Commission had a sufficient interest and that its intervention would be in the public interest.","start":6736.019,"stop":6749.565,"duration":13.55},{"text":"The Public Service Commission elected not to exercise this right of limited participation and made no appearance in the proceeding.","start":6749.565,"stop":6756.841,"duration":7.28},{"text":"Subsequently, an order was issued denying intervention and the Public Service Commission's petition for review with that order denying intervention was dismissed.","start":6756.841,"stop":6765.142,"duration":8.3},{"text":"The failure to perfect the petition for review whether the intervention in hindsight was proper or not is no more failed to the correctness of the Trunkline opinion in the 20-cent certificate therein, then would be the producers fair to brief and argue the in-line issue and the Callery case suggest that the Callery case is wrong.","start":6765.142,"stop":6786.506,"duration":21.36},{"text":"Both decisions must be taken as correct and they have an impact on this proceeding here.","start":6786.506,"stop":6791.536,"duration":5.03},{"text":"The 20-cent sales became final after the judicial review and are taking place to this date.","start":6791.536,"stop":6797.091,"duration":5.56},{"text":"Clearly, they were not erroneously issued.","start":6797.091,"stop":6799.717,"duration":2.63},{"text":"No action has been taken to modify them to any individual Section 5 (a) complaint proceeding, which maybe initiated either by the Commission or by any producer, distributor, or party agreed.","start":6799.717,"stop":6813.109,"duration":13.39}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now.","start":6813.109,"stop":6813.978,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":6813.978,"stop":6819.298,"duration":5.32},{"text":"We were talking before the luncheon break about the Commission action eliminating certain permanent non-suspect certificates.","start":6819.298,"stop":6828.778,"duration":9.48},{"text":"And the method the Commission selected to hold the line is the in-line method approved by this Court in Callery.","start":6828.778,"stop":6835.741,"duration":6.96},{"text":"And the Commission consistently states that the in-line price is derived from a review of only permanent non-suspect certificates when available.","start":6835.741,"stop":6844.482,"duration":8.74},{"text":"Then Superior insists that every comparable permanent certificate, not classified suspect under the suspect price doctrine, be included in that determination.","start":6844.482,"stop":6854.735,"duration":10.25},{"text":"The Commission has selected the method and it is under a legal obligation to apply it consistently.","start":6854.735,"stop":6860.249,"duration":5.51},{"text":"The Commission cannot be allowed to pick and choose among otherwise helpful permanent certificates no longer subject to review in order to find the price line.","start":6860.249,"stop":6869.76,"duration":9.51},{"text":"The error of citing Texaco Seaboard has authority to disregard these sales must not be allowed to result in unduly low price line.","start":6869.76,"stop":6878.935,"duration":9.18},{"text":"Full consideration of these sales raises the average weighted price to 16.92 cents per Mcf.","start":6878.935,"stop":6885.958,"duration":7.02},{"text":"Opinion 475 has done a weight average place for the period involved of 15.16 cents per Mcf.","start":6885.958,"stop":6892.881,"duration":6.92},{"text":"The fixing of the in-line price at the highest level of prices after elimination of property suspect prices were at some level between the weighted average price of 16.92 cents and 20 cents would result in a price line that would justify Superior's sale in this proceeding.","start":6892.881,"stop":6911.222,"duration":18.34},{"text":"The Commission committed further error in refusing to use six permanent certificates issued by the Commission under settlement orders.","start":6911.222,"stop":6919.564,"duration":8.34},{"text":"The prices of these file certificates ranged from 16 to 18 cents per Mcf and would have a clearly upward impact on the average weighted price.","start":6919.564,"stop":6928.36,"duration":8.8},{"text":"The Commission has made an express finding that such certificates resulted from settlements are required by the public interest.","start":6928.36,"stop":6935.66,"duration":7.3},{"text":"The certificates result from proposals or producers concurred in by regulatory bodies, distribution companies, and the Commission to accept amended price levels in order to obtain permanent certificates at firm prices without the usual administrative delay.","start":6935.66,"stop":6950.715,"duration":15.06},{"text":"The purposes that motivated the parties to a settlement are identical with the purposes of the producer in a contested certificate proceeding.","start":6950.715,"stop":6959.439,"duration":8.72},{"text":"Whatever the reasons for seeking a settlement, the obligations of the Commission under the Natural Gas Act are unchanged.","start":6959.439,"stop":6966.716,"duration":7.28},{"text":"It may not, for its own convenience, issue an order that is not in the public interest.","start":6966.716,"stop":6971.947,"duration":5.23},{"text":"Settlement orders specifically find that the prices approved by the Commission are required by the public interest.","start":6971.947,"stop":6978.181,"duration":6.23},{"text":"The permanent certificate is in all respect final and beyond review.","start":6978.181,"stop":6982.592,"duration":4.41},{"text":"Permanent certificates resulting from settlements have never been considered erroneous or suspect.","start":6982.592,"stop":6988.157,"duration":5.57},{"text":"In addition, settlements represent current conditions in the regulated industry.","start":6988.157,"stop":6992.932,"duration":4.77},{"text":"They reflect the consider judgment not only the Commission and the producer, but also the expressed or tacit approval of the distributors and the regulatory state bodies who have actively participated and who were submitted the proposed settlement offered before the Commission issued it's final order.","start":6992.932,"stop":7009.645,"duration":16.71}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it your position that the Commission may not consider anything but permanent certificate pricing?","start":7009.645,"stop":7018.686,"duration":9.04}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"It is the position of the Commission that in-line pricing, where permanent certificates are available to rely exclusively on permanent certificates.","start":7018.686,"stop":7026.673,"duration":7.99}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that your position?","start":7026.673,"stop":7027.532,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"That is my position also.","start":7027.532,"stop":7028.705,"duration":1.17},{"text":"And these are permanent certificates and must be relied on by the Commission and not ignored.","start":7028.705,"stop":7033.142,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes, but you -- but even if we considered all the outstanding permanent certificates, you would say they're also to consider some temporary certificates.","start":7033.142,"stop":7045.511,"duration":12.37}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"Temporary certificates can be looked to determine the current market as they've done in the Callery case in this instance so the --","start":7045.511,"stop":7052.9,"duration":7.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's assume that there are 10 permanent certificates that could give you a price of an 18.","start":7052.9,"stop":7058.407,"duration":5.51},{"text":"And there are some other evidence on what current market prices are that would reduce to 17.","start":7058.407,"stop":7064.518,"duration":6.11},{"text":"You would say it would stick with this --with the permanent certificate?","start":7064.518,"stop":7068.133,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"I would refer you to the Callery case, Mr. Justice White, where in fact --","start":7068.133,"stop":7071.571,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Your position like the distributors here?","start":7071.571,"stop":7074.288,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":7074.288,"stop":7075.29,"duration":1},{"text":"No, I would not say my position is like the consumer at all.","start":7075.29,"stop":7078.075,"duration":2.78},{"text":"I said that permanent certificates are available use them.","start":7078.075,"stop":7081.063,"duration":2.99},{"text":"And then look to the current -- for the current conditions in the market.","start":7081.063,"stop":7084.256,"duration":3.19},{"text":"You may look to the temporary certificates and see if they buttress your determination of the in-line price by using permanent certificates.","start":7084.256,"stop":7090.238,"duration":5.98}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But what if they would lower it?","start":7090.238,"stop":7092.377,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"In the Callery case, they were lowered.","start":7092.377,"stop":7095.144,"duration":2.77},{"text":"And in South Louisiana, they found for successive periods that from 1958, the average weighted price in fact had gone down but nevertheless in their own discretion and this Court proved it found the 20-cent price to continue for the in-line price determination despite the fact that subsequent to 1958 average weight of price determinations resulted in lower weighted prices.","start":7095.144,"stop":7118.343,"duration":23.2}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do you agree or disagree with it?","start":7118.343,"stop":7120.453,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree with the Commission discretion that they feel that the permanent certificates show a change downward nevertheless they may find the line continuous because of skimpy permanent certificates that are available in the post statement period.","start":7120.453,"stop":7132.256,"duration":11.8}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So you disagree with the Court of Appeals --","start":7132.256,"stop":7134.424,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, very much so.","start":7134.424,"stop":7135.582,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What kind of evidence is available?","start":7135.582,"stop":7138.14,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Killbourne","textObjs":[{"text":"Very much so.","start":7138.14,"stop":7138.694,"duration":0.55},{"text":"We made offers approved to show on company wide cost service and what not to try and get in before the Commission and that was denied, and Callery approved that.","start":7138.694,"stop":7148.453,"duration":9.76},{"text":"Very much so we would deny the holdings of the lower court in this case.","start":7148.453,"stop":7156.91,"duration":8.46},{"text":"The law and Commission policy is clear that where there is any objection to a proposed settlement, there is in fact no settlement to consider.","start":7156.91,"stop":7164.439,"duration":7.53},{"text":"The prices reflect what all of these parties believed to be the in-line price at that time.","start":7164.439,"stop":7169.539,"duration":5.1},{"text":"That they've considered such sales in the average weight of price is in error.","start":7169.539,"stop":7174.54,"duration":5},{"text":"The examiner categorized these settlements as other than permanent certificates.","start":7174.54,"stop":7178.722,"duration":4.18},{"text":"The settlements are obviously permanent certificates and worthy of as it is as much weight in the price line review as a contested permanent certificate.","start":7178.722,"stop":7186.547,"duration":7.82},{"text":"Full consideration of these settlement orders raises the average weighted price to 0.63 cents per Mcf above the average weighted price of Opinion 475 below.","start":7186.547,"stop":7197.84,"duration":11.29},{"text":"The full consideration of all non-suspect permanent certificates in Railroad District 3 for the pre-statement period, raises the average weighted prices at 16.95 cents per Mcf.","start":7197.84,"stop":7210.085,"duration":12.24},{"text":"Mr. Justice Fortas and this is my final point, I just want to bring to your attention here, and you ask the question yesterday whether or not, there are no permanent certificates involved in this proceeding.","start":7210.085,"stop":7219.127,"duration":9.04},{"text":"Superior believed they had a permanent certificate.","start":7219.127,"stop":7221.16,"duration":2.03},{"text":"In September of 1960, we're issued an unconditioned permanent certificate at 17.5 cents per Mcf.","start":7221.16,"stop":7230.122,"duration":8.96},{"text":"We held that certificate for over one year and the only condition -- I take it back, there was one small condition and it said that this is conditioned to the acceptance of a permanent certificate by Florida Gas Transmission, the pipeline purchaser.","start":7230.122,"stop":7245.422,"duration":15.3},{"text":"In August of 1961, a permanent certificate was issued and the same time, the Commission came out of an order resending our permanent certificate, at 17.5 cents, gave us an unconditioned temporary certificate at 17.5 cents.","start":7245.422,"stop":7264.016,"duration":18.59},{"text":"So we now look in 1968 to a situation where we find the Commission may file a 16-cent price with refunds, with interests of believing in 1958 that we had a permanent unconditioned certificate.","start":7264.016,"stop":7278.677,"duration":14.66},{"text":"Thank you.","start":7278.677,"stop":7284.095,"duration":5.42}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Caskin.","start":7284.095,"stop":7285.674,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and members of the Court.","start":7285.674,"stop":7288.719,"duration":3.05},{"text":"On behalf of 12 of the producing companies who were respondents in the cases coming here from the Tenth Circuit in the Amerada cases, I will discuss the retroactive refund issue.","start":7288.719,"stop":7302.447,"duration":13.73},{"text":"The Tenth Circuit is held but the Commission lack the power to impose refund liabilities upon amounts previously collected on the temporary certificates which contained no full wanting that refunds would be imposed.","start":7302.447,"stop":7316.467,"duration":14.02},{"text":"As its opinion makes clear, the Tenth Circuit carefully considered the circumstances in which these certificates were issued as well as the terms of the certificates themselves.","start":7316.467,"stop":7327.252,"duration":10.79},{"text":"At the outset, I wish to make clear that the producers recognized that the Commission may impose reasonable conditions at the time of issuance of the temporary certificates.","start":7327.252,"stop":7338.881,"duration":11.63},{"text":"And this Court in Hunt in -- at 376 U.S. has recognized that this power at that time is broad.","start":7338.881,"stop":7347.187,"duration":8.31},{"text":"The Commission often exercises its conditioning power when it issues temporary certificates.","start":7347.187,"stop":7352.889,"duration":5.7},{"text":"It sometimes reduces the initial price proposed.","start":7352.889,"stop":7356.607,"duration":3.72},{"text":"It sometimes imposes expressed refund conditions.","start":7356.607,"stop":7361.067,"duration":4.46},{"text":"Consequently, the absence of an express condition that temporary certificate was highly significant.","start":7361.067,"stop":7368.468,"duration":7.4},{"text":"In this case itself, the Commission exercised its conditioning power at the time of the issuance of the certificates.","start":7368.468,"stop":7375.838,"duration":7.37},{"text":"In one instance, it lowered the price proposed.","start":7375.838,"stop":7379.056,"duration":3.22},{"text":"In several other instances, it imposed the expressed refund conditions.","start":7379.056,"stop":7386.359,"duration":7.3},{"text":"This case, however, presents to the Court for the first time, whether the Commission is empowered to modify the terms of lawful temporary certificate orders, issued without refund condition by imposing refund conditions at a later point in time when a retroactive basis long after the producer has irrevocably dedicated his gas to the interstate market.","start":7386.359,"stop":7411.792,"duration":25.43},{"text":"A temporary certificate orders in this case not only lack their refund condition.","start":7411.792,"stop":7417.008,"duration":5.22},{"text":"Indeed the Commission affirmatively stated that the prices authorized were firm prices subject only to prospective modification at the time of permanent certification.","start":7417.008,"stop":7430.617,"duration":13.61},{"text":"Now, the temporary certificates in question must be considered in conjunction with the Commission statement of General Policy No. 61-1.","start":7430.617,"stop":7440.433,"duration":9.82},{"text":"This became effective on September 28, 1960.","start":7440.433,"stop":7443.877,"duration":3.44},{"text":"It established great standards for various producing areas in the United States, and in particular established price ceilings at or below which the Commission would issue temporary certificates or permanent certificates in the absence of innovation without a price condition.","start":7443.877,"stop":7463.567,"duration":19.69},{"text":"These price ceilings as evidenced by the Commission's Policy Statement were based upon comprehensive data and made available to the Commission as a result of six years of producer regulation.","start":7463.567,"stop":7477.58,"duration":14.01},{"text":"In its 1963 Phillip's decision at 373 U.S., this Court gave recognition to the significant role which the Policy Statement ceilings had had in maintaining and in some instances, reducing the upward trend of producer prices.","start":7477.58,"stop":7502.312,"duration":24.73},{"text":"But what I mean, they either maintain the level or reduce them.","start":7502.312,"stop":7507.576,"duration":5.26},{"text":"And the Commission itself wanted to -- wanted to establish this Policy Statement prices found that the prices would promote effective producer regulation and I quote, “in a manner fit to all with these interests are affected by Commission regulation.”","start":7507.576,"stop":7525.483,"duration":17.91},{"text":"There has been some contentions here that the Policy Statements -- the Policy Statement prices were pulled out to fit in.","start":7525.483,"stop":7537.319,"duration":11.84},{"text":"One only has to read the Commission's Policy Statement to see the comprehensive support that it marshaled for those prices.","start":7537.319,"stop":7547.067,"duration":9.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Where did you get those -- where did you get all that information, in an adversary proceeding?","start":7547.067,"stop":7553.846,"duration":6.78}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"In some cases, it did, Your Honor.","start":7553.846,"stop":7556.483,"duration":2.64},{"text":"It gathered out many of the individual cost cases that had been instituted by the Commission against producers following this Court's Phillips decision in 1954.","start":7556.483,"stop":7573.333,"duration":16.85},{"text":"It also had previously issued permanent certificates in these various areas.","start":7573.333,"stop":7579.599,"duration":6.27},{"text":"It looked to that.","start":7579.599,"stop":7583.582,"duration":3.98},{"text":"I must say that we were stymied in this case.","start":7583.582,"stop":7586.929,"duration":3.35},{"text":"We attempted to get to the bottom of this but we were excluded from testing the basis.","start":7586.929,"stop":7595.001,"duration":8.07},{"text":"However, the Commission by its own words, use the very comprehensive support for these Policy Statement pricing.","start":7595.001,"stop":7605.268,"duration":10.27},{"text":"I should also point out --","start":7605.268,"stop":7606.618,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"There was no hearing?","start":7606.618,"stop":7608.328,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"There was no hearing.","start":7608.328,"stop":7609.743,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Consumers never had an opportunity to be heard?","start":7609.743,"stop":7612.754,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the consumers were clearly given a notice that they have the opportunity to be heard because the Commission here --","start":7612.754,"stop":7619.862,"duration":7.11}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Any hearing?","start":7619.862,"stop":7621.956,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":7621.956,"stop":7622.468,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Any hearing?","start":7622.468,"stop":7623.89,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, the Commission said that they were establishing these prices as the guide for initial action by it.","start":7623.89,"stop":7634.225,"duration":10.34},{"text":"And as Mr. Schiff said yesterday, this would be reflected in temporary certificates.","start":7634.225,"stop":7640.988,"duration":6.76},{"text":"Now, this was a fully published statement and in the Federal Register, and I believe that the producers, I mean the distributors will put on clear notice that the Commission would implement its Policy Statement by the issuance of temporary certificate.","start":7640.988,"stop":7660.657,"duration":19.67},{"text":"And there's no doubt in my mind that temporary certificate always is judicially reviewable.","start":7660.657,"stop":7669.084,"duration":8.43},{"text":"Now --","start":7669.084,"stop":7671.311,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that contested in anyway here?","start":7671.311,"stop":7674.886,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"That they are judicially reviewable?","start":7674.886,"stop":7676.326,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":7676.326,"stop":7677.398,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"It is contested, Your Honor, to the extent that Mr. Coleman has suggested that this is a right without a remedy but what he does is rely on District of Columbia Circuits Mcdermott case which I think really took a very limited view to the scope of review of temporary certificates.","start":7677.398,"stop":7705.503,"duration":28.1},{"text":"And by comparison, I would point to the Seventh Circuit's review of temporary cer -- temporary certificates in the Pure case of 292 F. 2d, and the Tenth Circuit's review of temporary certificates in the Sohio case at 298 F. 2d.","start":7705.503,"stop":7726.341,"duration":20.84},{"text":"And there the Court really went into the question of whether or not temporary certificates based upon the Policy Statement, that is conditioned at or below the Policy Statement level were problem in the sense or in regard to whether or not the Policy Statement reflected the in-line price in the particular area and in those -- in both of those cases the courts found that the Policy Statement level was actually lower than the in-line price.","start":7726.341,"stop":7764.4,"duration":38.06},{"text":"That it has been --","start":7764.4,"stop":7765.349,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Has the Commission ever held any hearings on any temporary certificates?","start":7765.349,"stop":7772.285,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, the Act provides that they would be -- they are not issued without notice of hearing.","start":7772.285,"stop":7779.691,"duration":7.41},{"text":"The --","start":7779.691,"stop":7779.863,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"How did it happen?","start":7779.863,"stop":7780.847,"duration":0.98},{"text":"Why then do you say that the consumers were put on notice by this going in to the Federal Register so that they could have had their hearing?","start":7780.847,"stop":7790.698,"duration":9.85}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well as Mr. Schiff indicated yesterday and I think the distributors have from time to time considered this.","start":7790.698,"stop":7798.244,"duration":7.55},{"text":"The Commission indicated that they would use these policy statements as the basis for initial action in the issuance of temporary certificates.","start":7798.244,"stop":7809.431,"duration":11.19},{"text":"They didn't say so in so many words but that was very clear.","start":7809.431,"stop":7812.997,"duration":3.57},{"text":"And what I am saying is that the distributors who are on a highly sophisticated group were clearly unnoticed that this was going to be implemented.","start":7812.997,"stop":7825.872,"duration":12.88},{"text":"The only question then becomes as to the scope of the review of the temporary certificates which I would like to get to --","start":7825.872,"stop":7833.863,"duration":7.99}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What could they have demanded from in the nature of the hearing from or to present their case, the information on that issue?","start":7833.863,"stop":7844.224,"duration":10.36}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":7844.224,"stop":7844.63,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"That time?","start":7844.63,"stop":7847.913,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the Commission could have -- they could have asked for different procedures to be followed.","start":7847.913,"stop":7856.117,"duration":8.2},{"text":"But I think that the Act itself was a guide to the Commission that these temporary certificates which will meet emerging situations and it was necessary that as a consequence, they'd be passed upon without notice of hearing.","start":7856.117,"stop":7873.348,"duration":17.23},{"text":"But I wish to point out that the Commission's action was immaturely considered action.","start":7873.348,"stop":7880.521,"duration":7.17},{"text":"And I believe that the distributor's rights to whatever redress they thought they should have could have been fully protected on judicial review especially after the Commission's issuance of its February 5th order in this case.","start":7880.521,"stop":7898.569,"duration":18.05},{"text":"I'd like to explain the sequence in which these sales or the sequence in which these temporary certificates were issued, the Commission issued its Policy Statement.","start":7898.569,"stop":7912.691,"duration":14.12},{"text":"In District 4 which is the area in question, where the refund issue is, the Commission established a maximum price of 18 cents.","start":7912.691,"stop":7924.897,"duration":12.21},{"text":"Now, each of the contracts were executed subsequent to the Policy Statement and accepted one instance, they were at or below the policy statement level.","start":7924.897,"stop":7936.271,"duration":11.37},{"text":"They range from 15.9 cents to 18 cents.","start":7936.271,"stop":7941.058,"duration":4.79},{"text":"Most of them were in the area of 17 cents.","start":7941.058,"stop":7944.871,"duration":3.81},{"text":"Now, during the hearing, the producers attempted to show the extent of their reliance upon this policy statement.","start":7944.871,"stop":7956.22,"duration":11.35},{"text":"Some of the producers testified that they had ceased negotiations for a higher price in reliance upon what the Commission had said that is unconditional certification at or below the Policy Statement level.","start":7956.22,"stop":7971.002,"duration":14.78},{"text":"Other producers even made clear that they had given up specific intrastate market so we're alternatively available doing in reliance upon unconditional certificates.","start":7971.002,"stop":7983.735,"duration":12.73}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Has there ever been an approval of the rights and charges under these temporary certificates?","start":7983.735,"stop":7992.29,"duration":8.56}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I believe there was by the Commission --","start":7992.29,"stop":7995.84,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"But doesn't the temporary certificate say specifically, expressly and in so many words that the acceptance of a temporary filing is not to be considered as approval of the rates and charges?","start":7995.84,"stop":8010.273,"duration":14.43}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I believe that --","start":8010.273,"stop":8012,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it or it doesn't?","start":8012,"stop":8013.814,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes it does, Your Honor, but I would like to say that those words cannot be read literally in line of what the Commission has said this to the meeting.","start":8013.814,"stop":8023.739,"duration":9.92}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I think I had followed your argument, so that from a one point of view anyway because I'm far from coming to rest on this but from one point of view, it could be said that what we're dealing with here is not analytically a refund but for the first time, the approval of a price under the temporary certificate --","start":8023.739,"stop":8048.76,"duration":25.02}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I would have to confess that.","start":8048.76,"stop":8052.036,"duration":3.28},{"text":"I believe that --","start":8052.036,"stop":8052.888,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, you would.","start":8052.888,"stop":8054.118,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that –-","start":8054.118,"stop":8055.27,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"But what I'm saying is that I think if I'm correct there maybe have some significance that all of the temporary certificates with which we are here concerned did specifically recite that the temporary certification does not constitute approval of any rates and charges.","start":8055.27,"stop":8078.556,"duration":23.29}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":8078.556,"stop":8079.658,"duration":1.1},{"text":"And as a matter of fact, every temporary certificate ever issued by the Commission contains that language.","start":8079.658,"stop":8084.814,"duration":5.16},{"text":"But what I'm saying is, it must be read on the context of what the Commission has said since 1955 on.","start":8084.814,"stop":8091.736,"duration":6.92},{"text":"Mr. Coleman deprecated our citation of the Signal case.","start":8091.736,"stop":8095.749,"duration":4.01},{"text":"I think any reading of it, it appears at 238 F.2d will show that the Commission has not interpreted until this case that without prejudice language in the temporary certificate is a refund condition.","start":8095.749,"stop":8109.829,"duration":14.08},{"text":"And the February 5th order itself, shows that the Commission did not intend it as a refund condition because as I say, should the temporary certificates contained that without prejudice language.","start":8109.829,"stop":8125.424,"duration":15.6},{"text":"I believe, however, that the February 5th order is important in more than that respect.","start":8125.424,"stop":8130.81,"duration":5.39},{"text":"I mean, not only does it make clear that the prices authorized on the temporary certificate were firm prices subject to modification at the time of the permanent certificate.","start":8130.81,"stop":8142.406,"duration":11.6},{"text":"But it also articulates a well-considered Commission policy to grant temporary certificates at firm prices at or below the Policy Statement level while proscribing price increases during the period of temporary certification.","start":8142.406,"stop":8158.548,"duration":16.14},{"text":"Now, the February 5th order which appears in Volume 1 at page 155, and particularly, at page 158, the Commission says as to such temporary authorizations under those conditions, it's about -- about fourth line down, “We have balanced the competing interest of producers and consumers as well as given full consideration to the needs for certainty of the natural gas companies and the public general by providing that while temporarily certificated price is not subject to refund, the period, the price during this interim period cannot exceed our ceiling price.”","start":8158.548,"stop":8209.791,"duration":51.24},{"text":"Now, this as we have shown in our brief, was a policy not limited to this case.","start":8209.791,"stop":8216.45,"duration":6.66},{"text":"It was industry-wide scope.","start":8216.45,"stop":8218.937,"duration":2.49},{"text":"And from the point of view of the Commission, I want to establish initially that this policy was in effect retroactively changed by the Commission.","start":8218.937,"stop":8232.757,"duration":13.82},{"text":"And we believe that your decision in the American Tracking Association case at 358 U.S. condemns this action.","start":8232.757,"stop":8242.553,"duration":9.8},{"text":"The Court while recognizing that an agency may rectify inadvertent errors in prior decisions observed that an agency cannot make such retroactive changes merely to establish a new policy on a retroactive basis.","start":8242.553,"stop":8264.376,"duration":21.82},{"text":"Now, Mr. Coleman contends that this policy never existed.","start":8264.376,"stop":8269.289,"duration":4.91},{"text":"That is of issuing temporary certificates at or below the Policy Statement level or proscribing price increases during the temporary certification period.","start":8269.289,"stop":8278.545,"duration":9.26},{"text":"It's interesting to note that Mr. Schiff represents the Commission here never denied that.","start":8278.545,"stop":8285.671,"duration":7.13},{"text":"All that Mr. Coleman could muster for his support was an order in CATCO on remand issued in January '62.","start":8285.671,"stop":8296.329,"duration":10.66},{"text":"But as this order makes clear and I'm afraid it must be read quite clearly because the Commission really mischaracterized what it was doing there but what it was doing there was imposing refund liabilities upon temporary certifi -- a temporary certificate which contained an expressed refund condition.","start":8296.329,"stop":8319.809,"duration":23.48},{"text":"And we do not contest that in that situation, the power to order refunds exist.","start":8319.809,"stop":8330.058,"duration":10.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What would you do now?","start":8330.058,"stop":8330.938,"duration":0.88},{"text":"Are you defending entirely on the issue retroactivity?","start":8330.938,"stop":8338.047,"duration":7.11}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Not entirely, Your Honor.","start":8338.047,"stop":8340.1,"duration":2.05},{"text":"We're also saying –-","start":8340.1,"stop":8340.742,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Supposing it wasn't, as you call it retroactive, would you contest their power to order refund?","start":8340.742,"stop":8350.209,"duration":9.47}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"I contest their power to change a rate that has been filed and accepted without refund.","start":8350.209,"stop":8359.754,"duration":9.55}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you claim -- do you claim whatever rate they say that in fact, changes their evidence?","start":8359.754,"stop":8367.941,"duration":8.19}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"I would have to concede that they can change it prospectively.","start":8367.941,"stop":8372.987,"duration":5.05},{"text":"And this is what explicitly they refuse to do in the February 5th order.","start":8372.987,"stop":8376.843,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What you claim here is that whatever manner by the in-line price?","start":8376.843,"stop":8380.831,"duration":3.99},{"text":"They read on these certificates, temporary certificates.","start":8380.831,"stop":8385.647,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, that they were not bound --","start":8385.647,"stop":8387.278,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"They are bound until that's changed by some new order --","start":8387.278,"stop":8393.658,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"That is --","start":8393.658,"stop":8393.848,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"They cannot prospectively, retroactively, change that amount in that certificate.","start":8393.848,"stop":8401.45,"duration":7.6}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, Your Honor.","start":8401.45,"stop":8402.537,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the basis of your argument?","start":8402.537,"stop":8404.049,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, and it -- it ties in with the other aspect of the question that not only was this a well-articulated Commission policy that produce these unconditioned temporary certificates but the distributors themselves had the opportunity to contest it.","start":8404.049,"stop":8422.582,"duration":18.53},{"text":"And as I say, their idea of what the scope of review of a temporary certificate order is -- is -- is limited in my judgment.","start":8422.582,"stop":8434.138,"duration":11.56},{"text":"And as a matter of fact, when they cite the McDermott case in 32 -- at 327 F.2d, they failed to recognize that there was not a question there before the Court of a determination by the Commission, that a temporary certificate was explicitly not subject to refund.","start":8434.138,"stop":8458.953,"duration":24.81}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose they reach the conclusion that the temporary rate was confiscatory?","start":8458.953,"stop":8466.045,"duration":7.09}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"That the producers –-","start":8466.045,"stop":8467.938,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That a temporary rate was confiscatory, could they have remedy there on the permanent -- on the temporary certificates?","start":8467.938,"stop":8478.324,"duration":10.39}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I think it would be rather difficult to do it except prospectively.","start":8478.324,"stop":8486.677,"duration":8.35},{"text":"I think that we certainly as producers could come in and seek prospective relief but --","start":8486.677,"stop":8500.161,"duration":13.48}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you mean by prospective relief?","start":8500.161,"stop":8501.819,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, relief from and after the day that the Commission acted.","start":8501.819,"stop":8505.164,"duration":3.35},{"text":"I --","start":8505.164,"stop":8506.423,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That would relate retroactively, would it not?","start":8506.423,"stop":8509.751,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe so, Your Honor.","start":8509.751,"stop":8510.922,"duration":1.17},{"text":"I think that the Commission lacks a reparation power.","start":8510.922,"stop":8515.471,"duration":4.55},{"text":"And that under Section 5 of the Act, its action would be prospective only so that -- but we have of course raised a -- such questions.","start":8515.471,"stop":8528.648,"duration":13.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well no.","start":8528.648,"stop":8529.337,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"What we --","start":8529.337,"stop":8530.708,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- because that's not here but I was wondering if you meant that it was fixed and inflexible this temporary rate even though it was confiscatory.","start":8530.708,"stop":8540.929,"duration":10.22}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say that it was fixed until from the point of view that producers, we sought relief from confiscation if that was a question, and that the action on a requested relief would be of prospective effect.","start":8540.929,"stop":8560.587,"duration":19.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"If they had a policy, a general policy that all the producers relied upon, what was the standard guiding the Commission in determining that in some of these certificates, temporary certificates, they provided for refunds and some, they did not?","start":8560.587,"stop":8582.105,"duration":21.52}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, this requires going into the voice of the Commission and I really couldn't say except that they were exercising their discretionary authority to attach conditions at the time of issuance of the temporary certificates.","start":8582.105,"stop":8598.939,"duration":16.83}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Or if they have the power to fix the policy that everybody was controlled by, how would they have the right to pick and choose between these various companies or producers?","start":8598.939,"stop":8614.019,"duration":15.08}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I think that always that, peculiar circumstances have to be taken into account.","start":8614.019,"stop":8621.725,"duration":7.71},{"text":"And there is one temporary certificate in this case where the refund condition was imposed with a floor of 12 cents which obviously related to the fact that the producer was acquiring the properties from someone else.","start":8621.725,"stop":8641.276,"duration":19.55},{"text":"I think what the Commission was saying very clearly was, that in the case of new certificate applications controlling contracts or governing contracts under certif -- under con -- governing contracts issued after the Policy Statement.","start":8641.276,"stop":8659.123,"duration":17.85},{"text":"They would permit unconditional certification without refund condition provided that the producer was proscribed from filing price increases during the period of temporary certification.","start":8659.123,"stop":8675.676,"duration":16.55},{"text":"Now I --","start":8675.676,"stop":8675.772,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they say that?","start":8675.772,"stop":8676.986,"duration":1.21},{"text":"They say that?","start":8676.986,"stop":8678.053,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well yes sir.","start":8678.053,"stop":8678.97,"duration":0.92},{"text":"They said that in the February 5th order.","start":8678.97,"stop":8682.564,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well if they did, no, no, you're just taking your time.","start":8682.564,"stop":8684.759,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":8684.759,"stop":8685.563,"duration":0.8},{"text":"They said that at page 158 of Volume 1 of the record.","start":8685.563,"stop":8692.828,"duration":7.26},{"text":"Now, the Commission presently takes the position that its February 5th order didn't mean what it said.","start":8692.828,"stop":8703.525,"duration":10.7},{"text":"What it says is that the February 5th order was a refusal to imposed and expressed refund condition.","start":8703.525,"stop":8711.586,"duration":8.06},{"text":"The implication being that there was already an implicit refund condition.","start":8711.586,"stop":8717.317,"duration":5.73},{"text":"But this is truly incomprehensible in light with the plain words of the February 5th order, itself.","start":8717.317,"stop":8724.044,"duration":6.73},{"text":"And it only shows to me that it's a form of post hoc rationalization to cover a change in policy applied retroactively.","start":8724.044,"stop":8735.656,"duration":11.61}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What is that February 5th order?","start":8735.656,"stop":8735.881,"duration":0.22},{"text":"Is it cited here?","start":8735.881,"stop":8737.652,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"The February 5th order?","start":8737.652,"stop":8738.961,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":8738.961,"stop":8739.576,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":8739.576,"stop":8740.216,"duration":0.64},{"text":"It appears that page 155 of Volume 1 of the appendix.","start":8740.216,"stop":8748.751,"duration":8.53},{"text":"And it goes on to several pages Mr. Justice.","start":8748.751,"stop":8757.141,"duration":8.39},{"text":"Now, as a part of its argument, the temporary certificates --","start":8757.141,"stop":8762.751,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon.","start":8762.751,"stop":8763.814,"duration":1.06},{"text":"In your judgment, does a Commission have the power to issue an authorization to a producer, without approving the price, without any approved price.","start":8763.814,"stop":8783.209,"duration":19.4}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it's my position that they have to approve the price at -- at least a certain price.","start":8783.209,"stop":8793.168,"duration":9.96}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I thought and the fact of the matter is if you take -- go back to the temporary authorizations themselves they have not approved the price.","start":8793.168,"stop":8805.4,"duration":12.23},{"text":"And then you get all these stashing back and forth as it seems to be on the part of the Commission but you come back to the proposition that there has not been an approved price under this temporary authorization.","start":8805.4,"stop":8823.634,"duration":18.23},{"text":"What then affects and it's arguable therefore that what they're in effect doing now in addition to fixing a prospective price is to fix a price that would be applicable to the sales under these temporary certificates.","start":8823.634,"stop":8842.424,"duration":18.79},{"text":"I don't know whether that squares with the Commission's idea of a statute, what they're doing or not.","start":8842.424,"stop":8849.834,"duration":7.41},{"text":"I am impressed with your argument about this February 5 order particularly what is said on page 157 of the record.","start":8849.834,"stop":8863.046,"duration":13.21},{"text":"But to look at this thing from the point of view of a refund, you do have a February 5th order statements by the Commission which seemed clearly to indicate they don't think that they doubt that they've got the power to do it.","start":8863.046,"stop":8878.038,"duration":14.99},{"text":"And if they did they have the power to do it, that they thought this would be kind of short practice.","start":8878.038,"stop":8883.951,"duration":5.91}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I believe that --","start":8883.951,"stop":8887.278,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"But on the other hand that if you --","start":8887.278,"stop":8888.043,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"They thought they had the power.","start":8888.043,"stop":8890.112,"duration":2.07},{"text":"I believe they have the power.","start":8890.112,"stop":8892.229,"duration":2.12},{"text":"And the distributors were unnoticed.","start":8892.229,"stop":8895.786,"duration":3.56},{"text":"And if they want to assert --","start":8895.786,"stop":8897.64,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you believe they have the power to do what?","start":8897.64,"stop":8899.7,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"The power to issue temporary certificate what are (Voice Overlap).","start":8899.7,"stop":8901.876,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Without approving the price.","start":8901.876,"stop":8905.988,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, what I am saying is that they --","start":8905.988,"stop":8909.167,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I'm asking you though.","start":8909.167,"stop":8911.259,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Do they have the power to -- I say not unless they put a floor in it.","start":8911.259,"stop":8917.057,"duration":5.8},{"text":"They often issue temporary certificates for the refund conditions based upon an explicit price floor.","start":8917.057,"stop":8924.007,"duration":6.95},{"text":"And this is in clear accord with what they have done since 1959 following the Tenth Circuit Sunray Mid-Continent decision in 270 F.2d.","start":8924.007,"stop":8935.184,"duration":11.18},{"text":"So I say they have the power to issue a temporary certificate without approving the total price but they do not have the power to merely hold in advance what the price maybe contingent upon permanent certification.","start":8935.184,"stop":8955,"duration":19.82}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well they do it in some cases.","start":8955,"stop":8957.053,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, this was the first case that they've done it in.","start":8957.053,"stop":8963.162,"duration":6.11},{"text":"This is the first time that they have success -- not successfully, but have attempted to read without prejudice language as an absolute lack of approval of the rate accepted for filing of the temporary certification period.","start":8963.162,"stop":8982.893,"duration":19.73}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean that they might have approved as far as power is concerned the expressed provision and there shall be no refund with respect to this right.","start":8982.893,"stop":8989.505,"duration":6.61},{"text":"They could have gone that far.","start":8989.505,"stop":8994.528,"duration":5.02}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":8994.528,"stop":8995.138,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And in fact you're saying that's really what they did.","start":8995.138,"stop":8997.838,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"Francis H. Caskin","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I'm saying they did.","start":8997.838,"stop":8999.018,"duration":1.18},{"text":"That's what I'm saying they said they did witness the February 5th order.","start":8999.018,"stop":9006.242,"duration":7.22},{"text":"Your Honor, I would like to cover one question finally because it's before this Court and that is the question of the Commission's exercise of the refund power which we of course, concede or refuse to concede exist, I urge that the Court, the further view of that question at this time.","start":9006.242,"stop":9030.649,"duration":24.41},{"text":"When the Commission actually imposed the refund liabilities by its Opinion 501, the threshold question of whether it possessed the power was then pending before the Tenth Circuit.","start":9030.649,"stop":9041.216,"duration":10.57},{"text":"And by the time that the 11 petitions to review Opinion 501 were before the Tenth Circuit, that Court decided in Sunray DX that the Commission lacked power.","start":9041.216,"stop":9053.632,"duration":12.42},{"text":"And based upon a motion for summary disposition of the second series of appeals, the Tenth Circuit set aside Opinion 501 in light of its Sunray DX case.","start":9053.632,"stop":9064.454,"duration":10.82},{"text":"I wish to note that the Tenth Circuit had nothing before except a mere listing of the record and the allegations concerning the exercise of the power had not even been briefed.","start":9064.454,"stop":9080.01,"duration":15.56},{"text":"And for this reason, among others, as stated in our briefs, particularly our reply brief, I would respectfully urge this Court to let the Tenth Circuit decide this exercise of the power questions in the first instance.","start":9080.01,"stop":9095.464,"duration":15.45}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Wolf.","start":9095.464,"stop":9100.552,"duration":5.09}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":9100.552,"stop":9103.76,"duration":3.21},{"text":"I appear here today on behalf of the Standard Oil Company of Texas who is the main respondent in Number 80.","start":9103.76,"stop":9112.066,"duration":8.31},{"text":"We concern ourselves and address ourselves solely to the question of refunds.","start":9112.066,"stop":9118.972,"duration":6.91},{"text":"I think it is clear at least we argue that when the Commission issued a temporary certificate to Standard fixing and prescribing a temporary rate of 18 cents, and this was done in Standard's case after the guideline Policy Statement had been issued.","start":9118.972,"stop":9143.927,"duration":24.95},{"text":"And it was a temporary certificate which prescribed an 18-cent rate that cause Standard to reduce rates it had contracted to receive.","start":9143.927,"stop":9155.698,"duration":11.77},{"text":"The Commission was acting at that time in a legislative or a quasi-legislative capacity.","start":9155.698,"stop":9165.378,"duration":9.68},{"text":"Its action bounds Standard for the future until that action was changed.","start":9165.378,"stop":9173.225,"duration":7.85},{"text":"If the rate thus prescribed was by its terms that is by the quasi-legislative after the Commission at that time, made subject to refund, then we do not argue that a later refund ordered by the Commission would be improper or invalid.","start":9173.225,"stop":9194.209,"duration":20.98},{"text":"And I think that this is exactly what my friend, Mr. Coleman, and my friend Mr. Schiff are arguing.","start":9194.209,"stop":9200.894,"duration":6.68},{"text":"They are saying that the so-called “without prejudice language” in Standard's temporary certificates in effect said, that the temporary rate was to be 18 cents until a hearing on final certificate at which time when the Commission prescribed an in-line price a refund from the 18-cent rate would have to be paid down to the rate fixed as the in-line price.","start":9200.894,"stop":9230.064,"duration":29.17},{"text":"Now, one of Standard's temporary certificates particularly the one appearing in the joint appendix at pages 108 and 109 says, “This is without prejudice to such final determination of the application for the certificate as the record may require.”","start":9230.064,"stop":9254.999,"duration":24.93},{"text":"The other temporary that Standard received provides, and this is at the Joint Appendix 100, 101, “This authorization and the acceptance of the above rate schedule are without prejudice to such final disposition of the application for certificate as the record may require.”","start":9254.999,"stop":9274.883,"duration":19.88},{"text":"So the issue becomes how does one reads it without prejudice language.","start":9274.883,"stop":9280.508,"duration":5.63},{"text":"That question, Mr. Justice Fortas which I think you recently addressed yourself.","start":9280.508,"stop":9284.97,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you for that.","start":9284.97,"stop":9286.099,"duration":1.13},{"text":"Would you look at page 72 of Volume 1 of the joint appendix?","start":9286.099,"stop":9289.426,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon sir.","start":9289.426,"stop":9290.996,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 72.","start":9290.996,"stop":9292.483,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":9292.483,"stop":9293.397,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's say a temporary certification isn't it, for -- to the Sunray Oil Company?","start":9293.397,"stop":9301.474,"duration":8.08}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a temporary certification to the Sunray Oil Company, yes sir, in Docket CI 61, 657.","start":9301.474,"stop":9307.632,"duration":6.16}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"And on page 72, there is a sentence in the second paragraph, it says, this acceptance per filing shall not be construed as constituting approval of any rate charged classification etcetera --","start":9307.632,"stop":9323.294,"duration":15.66}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":9323.294,"stop":9323.392,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- obtained in the filing.","start":9323.392,"stop":9325.732,"duration":2.34},{"text":"And then I look at the Standard of Texas temporary certificates towards to just direct our attention.","start":9325.732,"stop":9337.043,"duration":11.31},{"text":"Those don't' have that provision and --","start":9337.043,"stop":9339.066,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"It is correct sir.","start":9339.066,"stop":9340.443,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Why is that?","start":9340.443,"stop":9341.247,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not know, sir.","start":9341.247,"stop":9342.944,"duration":1.7},{"text":"I suspect -- I suspect that it is a choice of language which the drafter of the temporary certificate may have used but significantly I suggest you that the language makes no difference.","start":9342.944,"stop":9357.912,"duration":14.97}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's what I wanted to ask you.","start":9357.912,"stop":9360.461,"duration":2.55},{"text":"That is do you contend but the temporary certification which your client received does constitute an approval in any degree of the rates?","start":9360.461,"stop":9376.881,"duration":16.42}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"I contend that the temporary certificate that was issued to my client prescribed that 18-cent rate until it could and would be changed prospectively.","start":9376.881,"stop":9387.678,"duration":10.8},{"text":"I challenge the Commission's authority to change it retroactively.","start":9387.678,"stop":9391.436,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"You have to be a little more blunt for me.","start":9391.436,"stop":9394.153,"duration":2.72},{"text":"Do you or do you not regard it as an approval of the rate until it changes?","start":9394.153,"stop":9399.148,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":9399.148,"stop":9399.909,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"You do?","start":9399.909,"stop":9400.531,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":9400.531,"stop":9401.146,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"But then that the situation would be different than the case of your client than it would be in the case of Sun Oil under the temporary certificate to which I directed your attention.","start":9401.146,"stop":9413.178,"duration":12.03}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, respectfully sir.","start":9413.178,"stop":9414.921,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well how can you say that the Sun Oil temporary certification is in approval of the rate when it says it's not?","start":9414.921,"stop":9424.069,"duration":9.15}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commission in its order of February 5th, 1963 has specifically unequipped stated exactly what it meant in temporary --","start":9424.069,"stop":9433.913,"duration":9.84}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Sometimes it says -- let's assume and I think it's right that February 5 order says we won't order -- we won't add a refund condition.","start":9433.913,"stop":9444.062,"duration":10.15}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":9444.062,"stop":9444.766,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's still isn't right on the button because I -- you have to leave out an important word, that little word not in the Sun Oil certification to reach your result and you have to say you're leaving it out because of some other things outside of the temporary certification itself and that's what you're arguing.","start":9444.766,"stop":9469.339,"duration":24.57},{"text":"That's what --","start":9469.339,"stop":9471.408,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"I regret that I do not appear to becoming too clear to you as I hope I would.","start":9471.408,"stop":9475.728,"duration":4.32},{"text":"What I am trying to say is irrespective of the language used in the respective temporaries, and particularly in the light of what the Commission said with regard to the language that it did use in its February 5 order.","start":9475.728,"stop":9490.884,"duration":15.16},{"text":"The Commission has made it quite clear that it did not intend to.","start":9490.884,"stop":9496.104,"duration":5.22},{"text":"It would not order refunds --","start":9496.104,"stop":9499.645,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":9499.645,"stop":9499.915,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"-- retroactively reduced the rates prescribed by the ordering of refund.","start":9499.915,"stop":9503.646,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"A few possible positions.","start":9503.646,"stop":9505.443,"duration":1.8},{"text":"One that temporary certification did approve the rate.","start":9505.443,"stop":9509.294,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":9509.294,"stop":9509.58,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Two, that the -- despite the fact that the temporary certification said that it did not.","start":9509.58,"stop":9514.898,"duration":5.32},{"text":"Two, that the temporary certification did not approve the rates and nothing subsequently changed that.","start":9514.898,"stop":9521.482,"duration":6.58},{"text":"The -- three, that approval of the rates was not necessary and that the Commission's February 5 statement that it would not order refunds as governs and is binding on the Commission.","start":9521.482,"stop":9534.418,"duration":12.94}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that latter you said, yes, yes Mr. Justice Fortas, is correct.","start":9534.418,"stop":9538.881,"duration":4.46},{"text":"And the significance of the argument that Standard of Texas wishes to present to you, is that what we are saying is clearly and wholly inline with the decisions that had been articulated by this Court.","start":9538.881,"stop":9555.448,"duration":16.57},{"text":"In Arizona Grocery, in 284 U.S., you said, that a quasi-legislative body and that is just the ICC could not retroactively repeal its own enactment.","start":9555.448,"stop":9569.76,"duration":14.31},{"text":"And we agree with that.","start":9569.76,"stop":9571.826,"duration":2.07},{"text":"We say that what the Commission is attempted to do in its Opinion 501 is retroactively to repeal its whole enactment.","start":9571.826,"stop":9578.051,"duration":6.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What you're saying here is the correct analysis, it's not of approval or disapproval of a rate rather this is in effect a legislative specification of a rate which may not be changed except prospectively because otherwise, it would be something ex post facto in nature, is that it?","start":9578.051,"stop":9597.844,"duration":19.79}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly, Your Honor, you have phrased it better than I.","start":9597.844,"stop":9600.814,"duration":2.97},{"text":"In fact, I should quit at that point.","start":9600.814,"stop":9604.131,"duration":3.32},{"text":"And as a matter of fact, I think I will.","start":9604.131,"stop":9608.328,"duration":4.2},{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor.","start":9608.328,"stop":9610.997,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I ask you just one question.","start":9610.997,"stop":9614.074,"duration":3.08},{"text":"This is the last one on your side, isn't it?","start":9614.074,"stop":9618.012,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":9618.012,"stop":9619.997,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Does any part of your objection to the refund order here go to saying that the in-line rate is not a proper measure of the refund if the refund is what we had but that the refund obligations should be measured by what ultimately is forthcoming in the area rate proceedings about fair and reasonable rates?","start":9619.997,"stop":9642.752,"duration":22.76}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not so argue with that Justice White, nor do I understand that that argu -- that the argument which you have just articulated has been set forth in any of the other briefs.","start":9642.752,"stop":9651.755,"duration":9}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So that the in-line rate is set by the Commission if there is to be a refund.","start":9651.755,"stop":9656.53,"duration":4.78},{"text":"You concede that it's a fair measure of what the refund should be.","start":9656.53,"stop":9660.039,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"If there is to be a refund and I sincerely trust there will not be because it would be retroactive rate measure.","start":9660.039,"stop":9664.978,"duration":4.94},{"text":"And the measure is the measure which the Commission has prescribed, the difference between the rates prescribed in the temporary certificate on the in-line.","start":9664.978,"stop":9673.263,"duration":8.29}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Does your argument necessarily mean that Callery was really wrong insofar as they decided a refund?","start":9673.263,"stop":9683.767,"duration":10.5}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't think that --","start":9683.767,"stop":9685.422,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"On Callery though, here's a Commission that in the -- in a Section 7 of the proceeding sets a rate.","start":9685.422,"stop":9692.866,"duration":7.44},{"text":"It determines a rate.","start":9692.866,"stop":9694.447,"duration":1.58},{"text":"And that company goes ahead and charges that rate.","start":9694.447,"stop":9698.459,"duration":4.01},{"text":"And it just so happens the rate isn't final.","start":9698.459,"stop":9702.59,"duration":4.13},{"text":"But the Commission has said it is, that the rate isn't final and gets reversed on appeal.","start":9702.59,"stop":9710.211,"duration":7.62},{"text":"And if there's a refund there, isn't the -- the Commission may order a refund.","start":9710.211,"stop":9714.958,"duration":4.75},{"text":"In fact, it has to, is that right?","start":9714.958,"stop":9716.126,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"In the circumstances of Callery, they did exactly what you say, Mr. Justice White.","start":9716.126,"stop":9720.131,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well now only --","start":9720.131,"stop":9721.384,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"But after the non-final permanent certificates had been vacated by this Court's decision in CATCO.","start":9721.384,"stop":9730.407,"duration":9.02}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I know but it seems to me that you haven't touch time with that case and that suggests that the temporary certificate which sets a rate is a less -- is a more formal, a more reliable, a more final sort of a thing than an in-line rate that's set in Section 7 proceeding after a hearing.","start":9730.407,"stop":9755.308,"duration":24.9},{"text":"And even if the producer goes ahead and charges that rate, set at us and -- charges the in-line rate that he's told to charge by the Commission, he nevertheless has to refund if this happens to get reversed.","start":9755.308,"stop":9768.693,"duration":13.38}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"I am saying that if the Commission prescribes a rate in a temporary certificate, it does not provide -- and -- and provides that it can be changed in the future prospectively that the producer provided (Voice Overlap) to keep those dollars.","start":9768.693,"stop":9788.998,"duration":20.31}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commission didn't provide anything like that in Callery.","start":9788.998,"stop":9792.417,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":9792.417,"stop":9793.07,"duration":0.65},{"text":"But they provided in the October 5th, in the February 5th order they said that's exactly what they did in this case.","start":9793.07,"stop":9799.831,"duration":6.76},{"text":"I'm not in Callery, if it may -- if it may please, Your Honor.","start":9799.831,"stop":9803.012,"duration":3.18},{"text":"I am in this case dealing with exactly what they said in date of effect --","start":9803.012,"stop":9806.752,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean -- you mean without -- without the February 5th order having been in review, you wouldn't be here.","start":9806.752,"stop":9813.116,"duration":6.36},{"text":"Oh!","start":9813.116,"stop":9813.262,"duration":0.15},{"text":"I'm sure you would.","start":9813.262,"stop":9817.964,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"I think I would be here on any --","start":9817.964,"stop":9820.006,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly the same argument except without the February 5th order.","start":9820.006,"stop":9822.937,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that if --","start":9822.937,"stop":9824.733,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You would say that that -- you would still say that the temporary rate set by the Commission was a legislative act that couldn't be changed through retroactively.","start":9824.733,"stop":9834.839,"duration":10.11}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"Retroactively, yes sir.","start":9834.839,"stop":9836.306,"duration":1.47},{"text":"Yes, yes, I would make that argument with or without the February 5th order.","start":9836.306,"stop":9839.659,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you think about -- what do you think about the in-line price though?","start":9839.659,"stop":9846.542,"duration":6.88},{"text":"Why does the company have to refund whatever rate that it's been charging which the Commissioner set after an in-line price hearing.Callery said it had to.","start":9846.542,"stop":9858.683,"duration":12.14}]},{"speakerName":"Justin R. Wolf","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't read Callery as at least, I may not if I don't read it.","start":9858.683,"stop":9863.531,"duration":4.85},{"text":"I certainly don't understand Callery in the way that you have just articulated Callery.","start":9863.531,"stop":9869.465,"duration":5.93},{"text":"I have to not hold to the fact that it's one of your opinions without mine but I (Voice Overlap) -- I did not read it that way.","start":9869.465,"stop":9878.192,"duration":8.73}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":9878.192,"stop":9887.789,"duration":9.6}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Schiff.","start":9887.789,"stop":9889.787,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice.","start":9889.787,"stop":9895.493,"duration":5.71},{"text":"Briefly, I think I should make it clear on the -- with respect to refunds, that first, we do believe that the -- without prejudice language in the temporaries, certainly shows the non-finality of the rates which were permitted to be charged under the temporary authorization.","start":9895.493,"stop":9925.166,"duration":29.67},{"text":"At the same time, if I did not make this clear yesterday, the Commission during the course of the proceedings with respect to in-liners has changed its view as to the equity of ordering refunds where there has been no express conditions stating that refunds would not be required at the end.","start":9925.166,"stop":9955.578,"duration":30.41}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, you really have to conceive, don't you, that your action here is contrary to that February 5 order, to the language of the February 5 order.","start":9955.578,"stop":9966.031,"duration":10.45}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I think, Mr. Justice Fortas, that the -- it's certainly our action is contrary to our or the Commission's view on the equities in that order.","start":9966.031,"stop":9977.19,"duration":11.16},{"text":"There is no question about that.","start":9977.19,"stop":9979.377,"duration":2.19},{"text":"The Commission's view of the equities in the February 5th order is precisely the same as the Commission's view of the equities in the Skelly case which was decided by the Commission in August of 1962.","start":9979.377,"stop":9997.415,"duration":18.04}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I myself don't think you could say stated position against refunds because they are more empathetically than it was said in Chairman Swidler's opinion for the Commission on February 5.","start":9997.415,"stop":10013.306,"duration":15.89}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that opinion is as I read it and it's consistently with your earlier decision is not that the Commissions had no power to order refunds of these even without the expressed refund condition.","start":10013.306,"stop":10029.693,"duration":16.39},{"text":"It is a view that the Commission at that time did not think it would be equitable to order refunds.","start":10029.693,"stop":10036.939,"duration":7.25},{"text":"Subsequently, had the consequence no doubt, of the reversal by the District of Columbia Circuit in the Skelly case and upon a more considered in depth consideration of the equities, the Commission concluded that although it assumed that the producers reasonably relied on the lack of refund condition in the belief that they would not have to order refunds, the Commission then concluded that it would be equitable to order refunds.","start":10036.939,"stop":10072.342,"duration":35.4},{"text":"And there is no question but that this is a change in the Commission's view of the equities.","start":10072.342,"stop":10078.519,"duration":6.18},{"text":"And then --","start":10078.519,"stop":10078.703,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose you -- suppose you argued on the basis that someone might believe what that order as said, was that the Commission was without power to do that even if it wanted to.","start":10078.703,"stop":10089.316,"duration":10.61},{"text":"And it wouldn't do it even if it has the power.","start":10089.316,"stop":10094.281,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I -- I think --","start":10094.281,"stop":10094.905,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I must say that's the way it looks to me like, what they said.","start":10094.905,"stop":10098.844,"duration":3.94},{"text":"What then would you say about the effect of that order?","start":10098.844,"stop":10103.01,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well and -- and if -- I don't think that order really makes any difference in this case, Your Honor.","start":10103.01,"stop":10108.262,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's it and why?","start":10108.262,"stop":10109.635,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me get to it.","start":10109.635,"stop":10111.989,"duration":2.35},{"text":"The temporaries in this case were issued in service commenced long before this February 5th order was entered.","start":10111.989,"stop":10123.043,"duration":11.05},{"text":"The Commission's action in -- the distributors in the motion which led up to this order, requested the Commission alternatively to either vacate the temporaries that had been issued or else to impose a prospective refund condition.","start":10123.043,"stop":10142.528,"duration":19.49},{"text":"In that motion, the distributors pointed out that they were challenging in Court the power of the Commission or the propriety of the Commission not ordering refunds and not imposing refund conditions.","start":10142.528,"stop":10160.199,"duration":17.67},{"text":"The Commission in its February 5th order said that because service had already commenced, it did not regard it as appropriate to vacate these temporaries because before you could stop service with respect to flowing gas, the Commission should make the determination as to whether abandonment was justified.","start":10160.199,"stop":10184.714,"duration":24.51},{"text":"It then went on to say that in any event, we don't think that it would be a fair play if we now after service had commenced change the terms of service.","start":10184.714,"stop":10202.564,"duration":17.85},{"text":"I don't believe, I'm not sure, but in my view, that order was in the context of a contention that the Commission has a power to order refunds in any event and all the Commission was doing here is saying we still think that it isn't equitable to order refunds.","start":10202.564,"stop":10221.616,"duration":19.05}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But it should hold what it said here.","start":10221.616,"stop":10223.533,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if --","start":10223.533,"stop":10223.981,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it your idea that the Commission was wrong without its power.","start":10223.981,"stop":10228.712,"duration":4.73},{"text":"And that it construed the statute improperly.","start":10228.712,"stop":10232.144,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I think it -- I think the Commission would have been wrong in construing that it did not have the power.","start":10232.144,"stop":10239.645,"duration":7.5},{"text":"I don't think that that order was strictly reviewable at that time because the service was already flowing and it really related to the consequences it would have at the end of the proceeding.","start":10239.645,"stop":10253.284,"duration":13.64},{"text":"I don't think that the February 5th order changed the consequences or the situation that existed prior to the February 5th order.","start":10253.284,"stop":10263.754,"duration":10.47}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It would have changed it, would it not, if they were right and as we're saying, and I think they did, that they will with that power to do this and they wouldn't do it if they could under the statute?","start":10263.754,"stop":10276.631,"duration":12.88}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I --","start":10276.631,"stop":10283.317,"duration":6.69}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't have to defend it, do you, if you think it was a wrong construction of the statute?","start":10283.317,"stop":10289.27,"duration":5.95},{"text":"Or are you defending it even though it was a wrong construction to the statute?","start":10289.27,"stop":10294.65,"duration":5.38}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"If it was a wrong construction that -- well, I don't think that that construction -- I think that construction, if that was a construction that we had no power to order refunds would be --","start":10294.65,"stop":10305.951,"duration":11.3}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Under those conditions.","start":10305.951,"stop":10307.061,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"-- under those conditions, would be an interlocutory interpretation by the Commission which was not binding even upon the Commission and was not viewed as the Commission's interpretation in the later order.","start":10307.061,"stop":10319.339,"duration":12.28}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do you think it has the power?","start":10319.339,"stop":10321.408,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, very definitely, I think the Commission has the power to order refunds.","start":10321.408,"stop":10325.38,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Even under those conditions.","start":10325.38,"stop":10328.271,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Even under the conditions that it had not imposed an expressed refund condition and in answer to Mr. Justice White's question yesterday, I think in effect that because of the prior history of refund conditions and no refund conditions, that you virtually have to get to the point of saying that the Commission has the power to order refunds where there is a tentative rate even if it had said we do not intend to order refunds.","start":10328.271,"stop":10359.466,"duration":31.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did I understand that this order was after these particular certificates here were issued?","start":10359.466,"stop":10364.802,"duration":5.34}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"This February 5th order was after these certificates were issued or it's long after the time when they had commenced service under those certificates.","start":10364.802,"stop":10373.042,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And you would say, therefore, I assume that the certificates hold it didn't have the right to rely on that so that it would be breaking face with them.","start":10373.042,"stop":10382.267,"duration":9.23},{"text":"That was wrong.","start":10382.267,"stop":10384.195,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well the -- oh, the Commission takes a view and I take the view that the certificate holders -- because not just because of this order, but also because other Commission orders in this period had the right to believe that they would not be required to make refunds and the Commission in the order in its Opinion 501 where it did order refunds expressly accepted the proposition that there had been reasonable reliance.","start":10384.195,"stop":10415.049,"duration":30.85},{"text":"But it went on to conclude that the producers when given an opportunity to show any detriment from that reliance had failed to do so except with a very limited area of royalties which was specifically paid out on reliance on the higher price and certain state production taxes.","start":10415.049,"stop":10435.884,"duration":20.83},{"text":"And it is our view -- and I think this is the only way that this can be differentiated from Callery which I think it's illegal for Callery, we think on a legal proposition is certainly controlling.","start":10435.884,"stop":10447.781,"duration":11.9},{"text":"But in terms of equity, the Commission's course of conduct here may have been such as to induce the producers to pay out certain specific sums which it would not otherwise have paid out.","start":10447.781,"stop":10458.59,"duration":10.81},{"text":"And we based on our decision on that assumption.","start":10458.59,"stop":10463.148,"duration":4.56},{"text":"But beyond that, we think that has to be reliance and a detriment from that reliance.","start":10463.148,"stop":10469.697,"duration":6.55},{"text":"And the producers simply haven't shown any detriment except in the very limited circumstances I've made.","start":10469.697,"stop":10475.794,"duration":6.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Thus the Commission specifically overruled or repudiated this February 5th order?","start":10475.794,"stop":10482.245,"duration":6.45}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh!","start":10482.245,"stop":10482.377,"duration":0.13},{"text":"Yes.","start":10482.377,"stop":10485.024,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It's done in an opinion?","start":10485.024,"stop":10487.036,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in Opinion 501 --","start":10487.036,"stop":10489.827,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"It's ordered to refund.","start":10489.827,"stop":10491.19,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"And it's ordered a refund, Opinion 501 which is in this small section --","start":10491.19,"stop":10495.948,"duration":4.76}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You're talking about in this case?","start":10495.948,"stop":10497.329,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"That's this case --","start":10497.329,"stop":10498.158,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I was asking, if they would have done it in with any another?","start":10498.158,"stop":10500.812,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there had been a series of other cases where the Commission has ordered refunds in comparable circumstances.","start":10500.812,"stop":10508.073,"duration":7.26},{"text":"There is the case which is pending here from the Tenth Circuit, Pan American case which relates to a Commission proceeding involving many South Louisiana sales.","start":10508.073,"stop":10519.716,"duration":11.64},{"text":"I believe that in that case, there was an order similar to the February 5th order.","start":10519.716,"stop":10525.07,"duration":5.35},{"text":"The Commission has ordered re -- well, it hasn't ordered refunds there yet.","start":10525.07,"stop":10528.877,"duration":3.81},{"text":"But it has again, said that this called for hearings to determine the equities.","start":10528.877,"stop":10534.342,"duration":5.47},{"text":"But it has now ordered refunds in the Hawkins case which is the Texas District 3 case.","start":10534.342,"stop":10544.694,"duration":10.35},{"text":"That case is pending in the Tenth Circuit.","start":10544.694,"stop":10548.267,"duration":3.57},{"text":"It has ordered refunds in the case relating to Sun Oil.","start":10548.267,"stop":10551.638,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Any difference detriment to either of the cases?","start":10551.638,"stop":10556.66,"duration":5.02}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in one -- in one case, Mr. Justice Brennan, I referred to yesterday, I think it's Hawkins.","start":10556.66,"stop":10564.247,"duration":7.59},{"text":"There was a situation where a producer showed and we've mentioned in our brief, produced to show that these very large -- that he had very large refunds in relation to his own operations.","start":10564.247,"stop":10576.217,"duration":11.97},{"text":"And that this, if he was required to make refunds immediately, might cause them difficulties even though --","start":10576.217,"stop":10584.234,"duration":8.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But all he did was spread that over to --","start":10584.234,"stop":10585.769,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that could be spread out over --","start":10585.769,"stop":10587.524,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I gather then, the Commission's position is that it does have power to order refunds but it also has power to adjust the amount of refunds or eliminate them entirely on the showing by the producer of what the Commission would regard as detriment.","start":10587.524,"stop":10605.596,"duration":18.07}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Mr. Justice Brennan.","start":10605.596,"stop":10606.942,"duration":1.35},{"text":"And in this respect, the District of Columbia Circuit in that early Skelly case, agreed with us that we should consider the equity.","start":10606.942,"stop":10617.027,"duration":10.09},{"text":"And the equities there were -- that were presented to them, there was in fact that there had been no specific refund obligation and the Judge Fahy in writing that opinion, recognized as the Commission has here that the Commission had not followed the straightest line in these matters and that we had to take this into account.","start":10617.027,"stop":10642.231,"duration":25.2},{"text":"I may say that there was an argument, I think both by the counsels here and there's an amicus brief which suggest that the Commission has a declared law which may producers were entitled to rely upon.","start":10642.231,"stop":10657.824,"duration":15.59},{"text":"Whatever that means here, the Commission accepted the reliance but it didn't find the (Voice Overlap)","start":10657.824,"stop":10662.462,"duration":4.64}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well as I gather it you -- you -- that the Commission's present position is that even if we had said we will not ask for refunds, we nevertheless have power to order refunds unless we discover that the reliance took the form of a concrete detriment to the producer of some kind, is that it?","start":10662.462,"stop":10683.615,"duration":21.15}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":10683.615,"stop":10686.625,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Schiff, if the in-line price here is determined to have been set too high, it's 15 rather than 16.","start":10686.625,"stop":10694.692,"duration":8.07},{"text":"And if the companies had been charging that higher in-line price at 16, and then the order is reversed and that it said that it should be 15, what authority is there for saying there would have to be a refund in that situation?","start":10694.692,"stop":10711.467,"duration":16.78},{"text":"Is that Callery?","start":10711.467,"stop":10713.195,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that is the situa -- well that is the situation --","start":10713.195,"stop":10717.142,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Except that in Callery, the original -- the rate or the part of which was refunded really wasn't set by the Commission, was it?","start":10717.142,"stop":10725.752,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I maybe I have -- I better make sure that I understand your question.","start":10725.752,"stop":10731.923,"duration":6.17},{"text":"If the Commission had fixed a 16-cent which is --","start":10731.923,"stop":10736.296,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in-line price.","start":10736.296,"stop":10737.559,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":10737.559,"stop":10738.323,"duration":0.76},{"text":"And you now were -- remanded and (Voice Overlap) ultimately would be 15.","start":10738.323,"stop":10748.505,"duration":10.18},{"text":"I think that would still be Callery.","start":10748.505,"stop":10751.668,"duration":3.16},{"text":"I think it would just change the measure of refunds but it wouldn't change the legal --","start":10751.668,"stop":10756.817,"duration":5.15}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't think it was significant in Callery that the -- that that was a permanent certificate and a rate under a permanent certificate, I suppose.","start":10756.817,"stop":10766.774,"duration":9.96},{"text":"But the Commission didn't specify that original rate in this.","start":10766.774,"stop":10769.663,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh!","start":10769.663,"stop":10769.797,"duration":0.13},{"text":"We approved the original rate in the -- in the original certificate just as much --","start":10769.797,"stop":10774.894,"duration":5.1}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"This might (Voice Overlap) in issuing the certificate?","start":10774.894,"stop":10777.025,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we had a hearing to determine whether that was a proper certificate price when we issued --","start":10777.025,"stop":10780.956,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"In Callery?","start":10780.956,"stop":10781.849,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"In Callery, that those were the cases that were set aside in the UGI case but we --","start":10781.849,"stop":10787.171,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But the rates you approved were actually agreed upon rates, weren't they?","start":10787.171,"stop":10792.606,"duration":5.43}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Agreed upon in this -- well, that -- that was a rate that the contract rates and we simply didn't lower it in that sense.","start":10792.606,"stop":10799.32,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Were the rates as specified it.","start":10799.32,"stop":10801.014,"duration":1.69},{"text":"You specified what the parties agreed to do?","start":10801.014,"stop":10802.889,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I don't think in terms of say the Arizona Grocery case of reparations that these are -- these were any different.","start":10802.889,"stop":10812.34,"duration":9.45}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Schiff, does a -- does the Commission have the power to -- under the statute, to issue a permanent or temporary certificate without approving rates?","start":10812.34,"stop":10825.377,"duration":13.04}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Without specifically approving rates?","start":10825.377,"stop":10828.199,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Without approving rates, sometimes, somehow, someway.","start":10828.199,"stop":10835.018,"duration":6.82}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think this Court's decision in the CATCO case indicates that the Commission must give careful scrutiny to the rates of the Commission if it wants to give scrutiny to the rates in the certificate case then of course has discretion in large measure to determine whether it will have a rate hearing.","start":10835.018,"stop":10858.567,"duration":23.55}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"When you issued temporary certificates here did the Commission or did it not approve the rates?","start":10858.567,"stop":10867.175,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well it approved them in the sense that these were the rates that could legally be charged, that if by the producer by charging them could not have been held --","start":10867.175,"stop":10876.396,"duration":9.22}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- provision was cited in the Sun Oil temporary certificate for example that it did not approve the rates.","start":10876.396,"stop":10887.108,"duration":10.71}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it didn't approve the level of the rates.","start":10887.108,"stop":10888.967,"duration":1.86},{"text":"It didn't find that they're either the just reasonable rate or the appropriate certificate rate.","start":10888.967,"stop":10895.281,"duration":6.31},{"text":"It was allowing the rates to be charged.","start":10895.281,"stop":10900.671,"duration":5.39},{"text":"I think the Commission has a power to do that.","start":10900.671,"stop":10903.82,"duration":3.15},{"text":"It doesn't have to necessarily give either the scrutiny required by section or by rate case --","start":10903.82,"stop":10911.083,"duration":7.26}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Then they have to come with time under this statute when the Commissioners to approve the rate?","start":10911.083,"stop":10915.83,"duration":4.75}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, all these rates are involved in the area rate proceeding relating to the Texas Gulf Coast.","start":10915.83,"stop":10921.968,"duration":6.14},{"text":"And we have considered them in the --","start":10921.968,"stop":10923.989,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Not if you don't have power to ref -- to order refund?","start":10923.989,"stop":10927.787,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this is why we think that we do could order refunds here down to the price determined in the permanent certificate case.","start":10927.787,"stop":10937.346,"duration":9.56},{"text":"I don't think we have to make a full adjudication of the rates before we permit them to commence service under a temporary.","start":10937.346,"stop":10948.228,"duration":10.88},{"text":"I would like to spend a minute or so on the questions of need.","start":10948.228,"stop":10955.789,"duration":7.56},{"text":"And I like to reiterate that the Commission fully realized this that it must consider not only whether the pipelines are getting sufficient quantities of gas but also whether there are more than sufficient quantities of gas being purchased and what effect this might have on the rates of the pipelines and consequently on the rates of the producers -- or of the consumers.","start":10955.789,"stop":10987.089,"duration":31.3},{"text":"The –- well, I see my --","start":10987.089,"stop":10989.935,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may make a very short statement.","start":10989.935,"stop":10992.134,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"But basically our view, however, as I said before is that the question of need may and can, and is being considered in pipeline proceedings.","start":10992.134,"stop":11005.914,"duration":13.78},{"text":"The particular pipeline facilities involved in these cases have been approved in the past.","start":11005.914,"stop":11014.716,"duration":8.8},{"text":"But normally, in order to consider the question of need before the gas goes into the market which is the proper time to consider it is in pipeline proceedings.","start":11014.716,"stop":11029.962,"duration":15.25},{"text":"It cannot be done in producer proceedings unless you simply eliminate temporaries because as was recognized before, the gas will be flowing long before for a long time before the question of a need can be finally determined in a producer case.","start":11029.962,"stop":11048.89,"duration":18.93},{"text":"So in these circumstances, the appropriate place is in the pipeline proceedings and there are continuing pipeline proceedings.","start":11048.89,"stop":11059.04,"duration":10.15},{"text":"They are always asking for new facilities to pick up more gas, there are these budget facilities, we believe that these cases provide an ample opportunity for the consumer interest.","start":11059.04,"stop":11074.571,"duration":15.53},{"text":"Those present here and any others to express their views as to the needs of the pipelines and of the various markets affected.","start":11074.571,"stop":11085.117,"duration":10.55},{"text":"Thank you.","start":11085.117,"stop":11091.788,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Simons.","start":11091.788,"stop":11093.771,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice.","start":11093.771,"stop":11098.777,"duration":5.01},{"text":"Mr. Tell during his presentation stated that in the prior cases, the Commission had found 15 cents as the in-line level for the 1950s and that the question before the Commission in this proceedings was to determine whether there were changed circumstances which would justify a change in the in-line price.","start":11098.777,"stop":11118.981,"duration":20.2},{"text":"I would like to comment on his statement in two respects.","start":11118.981,"stop":11122.305,"duration":3.32},{"text":"First of all, the prior in-line finding is not an in-line finding for the 50s.","start":11122.305,"stop":11127.682,"duration":5.38},{"text":"In Skelly, for the example, the Commission had before basically nine contracts executed in 1959 and 1960.","start":11127.682,"stop":11135.423,"duration":7.74},{"text":"And it predicated its finding on the conditions that existed from 1958 through 1960.","start":11135.423,"stop":11142.286,"duration":6.86},{"text":"In the Amerada case, we had contracts for the two-year period beginning immediately after Skelly from September 1960 through August 1962.","start":11142.286,"stop":11153.515,"duration":11.23},{"text":"But in any event, the question is, what were the changed circumstances that the Commission relied on to elevate its in-line level by a penny.","start":11153.515,"stop":11161.538,"duration":8.02},{"text":"The changed circumstances were essentially the higher prices negotiated in the marketplace.","start":11161.538,"stop":11167.063,"duration":5.52},{"text":"And I think that this brings us not only to the whole suspect line doctrine but to the manner in which it was phrased by Judge Bazelon below.","start":11167.063,"stop":11176.527,"duration":9.46},{"text":"He said the need for the FPC and for a concept like in-line prices arises primarily because the unregulated marketplace cannot protect the consumer adequately.","start":11176.527,"stop":11187.766,"duration":11.24},{"text":"Congress created the FPC to protect the consumer from the marketplace, not simply to reflect it.","start":11187.766,"stop":11194.027,"duration":6.26},{"text":"It may well be true that the marketplace was leading to higher prices of pipelines and producers who are willing to negotiate for higher prices in the 60s than they were in 1959 and 1960.","start":11194.027,"stop":11206.275,"duration":12.25},{"text":"This fact, far from contradicting a need for holding the line for FPC control merely emphasizes it.","start":11206.275,"stop":11215.645,"duration":9.37},{"text":"Now, the Commission attempts to say, “Well, we aren't relying on the naked marketplace as we did in the CATCO case which led to this Court's reversal.","start":11215.645,"stop":11224.027,"duration":8.38},{"text":"We're relying on the fact that we have issued temporary certificates.","start":11224.027,"stop":11228.979,"duration":4.95},{"text":"But the prices contained the temporary certificates are not approved.","start":11228.979,"stop":11233.276,"duration":4.3},{"text":"They are not final.","start":11233.276,"stop":11234.306,"duration":1.03},{"text":"They are subject to revision, happy outcome of the hearing on those temporary certificates.","start":11234.306,"stop":11240.105,"duration":5.8},{"text":"That price is the price that obtains only during the pendency of a hearing to determine whether it should be permanently certificated.","start":11240.105,"stop":11248.41,"duration":8.31},{"text":"And indeed once it's permanently certificated, it can be replaced by the just and reasonable rate at a later time.","start":11248.41,"stop":11255.156,"duration":6.75},{"text":"But it's for this reason that no reliance can be placed on temporary -- temporarily certificated prices.","start":11255.156,"stop":11261.867,"duration":6.71},{"text":"Now, what is the difference between certificating an in-line level of 15 cents and an in-line level of 16 cents?","start":11261.867,"stop":11269.693,"duration":7.83},{"text":"It is just this, under both circumstances, the producer can file it up to its contract level, be it 16, 17, 18 cents, or whatever.","start":11269.693,"stop":11278.759,"duration":9.07},{"text":"However, if the ultimate just and reasonable rate is determined in the area rate proceedings, turns out to be lower than 16 cents, if the in-line -- the difference between 15 and 16 cannot be recouped unless the in-line level has been fixed at 15.","start":11278.759,"stop":11298.543,"duration":19.78},{"text":"It's possible that the just and reasonable level could be even lower than 15 cents.","start":11298.543,"stop":11303.412,"duration":4.87},{"text":"In that case, the consumer is just disadvantaged without any recourse at all.","start":11303.412,"stop":11307.896,"duration":4.48},{"text":"But the fact is --","start":11307.896,"stop":11309.13,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless there is a proper condition in the permanent certificate?","start":11309.13,"stop":11312.154,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are no conditions, no conditions are put --","start":11312.154,"stop":11313.37,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"There aren't any?","start":11313.37,"stop":11314.692,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no sir.","start":11314.692,"stop":11315.396,"duration":0.7},{"text":"There are none in any others that I know of.","start":11315.396,"stop":11318.769,"duration":3.37},{"text":"The permanent condition -- the conditions that's put in is to certificate at an in-line level which is the initial certificating level.","start":11318.769,"stop":11325.928,"duration":7.16},{"text":"That's what you can charge until you change it under Section 4.","start":11325.928,"stop":11329.43,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And then no refund?","start":11329.43,"stop":11331.317,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"There are no refunds if you don't change it.","start":11331.317,"stop":11333.015,"duration":1.7},{"text":"That's right.","start":11333.015,"stop":11333.441,"duration":0.43},{"text":"There is no way to touch that at all.","start":11333.441,"stop":11336.063,"duration":2.62},{"text":"That's firm and fixed.","start":11336.063,"stop":11337.989,"duration":1.93},{"text":"Now, the basis for the determination -- oh, incidentally I would say that the Commission never made any finding that there was less need for consumer protection with respect to these contracts which have the 16-cent level than it had for the contracts in Skelly which had a 15-cent level.","start":11337.989,"stop":11355.557,"duration":17.57},{"text":"There was in all three of these cases a diminution in the degree of consumer protection over the prior series of cases without any finding by the Commission that such diminution was proper or was required.","start":11355.557,"stop":11368.173,"duration":12.62},{"text":"Now, what was the basis for the determination of the in-line price?","start":11368.173,"stop":11371.495,"duration":3.32},{"text":"In each of these proceedings, I want to run through it very briefly.","start":11371.495,"stop":11374.706,"duration":3.21},{"text":"In Amerada, I understand this morning that I said that of the 38 contracts relied on for guideline level, and I should have said for in-line level purposes here, 36 of the --","start":11374.706,"stop":11384.283,"duration":9.58}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me, Mr. Simons, did I understand you said that the Commission has no power to condition a permanent certificate on refund after determination of the just and reasonable rate?","start":11384.283,"stop":11396.262,"duration":11.98}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know of any that they have ever done that way, Mr. Justice Brennan.","start":11396.262,"stop":11399.401,"duration":3.14}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I thought I heard you say that but did you suggest that the Commission has no power to do that?","start":11399.401,"stop":11405.007,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't say that.","start":11405.007,"stop":11407.355,"duration":2.35},{"text":"I don't know whether they do.","start":11407.355,"stop":11408.47,"duration":1.11},{"text":"Let me say that.","start":11408.47,"stop":11409.392,"duration":0.92},{"text":"I don't think it has ever arisen.","start":11409.392,"stop":11411.114,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought I heard Mr. Schiff say that.","start":11411.114,"stop":11414.332,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I --","start":11414.332,"stop":11414.341,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"There are no reparations prior to --","start":11414.341,"stop":11416.208,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's right.","start":11416.208,"stop":11417.081,"duration":0.87},{"text":"There is no reparation.","start":11417.081,"stop":11417.788,"duration":0.71},{"text":"Now, if they put in a specific condition for that, I don't know.","start":11417.788,"stop":11420.401,"duration":2.61},{"text":"We're talking about two different situations.","start":11420.401,"stop":11422.534,"duration":2.13},{"text":"If the certificate let's say, at 15 cents, and the in-line price turns out to be 14 later, there is no power to get reparation on the difference between 15 and 14.","start":11422.534,"stop":11432.163,"duration":9.63},{"text":"If they can issue a certificate conditioned at 15 and said further more, anything we later find in an area rate proceeding to be unjust and reasonable shall be refunded.","start":11432.163,"stop":11442.105,"duration":9.94},{"text":"Then you would have the propriety of that kind of a condition.","start":11442.105,"stop":11444.815,"duration":2.71},{"text":"The Commissioner has never imposed that kind of a condition so far as I know.","start":11444.815,"stop":11447.778,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sure my Brothers Brennan is on certainty about what the Commission's position is on that range of possibilities.","start":11447.778,"stop":11456.612,"duration":8.83}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"About imposing a condition that's not in this case?","start":11456.612,"stop":11460.631,"duration":4.02},{"text":"Yes.","start":11460.631,"stop":11461.596,"duration":0.97},{"text":"I would hesitate to say.","start":11461.596,"stop":11462.617,"duration":1.02},{"text":"I'm a great believer.","start":11462.617,"stop":11463.975,"duration":1.36},{"text":"I'm leaving it to the litigation lending their eyes with this.","start":11463.975,"stop":11467.521,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Callery, the Callery case itself said that the fixing of an initial in-line prices establishes a firm price.","start":11467.521,"stop":11475.521,"duration":8}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":11475.521,"stop":11476.219,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And which a producer may operate without any contingent liability to make refunds.","start":11476.219,"stop":11479.873,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":11479.873,"stop":11480.407,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That this is just a reasonable rate to have it be lowered than the in-line price.","start":11480.407,"stop":11483.992,"duration":3.59},{"text":"And one of the reasons given was the Commission didn't have any reparation power.","start":11483.992,"stop":11487.459,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":11487.459,"stop":11488.894,"duration":1.43},{"text":"I thought Mr. Justice Brennan was asking me about a situation not present in Callery, not present in --","start":11488.894,"stop":11493.403,"duration":4.51}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You're absolutely right, I was.","start":11493.403,"stop":11494.246,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, certainly.","start":11494.246,"stop":11495.305,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I've misunderstood what you've said.","start":11495.305,"stop":11496.912,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":11496.912,"stop":11500.344,"duration":3.43},{"text":"Since you have mentioned Callery, I would like to turn right to that.","start":11500.344,"stop":11504.354,"duration":4.01},{"text":"At this point, in Callery, this Court twice mentioned what the standard is for fixing in-line price.","start":11504.354,"stop":11511.902,"duration":7.55},{"text":"It said at 382 U.S. 227, consumer protection is afforded by keeping the in-line price -- by keeping the in-line price at the level where substantial amounts of gas have been certificated to enter the market under contemporaneous certificates no longer subject to judicial review or in any way suspect.","start":11511.902,"stop":11535.003,"duration":23.1},{"text":"Now, there's no question here that the Commission use suspect prices.","start":11535.003,"stop":11539.625,"duration":4.62},{"text":"Again the Court said at page 229, the in-line price of 18.5 cents is supported by the contract prices in the South Louisiana area that were not suspect.","start":11539.625,"stop":11550.82,"duration":11.19},{"text":"Again there's not question that the temporarily certificated prices and the contract prices, that the Commission relied on in this case, the elevated in-line level and thereby reduced the amount of consumer protection were suspect.","start":11550.82,"stop":11563.677,"duration":12.86},{"text":"I said in Amerada that 36 of the 38 contracts which have been temporarily certificated and were relied on for the guideline level were the very -- to fix the in-line level, were the very contracts before the Commission itself.","start":11563.677,"stop":11577.123,"duration":13.45},{"text":"In Sinclair, the Commission referred to the fact and they said this out on page 33 of their brief.","start":11577.123,"stop":11582.929,"duration":5.81},{"text":"They were impressed by the fact that 40% of the total volume was moving at 18 cents.","start":11582.929,"stop":11587.651,"duration":4.72},{"text":"That 40% was all under temporary certificates.","start":11587.651,"stop":11591.774,"duration":4.12},{"text":"Three quarters of that 40% were sales to Lone Star Gathering Company which as I discussed this morning under the need issue, it was subsequently determined.","start":11591.774,"stop":11602.195,"duration":10.42},{"text":"There was no need for it.","start":11602.195,"stop":11603.247,"duration":1.05},{"text":"The certificates were vacated.","start":11603.247,"stop":11605.227,"duration":1.98},{"text":"That 75% of the 40%, three quarters of the 40%, those sales are no longer being made in interstate commerce.","start":11605.227,"stop":11613.883,"duration":8.66},{"text":"Yet, that's what the Commission relied on.","start":11613.883,"stop":11615.849,"duration":1.97},{"text":"They relied on sales that are no longer being made in interstate commerce.","start":11615.849,"stop":11619.555,"duration":3.71},{"text":"That fact alone, it seems to me, would require vacation of the Commissions finding that the in-line level is 16 cents.","start":11619.555,"stop":11626.095,"duration":6.54},{"text":"I would point out too that those were all contracts that were before the Commission to determine the propriety of the in-line price for permanent certification.","start":11626.095,"stop":11635.574,"duration":9.48},{"text":"In the Hawkins case, the Commission seems to have shifted its basis for getting the price of a penny.","start":11635.574,"stop":11640.933,"duration":5.36},{"text":"And it says that its primary reliance was on three permanently certificated 18-cent prices.","start":11640.933,"stop":11647.488,"duration":6.55},{"text":"Those three 18-cent prices, I don't want to go into all of it, but those three prices were deemed suspect by the examiner, by the Commission staff, by the two dissenters, and we set out the reasons in Volume 3 of the appendix of pages 312, 313, why those were suspect.","start":11647.488,"stop":11663.7,"duration":16.21},{"text":"The Commission never addressed itself to a discussion of whether or not they were in fact suspect.","start":11663.7,"stop":11669.599,"duration":5.9},{"text":"But we think clearly under the prior court decisions, they were.","start":11669.599,"stop":11673.711,"duration":4.11},{"text":"Now, the Commission says, it attempts to get around this business of the fact the prices were suspect by saying, well we gave discounted weight, we didn't give full weight to it.","start":11673.711,"stop":11684.043,"duration":10.33},{"text":"But the problem with giving weight anyway to suspect prices is the suspect prices are probative nothing at all of no factor that is relevant in an in-line determination.","start":11684.043,"stop":11692.856,"duration":8.81},{"text":"And you don't cure the defect of giving weight to inadmissible evidence that has no probative value by saying, you gave discounted weight.","start":11692.856,"stop":11700.898,"duration":8.04},{"text":"There is no question here that the discounted weight was crucial.","start":11700.898,"stop":11704.012,"duration":3.11},{"text":"The Commission itself said in Sinclair that if we didn't give any weight, we would have arrived at a lower level.","start":11704.012,"stop":11711.118,"duration":7.11},{"text":"And so you had an inadmissible confession and you had no other evidence so you needed some evidence, so you let it in because it provided that the term would be reduced by one-half or one-fourth.","start":11711.118,"stop":11722.115,"duration":11},{"text":"If it's inadmissible, it's inadmissible.","start":11722.115,"stop":11724.084,"duration":1.97},{"text":"If it's not probative, it's not probative.","start":11724.084,"stop":11725.548,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) was that after all the Commission has some expert -- expertise in this business type where they (Inaudible).","start":11725.548,"stop":11737.218,"duration":11.67}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I think Mr. Justice Harlan --","start":11737.218,"stop":11738.844,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":11738.844,"stop":11740.242,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"I think Mr. Justice Harlan that you get into a tyranny of lack of standards and vague standards.","start":11740.242,"stop":11745.464,"duration":5.22},{"text":"And I want to --","start":11745.464,"stop":11746.435,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Very complicated problem that any standards you find to regulate this industry that we all have experience it in this Court.","start":11746.435,"stop":11758.199,"duration":11.76},{"text":"And we hold to make (Inaudible).","start":11758.199,"stop":11764.077,"duration":5.88}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's see what the Commission itself said.","start":11764.077,"stop":11766.972,"duration":2.9},{"text":"At page 33 of its brief it says, it's speaking here of the Sinclair case.","start":11766.972,"stop":11770.833,"duration":3.86},{"text":"It says, “No doubt on this evidence, the Court examining the matter de novo might choose a different price line.","start":11770.833,"stop":11777.353,"duration":6.52},{"text":"There is room for arguing that the price line should be 15 cents or 15.5 cents or even as high as 18 cents.","start":11777.353,"stop":11783.974,"duration":6.62},{"text":"But in the final analysis, the statute commits the decision to the expert judgment of the Commission.","start":11783.974,"stop":11790.463,"duration":6.49},{"text":"Now, as I understand that they're saying based on the evidentiary record before that they could have come up with anything between 15 and 18 cents.","start":11790.463,"stop":11798.671,"duration":8.21},{"text":"And I submit Mr. Justice Harlan, that that kind of standard is just too vague.","start":11798.671,"stop":11803.279,"duration":4.61},{"text":"It has no meaning.","start":11803.279,"stop":11804.456,"duration":1.18},{"text":"If that's what it is, then the hearing that we had, we might just as well have forgotten it.","start":11804.456,"stop":11809.016,"duration":4.56},{"text":"If that, there is that much range for the Commission to pick an in-line level, then I think that the in-line determination and the protection that this Court intended in CATCO, have been a terrible waste of time.","start":11809.016,"stop":11821.521,"duration":12.51},{"text":"Now, I want to address myself to certain statements made by Mr. Caskin with respect to the Policy Statement.","start":11821.521,"stop":11829.247,"duration":7.73},{"text":"First of all, it was not possible as you pointed out Mr. Chief Justice, to take an appeal from the Policy Statement when it was issued.","start":11829.247,"stop":11837.481,"duration":8.23},{"text":"It was issued without notice, without hearing, without record.","start":11837.481,"stop":11841.75,"duration":4.27},{"text":"The State of Wisconsin representing the consumer interest, filed an application for rehearing which is a prerequisite for review.","start":11841.75,"stop":11849.267,"duration":7.52},{"text":"The Commission rejected that application.","start":11849.267,"stop":11851.814,"duration":2.55},{"text":"The State of Wisconsin took an appeal to the District of Columbia Circuit that Commission defended on the ground that the Policy Statement fixes no rights.","start":11851.814,"stop":11861.084,"duration":9.27},{"text":"It fixes no procedures.","start":11861.084,"stop":11862.732,"duration":1.65},{"text":"When it is applied, that is the time to approach it when it is implemented.","start":11862.732,"stop":11867.761,"duration":5.03},{"text":"I would point out too that in June of 1962, the New York Commission filed the petition to amend the Policy Statement.","start":11867.761,"stop":11875.135,"duration":7.37},{"text":"That petition has been pending for six years.","start":11875.135,"stop":11877.741,"duration":2.61},{"text":"I don't think we're going to get any action on it.","start":11877.741,"stop":11879.852,"duration":2.11},{"text":"When the Commission did implement the Policy Statement in a case like McDermott, we did appeal.","start":11879.852,"stop":11885.425,"duration":5.57},{"text":"The DC Circuit said, “We don't have a full record.”","start":11885.425,"stop":11887.784,"duration":2.36},{"text":"These matters can all be worked out.","start":11887.784,"stop":11889.698,"duration":1.91},{"text":"We did attack specifically in the McDermott appeal, the failure to include and express refund condition, we attack the fact that the price was out of line in the temporary.","start":11889.698,"stop":11898.199,"duration":8.5},{"text":"The DC Circuit said, “These matters, we don't have a full record before as these matters can all be determined on permanent certification.","start":11898.199,"stop":11905.632,"duration":7.43},{"text":"That is the time to obtain it.”","start":11905.632,"stop":11907.707,"duration":2.08},{"text":"Now, Mr. Johnson has suggested that the distributor companies are here before you because they will retain a large amount of money if they can and that it's purely a selfish interest.","start":11907.707,"stop":11919.914,"duration":12.21},{"text":"First of all, a statement would not apply in any event to the Public Service Commission of the State of New York which is not a distributor.","start":11919.914,"stop":11925.495,"duration":5.58},{"text":"With respect to the three distributors I represent, I like to state that two of them, Brooklyn Union Gas Company, Long Island Lighting Company have purchased gas adjustment clauses in their contract, the effect of which is that any dollar that they get back out of this proceeding will flow right through to their customers.","start":11925.495,"stop":11941.761,"duration":16.27},{"text":"They will not retain it.","start":11941.761,"stop":11943.153,"duration":1.39},{"text":"With respect to Philadelphia Electric Company, I had occasion to check what they had done with the monies they have gotten back through the end of 1966.","start":11943.153,"stop":11951.512,"duration":8.36},{"text":"They had received $4 million from their two pipeline suppliers, part of it, being producer refunds that the pipelines have passed on.","start":11951.512,"stop":11959.948,"duration":8.44},{"text":"And they had refunded or flow through to their customers, passed on to their customers 99.6% of that.","start":11959.948,"stop":11966.757,"duration":6.81},{"text":"Now, I think that this is a meretricious argument.","start":11966.757,"stop":11971.024,"duration":4.27},{"text":"I think if there's any question at all, certainly the clients I represent would have no problem if this Court where to say that the money should flow through directly to the consumer.","start":11971.024,"stop":11979.431,"duration":8.41},{"text":"We are here trying to vindicate the consumer interest.","start":11979.431,"stop":11981.972,"duration":2.54},{"text":"We're not trying to make the money for ourselves.","start":11981.972,"stop":11984.866,"duration":2.89},{"text":"I would point out too that as to some of the refunds that were withheld by some distributors, they may well have been used to offset rate increases.","start":11984.866,"stop":11990.448,"duration":5.58},{"text":"They may well have benefited the consumer in other ways.","start":11990.448,"stop":11995.521,"duration":5.07},{"text":"In any event, they don't apply so far as these refunds are concerned with respect to my clients.","start":11995.521,"stop":12014.624,"duration":19.1},{"text":"With respect to the Commission's exercise of its refund power, I would like to point out that in Amerada, the Commission declined in its original Amerada order, Opinion 422 in 1964, the Commission declined to take any action on refunds.","start":12014.624,"stop":12032.043,"duration":17.42},{"text":"In our appeal to the Tenth Circuit, and in our appeal here, we took the position that the Commission's failure to take action was error, that it was required to act and that it was required that it had the duty to order refunds.","start":12032.043,"stop":12043.551,"duration":11.51},{"text":"If we are correct in that contention which is before this Court, and if this Court should find that we are correct, then you don't get into the problem of the equities.","start":12043.551,"stop":12054.566,"duration":11.02},{"text":"We accept the fact that the Commission's subsequent order Opinion 501, substantially moots our appeal on that point if 501 does satisfy our request on that point.","start":12054.566,"stop":12067.757,"duration":13.19},{"text":"But our appeal right from the beginning was that the Commission had the power and the duty to order refunds at the time that it issued permanent certificates.","start":12067.757,"stop":12078.332,"duration":10.58},{"text":"I think that the issue we have here in these cases is one of proper administrative standards, does the Commission have to explain in a meaningful way what it did?","start":12078.332,"stop":12088.651,"duration":10.32},{"text":"Does it have to provide adequate protection for the consumer?","start":12088.651,"stop":12093.089,"duration":4.44},{"text":"We would ask that you find that the Commission must make a finding of need before it certificates, that it must hold the line at the level that it previously found and not elevate it by reference to temporary certificates and that refunds were required to make the consumer hold for the out of line amounts paid.","start":12093.089,"stop":12110.509,"duration":17.42}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you brush on that point?","start":12110.509,"stop":12113.711,"duration":3.2},{"text":"What was this need issue?","start":12113.711,"stop":12116.913,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Morton L. Simon","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh!","start":12116.913,"stop":12117.632,"duration":0.72},{"text":"Yes.","start":12117.632,"stop":12119.886,"duration":2.25},{"text":"I meant to respond to that, Mr. Justice Harlan.","start":12119.886,"stop":12124.579,"duration":4.69},{"text":"The Amerada proceeding arose in 1962.","start":12124.579,"stop":12127.939,"duration":3.36},{"text":"The Hawkins and Sinclair in a related term (Inaudible) proceedings came on for hearing 1964.","start":12127.939,"stop":12135.21,"duration":7.27},{"text":"At 1962 and through 1962, we were willing to accept the fact that there was a need or at least we were not raising that issue.","start":12135.21,"stop":12142.313,"duration":7.1},{"text":"We were attempting to focus in on the price issue.","start":12142.313,"stop":12145.022,"duration":2.71},{"text":"And we did not raise the issue either we did not raise it or in some cases, Union Texas was another contemporaneous case we stipulated.","start":12145.022,"stop":12152.208,"duration":7.19},{"text":"But we became increasingly aware between the institution of the Amerada proceeding and Hawkins-Sinclair that the pipelines were getting into increasing difficulty that they were having to make dump, the low cost dump sales from oil re-fillers for example because they had these take-or-pay problems for their use.","start":12152.208,"stop":12168.472,"duration":16.26},{"text":"And so by 1964, we concluded that we could no longer stipulate that there was a need.","start":12168.472,"stop":12173.98,"duration":5.51},{"text":"If -- had Amerada come later we would have raised it.","start":12173.98,"stop":12176.075,"duration":2.1},{"text":"Had the others come earlier, we probably wouldn't have it this time.","start":12176.075,"stop":12180.668,"duration":4.59},{"text":"Thank you very much.","start":12180.668,"stop":12189.003,"duration":8.34}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 22, 1968","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren15/oral_argument_audio/15321","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 60, Federal Power Commission, Petitioner, versus Sunray DX Oil Company et al. and companion cases, number 61 to 62, 80, 97, and 111, 143, 144 and 271.","start":0,"stop":37.817,"duration":37.82},{"text":"Mr. Schiff.","start":37.817,"stop":39.456,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":39.456,"stop":44.376,"duration":4.92},{"text":"The group of cases before the Court today are part of the Commission's interim program for determining initial certificate prices for the sales by independent producers of natural gas.","start":44.376,"stop":60.956,"duration":16.58},{"text":"This is interim awaiting the Commission's determination of just and reasonable rates in area rate proceedings.","start":60.956,"stop":70.963,"duration":10.01},{"text":"Under this interim program which this Court has -- had the occasion to discuss in the second Phillips case and has dealt with to some extent in the Callery case in 1965.","start":70.963,"stop":85.808,"duration":14.85},{"text":"The Commission building on another decision of this Court the CATCO case which was decided in 1959, that was under the style of Atlantic Refining Company and Public Service Commission of New York has been using its conditioning power under Section 7 of the Natural Gas Act to stabilize prices, producer prices or in the words of this Court to attempt to hold the line.","start":85.808,"stop":124.22,"duration":38.41},{"text":"As an early part of this interim program, the Commission at the time that it decided the second Phillips case that is the case where it concluded that the just and reasonable rates of independent producers should be determined on a area basis.","start":124.22,"stop":144.559,"duration":20.34},{"text":"The Commission promulgated a statement of general policy designating 23 pricing areas and for each of these pricing areas, it established a ceiling price above which the Commission would not permit gas to add on the market under the certificates of public convenience and necessity.","start":144.559,"stop":169.009,"duration":24.45},{"text":"If there was no objection, the Commission would issue a premise certificate at those prices.","start":169.009,"stop":175.657,"duration":6.65},{"text":"If there were objection, the Commission would issue temporary certificates if the proper allegations were made by the producers and requested such certificates.","start":175.657,"stop":191.279,"duration":15.62},{"text":"These ceilings or guidelines as they have been referred to were issued in September of 1960.","start":191.279,"stop":200.599,"duration":9.32},{"text":"And while some of these guidelines has subsequently been adjusted downward, the guidelines themselves did clamp a lid on the price rise that have been generated in the market.","start":200.599,"stop":216.264,"duration":15.67},{"text":"During the same general period of time, the Commission in attempting to apply the requirement to hold line commends the series of the so-called in-line proceedings and the case is there before the Court now fit into that category.","start":216.264,"stop":240.321,"duration":24.06},{"text":"The Commission as part of this interim program has had more than 25 proceedings to determine the appropriate initial certificate price for producer sales and these are related to 13 pricing areas.","start":240.321,"stop":258.624,"duration":18.3},{"text":"As a result of this program, the price rise as I've indicated would stop and the program as Mr. Solomon told you during the course of the Permian Basin argument has resulted in price reductions below the proposed contract levels of about $134 million.","start":258.624,"stop":282.151,"duration":23.53},{"text":"This included both the fully adjudicated cases as well as settlements which generally followed the principles.","start":282.151,"stop":290.755,"duration":8.6},{"text":"It does not include the amounts of money that are involved in these cases.","start":290.755,"stop":297.74,"duration":6.99},{"text":"The -- essentially the in-line program that I have described should be viewed as being in the past tense because except for the Texas Gulf Coast area which is involved here and the South Louisiana area, there is no dispute as to the appropriate initial certificate price and the price question at least poses no barrier to the issuance of permanent certificates.","start":297.74,"stop":331.688,"duration":33.95},{"text":"And in the Texas Gulf Coast areas and in the South Louisiana area, it is my understanding that the Commission will not conduct further in-line proceedings of the type that are involved here but that instead it will issue the -- as it had issue temporary authorization for the guideline prices and then determine the final certificate price on the basis of the just and reasonable determination to be made in the pending area rate proceedings.","start":331.688,"stop":370.359,"duration":38.67},{"text":"Now, in saying this I do not wished to give the impression that this case is of no consequence because indeed the resolution of the series of conflicting Court of Appeals' decisions will determine the disposition of -- in the neighborhood of $20 to $30 million.","start":370.359,"stop":396.396,"duration":26.04},{"text":"The present group of cases arise from three different commission proceedings relating to something more than a hundred sales by independent producers.","start":396.396,"stop":413.733,"duration":17.34},{"text":"Each proceeding related to one of the pricing areas in the Texas Gulf Coast in the Commission for these purposes has followed the designations of areas of the Texas Railroad Commission.","start":413.733,"stop":427.955,"duration":14.22},{"text":"So, the Commission had a separate proceeding for Texas District 4 which with the first case at -- in time and another one for Texas District Number 2 and a third one for Texas District Number 3.","start":427.955,"stop":443.975,"duration":16.02},{"text":"And the cases arise from two different Courts of Appeals.","start":443.975,"stop":449.421,"duration":5.45},{"text":"The first one, relating the so-called Amerada case comes from the decisions by the Tenth Circuit and the other two cases which have been generally referred to by the Courts and the Commission as the Hawkins and Sinclair cases were decided at the -- at one time by the Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit.","start":449.421,"stop":474.966,"duration":25.55}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now, Mr. Schiff.","start":474.966,"stop":484.184,"duration":9.22},{"text":"Mr. Schiff, you may continue your argument.","start":484.184,"stop":488.273,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice as I was saying before lunch, these cases involved about hundred sales of independent producers from the various pricing districts on -- in the Texas Gulf Coast.","start":488.273,"stop":504.243,"duration":15.97},{"text":"The sales involved were all contracted for during the period from about 1958 to 1963.","start":504.243,"stop":512.647,"duration":8.4},{"text":"And in just about all instances, the sales commenced under a temporary authorizations which are issued on the basis of producer allegations of emergency and without any notice for hearing.","start":512.647,"stop":528.084,"duration":15.44},{"text":"The -- for the period prior to the policy statement which was issued in September 1960, the temporary in some instances ranged up to a price of 20 cents.","start":528.084,"stop":541.421,"duration":13.34},{"text":"And for the period after that, there were no prices that were charged although there are some higher contracts but no price is charged at above the 18-cent guideline price level.","start":541.421,"stop":555.03,"duration":13.61},{"text":"In the first of the three proceedings that is here which is known as -- was known as the Amerada proceeding before the Commission and with respect to which -- there are two volumes of the joint appendix, numbers 1 and 2, that case involves sales in Texas District Number 4 and in all instances, the contracts involved were executed after the date of the policy statement in 1960.","start":555.03,"stop":586.963,"duration":31.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":586.963,"stop":587.447,"duration":0.48},{"text":"Did the guidelines or policy statement was 18-cents or --","start":587.447,"stop":590.362,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"The policy statement guideline was 18 cents.","start":590.362,"stop":594.658,"duration":4.3},{"text":"The Commission in its opinion in this case fixed the in-line prize at 16 cents and it deferred for later consideration the question of whether it should order of refunds with the respect to most of the temporary authorizations involved because these temporaries did not have an expressed warning that refunds might be issued in connection with the permanent certificate.","start":594.658,"stop":628.654,"duration":34},{"text":"The reason for the deferral was that in an earlier case, the Commission had held that in its view it would not be equitable to require the producers, although they had charged excess amounts during the temporary authorization to make refunds, simply on the ground that there had been no expressed warning of this possibility.","start":628.654,"stop":653.537,"duration":24.88},{"text":"The Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit, in the case which has been referred to in the briefs of the Skelly case decided that the Commission in those circumstances would as the Commission itself believed have the power to order refunds and that in addition, the -- in its view, the Commission had not adequately considered the equitable factors relating to refunds.","start":653.537,"stop":681.205,"duration":27.67},{"text":"This decision was decided by the Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit just about two month before the Commission's decision in Amerada and since the Court had told the Commission that it should give more penetrating analysis of the equitable considerations, the Commission followed that same course here.","start":681.205,"stop":704.803,"duration":23.6},{"text":"On review, the Tenth Circuit stating its view that the Commission would have no power to order any refunds in these circumstances said that the Commission had erred in deferring the refund question.","start":704.803,"stop":722.365,"duration":17.56},{"text":"But it did find that the Commission's determination of the 16-cent in-line price was properly supported.","start":722.365,"stop":730.618,"duration":8.25},{"text":"In so doing, it rejected tax by producers that this 16-cent price was too low and also the contentions of the New York Commission and various eastern distributors whom we have referred to as the “seaboard interests” collectively, their contentions that the line should have been no more than 15 cents.","start":730.618,"stop":755.348,"duration":24.73},{"text":"During the pendency of the Tenth Circuit proceedings, the Commission in fact concluded the deferred refund proceeding and held that, with very limited exceptions, the producers as an equitable matter should make refunds of all the amounts in excess of the 16-cent in-line price that the Commission had determined.","start":755.348,"stop":780.384,"duration":25.04}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But Mr. Schiff, before that, had the Commission actually denied a -- some sort of a request from distributor groups to alter the temporary certificates to provide for the refund obligation?","start":780.384,"stop":795.226,"duration":14.84}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think in --","start":795.226,"stop":796.79,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"In this very case -- in these -- on","start":796.79,"stop":798.08,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"In these very cases and on -- I think the order is in early 1963, the Commission had denied a request by the some of the interveners to impose a condition for refunds.","start":798.08,"stop":812.3,"duration":14.22}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now would you -- would you suggest that -- or did the Court of Appeals suggest that the -- that the Commission does not have the power to issue a temporary certificate without the obligation for refund?","start":812.3,"stop":827.611,"duration":15.31},{"text":"Let's assume the circuit here said it expressly there should be no obligation to refund.","start":827.611,"stop":836.581,"duration":8.97}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- well I -- I believe that even -- I'm not sure Mr. Justice White, in these cases --","start":836.581,"stop":850.026,"duration":13.44}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Because that's really what you have here, isn't it?","start":850.026,"stop":851.684,"duration":1.66},{"text":"Is that the Commission saying, “We refused to modify these certificates to provide for an expressed -- to expressly provide for refund because we don't think it would -- we don't intend to have and make a refund”, that what they've said.","start":851.684,"stop":865.317,"duration":13.63}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Commission in effect in that order was saying that we have previously expressed our views in the Skelly case that it would not be equitable to order refunds in the absence of an expressed condition, and we don't think that we should change the nature or the condition after the service under the temporary had already commenced.","start":865.317,"stop":889.889,"duration":24.57}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"At least they --","start":889.889,"stop":890.327,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Now --","start":890.327,"stop":890.759,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"They said that by -- with these temporary certificates, we haven't -- we have not intended and don't intend to require a refund?","start":890.759,"stop":897.901,"duration":7.14}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"I think there's no question, but that was what the Commission was saying.","start":897.901,"stop":902.382,"duration":4.48},{"text":"Even though there is some language in the -- in all of these temporary authorizations which said that the grant of the temporary authorization with -- is without prejudice to the final disposition of the rate questions and --","start":902.382,"stop":918.48,"duration":16.1}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you -- you don't suggest that the Commission wouldn't have the power to --","start":918.48,"stop":923.069,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it is our -- it is our -- well, that it would have the power to say, “We will not order refunds” I think the thrust of these -- the opinions of the District of Columbia Circuit and of the D.C. and of the Fifth Circuit is that at least in the present circumstances, in the way these temporaries are issued without any notice are -- and for the benefit of the producers who are claiming that they -- they have to flare their gas that their gas maybe drained, these are their own representations of emergency.","start":923.069,"stop":963.341,"duration":40.27},{"text":"I think in these circumstances that the -- it is implicit in our decision that in these circumstances, we cannot impose -- we can't relieve the producers of a refund obligation.","start":963.341,"stop":980.622,"duration":17.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But the point is -- in that would you find in the Court of Appeals' decision in D.C. and in the Fifth Circuit?","start":980.622,"stop":988.442,"duration":7.82}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that --","start":988.442,"stop":989.01,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a point of view which the Commission didn't share until they announced this, is that right?","start":989.01,"stop":994.968,"duration":5.96}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commission was -- before that had never -- has never said it could not order refunds even in those circumstances.","start":994.968,"stop":1005.92,"duration":10.95},{"text":"Well, let me -- if I may describe the problem that arose or the situation that developed.","start":1005.92,"stop":1018.097,"duration":12.18},{"text":"The Commission in some instances, in issuing these temporary authorizations did impose express refund conditions and in others it did not impose expressed refund conditions.","start":1018.097,"stop":1034.087,"duration":15.99},{"text":"In 1959, the Tenth Circuit in the Sunray case set aside the Commission temporary authorization where the Commission had imposed a refund obligation.","start":1034.087,"stop":1049.877,"duration":15.79},{"text":"And it said, it decided on the ground that the obligation was too indefinite because the Commission said you may have to make refunds down to the certificate price that we ultimately determined.","start":1049.877,"stop":1064.746,"duration":14.87},{"text":"And the Tenth Circuit seemed to take the view that the Commission would have to put a floor in on any refund condition that it might impose.","start":1064.746,"stop":1074.156,"duration":9.41},{"text":"Thereafter, the Commission in most instances, at least where the price was at the level that the Commission viewed to be the appropriate guideline price did not insert any refund conditions although it did include in their certificates the warning that this price is -- or these temporaries are without prejudice to what the Commission might ultimately do.","start":1074.156,"stop":1100.861,"duration":26.71},{"text":"But there was never any expressed statement by the Commission at any time that it could not order refunds in these circumstances.","start":1100.861,"stop":1110.008,"duration":9.15},{"text":"And indeed when this issue was first decided, I think in the Skelly case, the Commission said, “We don't think it would be equitable because we hadn't given you notice”, and of course there was this course of conduct only Commission which -- the Commission in these cases has acknowledges, lead the producers to think that they might not have to make refunds.","start":1110.008,"stop":1136.744,"duration":26.74},{"text":"But we don't think that this goes to the power of the Commission to order refunds.","start":1136.744,"stop":1141.467,"duration":4.72},{"text":"At most, we think, it goes to the question of whether it is equitable to require them to make refunds and that before the producers can be -- or that the mere fact of reliance doesn't prove that there has been -- and doesn't even show that there has been any detrimental reliance thereon.","start":1141.467,"stop":1164.986,"duration":23.52},{"text":"On the other hand, the consumers for whom the Act is -- for whose protection the Act was primarily adopted have had no notice before these temporaries are even issued.","start":1164.986,"stop":1179.7,"duration":14.71},{"text":"Now, in that respect, at the time of this February 5th order, Justice White, the temporaries had already been issued, the service had already commenced.","start":1179.7,"stop":1193.143,"duration":13.44}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And those who didn't -- haven't had notice came in and asked that they can --","start":1193.143,"stop":1196.692,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they asked that prospectively that there'd be a refund condition imposed and the Commission adhering to its view in the Skelly case that no, we don't think we should change it.","start":1196.692,"stop":1208.612,"duration":11.92},{"text":"But, this wouldn't have given the producers the option, for example that the Tenth Circuit had said in Sunray, they should have by being able to reject the certificate if they didn't like the terms and conditions.","start":1208.612,"stop":1220.322,"duration":11.71},{"text":"We would merely have been putting in something supplemental and at that point, I don't think that the Commission's grant or denial of the motion would have very much legal significance.","start":1220.322,"stop":1236.259,"duration":15.94},{"text":"If the Commission had granted the -- had modified it, of course I think it would have cutoff any equitable argument that the producer should thereafter not have to make refunds.","start":1236.259,"stop":1246.659,"duration":10.4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, at least I gather then the Commission's views of whether it's equitable or not had changed to some extent.","start":1246.659,"stop":1254.389,"duration":7.73}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that is certainly true.","start":1254.389,"stop":1257.383,"duration":2.99},{"text":"That in light of the -- the --","start":1257.383,"stop":1262.427,"duration":5.04}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"With some help from the courts?","start":1262.427,"stop":1263.993,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1263.993,"stop":1264.642,"duration":0.65},{"text":"That is very, very much so.","start":1264.642,"stop":1269.41,"duration":4.77},{"text":"But then, this is the -- I think the story of all of everything in these in-line proceedings that's been a constant course of Commission decisions and approval by the Court in some instance, disapproval and as these cases as well as two other cases which are pending on certiorari petitions that this point show that the lower courts have been totally at odds with each other and in some instance with the Commission and obviously in others is not.","start":1269.41,"stop":1312.307,"duration":42.9},{"text":"The -- I think as long as I have been discussing the refund issue to this extent, I will proceed with that and connote that in the other two cases involved here, involving the other two districts and the one which came up from the District of Columbia Circuit, there was no discussion of the refund question except to say that the deferral of the refund question there was appropriate.","start":1312.307,"stop":1339.867,"duration":27.56},{"text":"And I will get back to those in discussing the issues on the merits.","start":1339.867,"stop":1345.092,"duration":5.23},{"text":"In our view, the -- we believe that the Commission's power to order refunds in this case is very much the same issue that this Court decided in 1965 in the Callery case.","start":1345.092,"stop":1361.297,"duration":16.2},{"text":"In the Callery case, the Commission had originally issued permanent certificates of public convenience and necessity at the level of about 22 cents and above.","start":1361.297,"stop":1375.654,"duration":14.36},{"text":"This was the level which had been disapproved in the earlier CATCO case.","start":1375.654,"stop":1382.039,"duration":6.38},{"text":"The Commission's decisions in these cases were set aside both by summary reversal in one instance by this Court and by a series a Court of Appeals decisions holding that the Commission hadn't adequately considered the price question.","start":1382.039,"stop":1401.258,"duration":19.22},{"text":"On remand from those cases, the Commission found that the appropriate in-line price was 20 cents.","start":1401.258,"stop":1409.514,"duration":8.26},{"text":"However, in the meantime, the producers had been selling their gas under these permanent certificates they had started after the hearing and after the certificate order.","start":1409.514,"stop":1420.43,"duration":10.92},{"text":"But with knowledge that there was going to be Court review or that it had not in fact been instituted.","start":1420.43,"stop":1428.223,"duration":7.79},{"text":"There was no condition inserted or given by either the Commission or the courts prior to the time that they commend service.","start":1428.223,"stop":1439.126,"duration":10.9},{"text":"The Commission ordered the refunds down to the price ultimately found to be the appropriate in-line price.","start":1439.126,"stop":1447.179,"duration":8.05},{"text":"It was argued in that case the Commission had no power to order refunds because we lack reparations authority.","start":1447.179,"stop":1455.982,"duration":8.8},{"text":"The Court held, however, in agreeing with the Commission that the lack or reparations authority does not apply to a situation where the order under which rates are collected is in itself not a final order.","start":1455.982,"stop":1473.906,"duration":17.92},{"text":"Now, in Callery, it is true that the order was subject to Court review.","start":1473.906,"stop":1480.7,"duration":6.79},{"text":"In this instance, we do not believe that these temporary authorizations which are issued on ex parte basis on the basis of producer representations of emergency without any notice or hearing and without any realistic opportunity to obtain court review that the temporaries have any greater claim to finality than did the certificates under which service was rendered in the cases involved in the Callery case.","start":1480.7,"stop":1512.919,"duration":32.22},{"text":"If anything, there's even less claim to finality here.","start":1512.919,"stop":1517.573,"duration":4.65},{"text":"The argument which seems to the contrary that is pressed is of temporary authorizations can be reviewed.","start":1517.573,"stop":1527.822,"duration":10.25},{"text":"And of course, there have been a number of cases in which temporaries have been reviewed and generally, at the instance of the producers themselves whether not been satisfied with the condition -- price reduction conditions or other conditions that the Commission has imposed.","start":1527.822,"stop":1545.144,"duration":17.32},{"text":"There has been one instance where the New York Commission obtained review of temporary authorizations.","start":1545.144,"stop":1553.024,"duration":7.88},{"text":"Its challenge was principally that we had no power to issue temporary authorizations at all.","start":1553.024,"stop":1560.878,"duration":7.85},{"text":"The New York commend the District of Columbia Circuit and sustained the Commission's power to issue temporary authorizations, it indicated that it if temporaries were going to achieve the objective that they were intended to, of permitting a producer to start service quickly because of these emergencies that do exist in the field and basically they're economic emergencies, that there could be no comprehensive review of a temporary authorization.","start":1560.878,"stop":1594.658,"duration":33.78},{"text":"And of course, there is no actual notice or any formal notice to the -- any of the distributors.","start":1594.658,"stop":1604.289,"duration":9.63},{"text":"If they are careful and keep tabs of what's going on in the public information office at the Commission, there is narrow file, I don't know when they started which shows the temporaries that are issued, but there is no notice to them.","start":1604.289,"stop":1618.974,"duration":14.68},{"text":"There is no opportunity to object.","start":1618.974,"stop":1621.572,"duration":2.6},{"text":"And if there was going to be review, the whole purpose of temporaries could not be achieved.","start":1621.572,"stop":1631.61,"duration":10.04},{"text":"To give finality to the temporaries, we suggest, would convert them into a limited term permanent certificates without any real scrutiny of the -- of them in light of the public interest and we believe that the Callery decision as to the power of the Commission is fully controlling.","start":1631.61,"stop":1655.601,"duration":23.99}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Schiff, is it possible that in the Section 4 or Section 5 proceeding, a company that let's say in Amerada case would get a higher rate?","start":1655.601,"stop":1672.762,"duration":17.16}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it's possible.","start":1672.762,"stop":1675.298,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, that would not relay the fact, would it?","start":1675.298,"stop":1679.927,"duration":4.63}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":1679.927,"stop":1680.561,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose I got a lower rate, would they -- would the Commission have power to require refunds to those who had paid the in-line price?","start":1680.561,"stop":1694.597,"duration":14.04}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the in-line price being the price which has been permanently certificated, my answer is no.","start":1694.597,"stop":1701.149,"duration":6.55},{"text":"That would then be a firm price which the Commission would not -- it couldn't go back for the at least the period prior to the initiation of a -- of an increased rate proceeding.","start":1701.149,"stop":1718.199,"duration":17.05}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Why is that?","start":1718.199,"stop":1719.837,"duration":1.64},{"text":"How do you work that out on the statute?","start":1719.837,"stop":1721.602,"duration":1.77},{"text":"In other words, if you have power to require a refund when you fix an in-line price, why don't you have a power to require refunds when you fixed a price under -- under Section 4 or Section 5 proceeding?","start":1721.602,"stop":1738.58,"duration":16.98}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Commission's rate powers are under Section 5, there are two determinant just and reasonable rates to be charged thereafter.","start":1738.58,"stop":1749.031,"duration":10.45},{"text":"Under Section 4, the Commission has a power to order refunds from the time that a rate become -- goes into effect subject to -- to refund.","start":1749.031,"stop":1762.371,"duration":13.34},{"text":"The -- to order refunds for the period prior that time would under the cases where there has been a final Commission decision be regarded as reparations which this Court in cases relating both to the Federal Power Act and the Natural Gas Act has indicated that the Commission has no reparations authority which is derived from the legislative history of the Act as well.","start":1762.371,"stop":1791.341,"duration":28.97}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's take a company that has -- has had a permanent certificate and now for the fixed in-line prices, affecting that company, is that right?","start":1791.341,"stop":1805.481,"duration":14.14}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"No, let's had -- the company would have had temporary authorization and then we would fix the in-line price which would be the permanent certificate price.","start":1805.481,"stop":1812.458,"duration":6.98}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"But none of the companies affected by this order has a permanent certificate?","start":1812.458,"stop":1817.569,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they do under the orders which the Commission has issued and which are under review.","start":1817.569,"stop":1823.758,"duration":6.19}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I thought.","start":1823.758,"stop":1825.82,"duration":2.06},{"text":"And -- but even there, you say that the Commission has power to order a refund?","start":1825.82,"stop":1832.976,"duration":7.16}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the power that we -- to refund that we exercised in this case was at the time that we issued the permanent certificates in these cases, we said that you should make refunds for the period of time during which you are collecting and selling under your temporary authorization.","start":1832.976,"stop":1855.534,"duration":22.56},{"text":"We --","start":1855.534,"stop":1855.669,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you say that -- well, let me see.","start":1855.669,"stop":1857.676,"duration":2.01},{"text":"I guess I don't understand this.","start":1857.676,"stop":1860.075,"duration":2.4},{"text":"Is it your position that just as soon as -- as the Commission -- does the Commission say that as soon as a permanent certificate is issued, the power to order refunds ceases?","start":1860.075,"stop":1873.661,"duration":13.59}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Once a permanent certificate is at least finally approved by the Courts, the power to issue -- to go behind that rate ceases.","start":1873.661,"stop":1885.606,"duration":11.94}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless you reserve some power in it?","start":1885.606,"stop":1888.376,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless we reserve some power --","start":1888.376,"stop":1889.49,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But you --","start":1889.49,"stop":1890.434,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"-- except --","start":1890.434,"stop":1890.558,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But you put a condition on subject to refund?","start":1890.558,"stop":1893.068,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"In the permanent cert --","start":1893.068,"stop":1893.368,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- because of just and reasonable -- yes.","start":1893.368,"stop":1895.252,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I'm sure that we can, in the permanent certificate but --","start":1895.252,"stop":1898.489,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you do it?","start":1898.489,"stop":1899.928,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"On the permanent certificate -- well there have been some -- and not in the producer cases.","start":1899.928,"stop":1907.746,"duration":7.82},{"text":"We have imposed some price conditions even on permanent certificates especially pipelines that --","start":1907.746,"stop":1914.879,"duration":7.13}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Pipeline?","start":1914.879,"stop":1914.938,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but this is subject to future revision.","start":1914.938,"stop":1916.918,"duration":1.98},{"text":"But --","start":1916.918,"stop":1917.052,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"From --","start":1917.052,"stop":1917.349,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the specific kind of condition that you mentioned, no.","start":1917.349,"stop":1921.966,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"So that all we have to concern ourselves with here is companies that have received a temporary certificate so far as the refund question is concerned?","start":1921.966,"stop":1933.2,"duration":11.23}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":1933.2,"stop":1943.044,"duration":9.84},{"text":"As I'm -- as I indicated that the -- we think that the Tenth Circuit was plainly incorrect in finding that the Commission had no power to order refunds on grounds of finality.","start":1943.044,"stop":1961.191,"duration":18.15},{"text":"The Tenth Circuit although it alleged not to pass on the equities of the situation, also held in saying that the Commission had no power to order refund.","start":1961.191,"stop":1971.948,"duration":10.76},{"text":"It said that in its view for the good of the public, the consumers, the distributors, the pipelines and the producers, certainty and stability are prime importance.","start":1971.948,"stop":1983.456,"duration":11.51},{"text":"And it also stated in its opinion that the repricing of gas without warning cannot help but have a severe impact on the operations of the producer.","start":1983.456,"stop":1996.437,"duration":12.98},{"text":"It seems to us that these factors to the extent, they are relevant as to whether refunds should be required or not, relate not to the Commission's power but to the -- the equities of the circumstances.","start":1996.437,"stop":2010.973,"duration":14.54},{"text":"And that this is a question which the Commission should be allowed to pass on in the first instance and which as a matter of fact, the Commission did pass on in the separate proceeding.","start":2010.973,"stop":2025.646,"duration":14.67},{"text":"And at that time, the producers in the Commission's view made no showing of being harmed by not having had notice of the refund condition.","start":2025.646,"stop":2037.386,"duration":11.74},{"text":"The Commission assumed that they could properly -- had properly relied on the Commission's own course of conduct in the thinking that they would not make refunds.","start":2037.386,"stop":2046.292,"duration":8.91},{"text":"But the Commission found that there were only two situations where the producers had shown harm.","start":2046.292,"stop":2054.136,"duration":7.84},{"text":"One was that the producers had paid out royalties with respect to the difference between the in-line price and the higher price being collected.","start":2054.136,"stop":2064.123,"duration":9.99},{"text":"And it appeared that even if these royalties -- this amount could be recouped from the royalty owners, that the practicalities of such recoupment would be prohibitive.","start":2064.123,"stop":2081.065,"duration":16.94},{"text":"It also appeared that in some instances it might not be possible to recover state production taxes paid to the State of Texas although there would be a possibility of setoff where they were continuing sales to the extent that such setoff was not possible, the Commission held that producers should be relieved of any obligation to make refunds as to those amounts.","start":2081.065,"stop":2108.852,"duration":27.79},{"text":"In fact, these amounts are less than the -- or probably about an eighth of the total amount that of the excess collections.","start":2108.852,"stop":2120.461,"duration":11.61},{"text":"Other than that, there were various allegations by the producers that the -- their financial stability would be affected and that they shouldn't be required to order refunds because of the adverse effects on budgeting and planning.","start":2120.461,"stop":2136.194,"duration":15.73},{"text":"And in the Commission's view, it was difficult to understand how in reliance on the transitory nature of these temporaries, that any real long-range commitments could be made with respect to -- on that basis.","start":2136.194,"stop":2152.48,"duration":16.29},{"text":"It also did not think that there would be any refund themselves, would have any significant impact on the operation of producers.","start":2152.48,"stop":2162.237,"duration":9.76},{"text":"However, it did recognized expressly in another case which came out about the same time is these, that if a producer could demonstrate that by making a large refund, the smaller producer would have to make a large refund and that this would cause him serious present difficulties, that the Commission would permit this to be refunded over a period of time, that it had no intention or desire to use the refunding process to put any company into bankruptcy or other dire restraints.","start":2162.237,"stop":2198.12,"duration":35.88},{"text":"But unless this was shown which hasn't been shown at any of the cases at the dockets before this Court, the Commission felt that this did not provide a reason for excusing the refunds or the excess amounts collected when if judged in the context that the consumers during this period of time have been paying excess amounts of money.","start":2198.12,"stop":2225.438,"duration":27.32},{"text":"The -- I do wished to urge, the Tenth Circuit did not pass on the reasonableness of the Commission's assessment of the equities because in its view, the Commission simply had no power to order refunds and the assessment of the equities came up in a second proceeding.","start":2225.438,"stop":2248.528,"duration":23.09},{"text":"We have urged in our petition and in our brief that the Court decide this issue now even though the Tenth Circuit has not passed on it.","start":2248.528,"stop":2257.134,"duration":8.61},{"text":"I suggest that this is especially appropriate because this question of power as viewed by the Tenth Circuit and the question of the equities seems to be closely interrelated.","start":2257.134,"stop":2269.299,"duration":12.16}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the total refund figure has been?","start":2269.299,"stop":2274.136,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Our estimate is that for the period prior to the Commission's order or orders, not just here but also in -- on the cases relating the South Louisiana and another case involving the Texas Gulf Coast, both of which are the cases are pending on certiorari petitions, that under the Commission's order, the refund obligations would be in the neighborhood of $10 million, this would be increased perhaps by an equivalent amount but I think by somewhat less depending on the disposition of the price question.","start":2274.136,"stop":2315.728,"duration":41.59},{"text":"And I'd like -- I'd now liked to turn to the price level question.","start":2315.728,"stop":2327.128,"duration":11.4},{"text":"I've indicated that the Tenth Circuit sustained the Commission's determination of 16-cent in-line price.","start":2327.128,"stop":2334.733,"duration":7.61},{"text":"The District of Columbia Circuit dealing with the proceedings coming up from the two other Texas Gulf Coast areas thought that the Commission's -- in both of those areas, the Commission had sales relating both to the period before the Policy Statement and for the period after the Policy Statement.","start":2334.733,"stop":2360.249,"duration":25.52},{"text":"For the pre-Policy Statement period in Texas District 2, it found an in-line price of 15 cents which is not the issue here are at all.","start":2360.249,"stop":2372.562,"duration":12.31},{"text":"And for the periods subsequent to the Policy Statement for that area, it's on the 16-cent in-line price.","start":2372.562,"stop":2380.997,"duration":8.43},{"text":"This is challenged by the “seaboard interests” and the Commission's decision in this respect that were set aside by the District of Columbia Circuit.","start":2380.997,"stop":2390.704,"duration":9.71},{"text":"Similarly, in the Texas District 3 which is the part of the Gulf Coast which is adjacent to South Louisiana, the Commission found a 16-cent pre-Policy Statement in-line price which I may say was in reaffirmance of earlier decisions on this point.","start":2390.704,"stop":2410.612,"duration":19.91},{"text":"That price is challenged by the superior oil companies being too low.","start":2410.612,"stop":2417.126,"duration":6.51},{"text":"And for the post-Policy Statement period, the Commission found an in-line price of 17 cents which is challenged by the “seaboard interest” as being too high and by the Superior Oil Company as being too low.","start":2417.126,"stop":2436.02,"duration":18.89},{"text":"The question of price is as the Commission has recognized, at least since this Court's decision in 1959 in the Callery -- in the CATCO case, a question of the major importance in our producer certificate cases.","start":2436.02,"stop":2459.269,"duration":23.25},{"text":"In line with that -- this Court's decision, however, it's been recognized that the determination of the proper price at which sales can commence should be done in a expeditious type of proceeding and not in a just and reasonable -- not as in a case involving the determination of just and reasonable rates.","start":2459.269,"stop":2482.396,"duration":23.13},{"text":"The -- the objective is to -- if the price is too high is to reduce it quickly pending further consideration of what the just and reasonable price may be.","start":2482.396,"stop":2496.338,"duration":13.94},{"text":"So the problem faced in these cases is how to determine the price line for the interim period that is fair and reasonable while avoiding protracted proceedings that necessarily accompany the determination of just and reasonable rates.","start":2496.338,"stop":2515.067,"duration":18.73},{"text":"The Commission has utilized a in-line pricing approach which was fashioned principally on the basis of the teachings of the Ninth Circuit in the case of United Gas Improvement Company against Federal Power Commission which was decided in 1960 and has been -- was at that time followed by three other Courts of Appeals.","start":2515.067,"stop":2543.732,"duration":28.66},{"text":"I think that case pretty well sets forth the standards have been followed.","start":2543.732,"stop":2548.826,"duration":5.09},{"text":"There the Ninth Circuit stated that the price line is intended to reflect current conditions in the industry.","start":2548.826,"stop":2557.621,"duration":8.8},{"text":"Therefore, comparable prices upon which it is based must be prices under which a substantial amount of natural gas presently moves in interstate commerce.","start":2557.621,"stop":2569.877,"duration":12.26},{"text":"Now, all the Court cases since that time with the exception of the District of Columbia Circuit in this case, including this Court in Callery have recognized that this in-line price should reflect current market conditions.","start":2569.877,"stop":2589.704,"duration":19.83},{"text":"At the same time, the Ninth Circuit in what is referred to as the UGI case held that the Commission could not simply look at the prices -- contemporaneous prices at -- in the area without recognizing that some of those prices were in itself the result of improper Commission action.","start":2589.704,"stop":2612.653,"duration":22.95},{"text":"But specifically, what had occurred in the UGI cases was that the Commission had approved 22-cent prices in a very -- in various prior proceedings and then it looked at those prices to approve the price involved in that case.","start":2612.653,"stop":2637.097,"duration":24.44},{"text":"But the earlier 22-cent prices had all resulted and had all leapfrogged up to that level because of the Commission's improper decision in the CATCO case where it had approved price of about 21-and-a-half cents even though before that time, all the prices in the area was substantially less.","start":2637.097,"stop":2659.651,"duration":22.55},{"text":"So in the UGI case, the Court formulated what's been known as the suspect price stock during that the Commission cannot simply simply accept its face value prices which appeared to have leapfrogged as result of prior Commission errors.","start":2659.651,"stop":2683.469,"duration":23.82},{"text":"But in that case, the Ninth Circuit also rejected a contention by the distributor groups that the Commission couldn't consider any prices other than those which had received full Commission approval in a -- in a adjudicated hearing type of case.","start":2683.469,"stop":2706.595,"duration":23.13},{"text":"What they were thinking of there was that in many instances, that there is no objection, the Commission will issue permanent certificates at the prices that it deems appropriate.","start":2706.595,"stop":2717.288,"duration":10.69},{"text":"The Ninth Circuit said if you couldn't look at any of those prices, you would simply have a rollback of prices because there would might not be any substantial volumes of gas that you could look at to determine what the current market conditions were.","start":2717.288,"stop":2738.163,"duration":20.88},{"text":"Now, following the UGI cases, the Commission itself never treated the suspect price doctrine as the case which precluded the Commission from giving any effect to prices which had not been finally approved.","start":2738.163,"stop":2759.156,"duration":20.99},{"text":"Thus, in the Skelly case which I've referred to in connection in one of the refund question, the Commission stated that it had given some or be it discounted way to temporary authorizations.","start":2759.156,"stop":2773.893,"duration":14.74},{"text":"But until the cases that at least the Amerada case here involved, most of the early cases there had in fact been substantial volumes of gas that had moved at prices that near the -- near the line that Commission determined.","start":2773.893,"stop":2793.873,"duration":19.98},{"text":"There are a fair number of non-suspected prices.","start":2793.873,"stop":2797.231,"duration":3.36},{"text":"In Amerada, the situation was quite different, only about 90 -- about 90% of the gas in the area during the period of time covered by the contracts at issue was flowing under temporary certificates, and most of these were prices from 16 to 18 cents.","start":2797.231,"stop":2825.373,"duration":28.14},{"text":"There were a few prices, few sales but not really very small volumes which are at lower prices.","start":2825.373,"stop":2831.378,"duration":6.01},{"text":"The reason for this is that the “seaboard interests” during this period of time were challenging all prices above the 14-and-a-half to 15-cent levels, so the Commission foreclosed from issuing permanent certificates and a situation developed where the Commission would be unable to make any assessment of current conditions on the basis of the contract prices in the area.","start":2831.378,"stop":2864.912,"duration":33.53},{"text":"Because no substantial volumes of gas could be looked at, that is if we accepted the position of the “seaboard interests”.","start":2864.912,"stop":2873.638,"duration":8.73},{"text":"Now, in this connection, I may add that the Commission with the approval of this Court held that the cost evidence should not be considered in these cases because that would simply preclude the possibility of an in-line determination before the just and reasonable determination.","start":2873.638,"stop":2893.906,"duration":20.27},{"text":"The Commission did not in these circumstances think it appropriate to ignore temporary authorizations or some of the contract prices.","start":2893.906,"stop":2906.421,"duration":12.51},{"text":"But it took a middle course, it looked at all the market contract price evidence in the area and it carefully examined them.","start":2906.421,"stop":2920.744,"duration":14.32},{"text":"It looked that the trends between the period before the Policy Statement and the period after the Policy Statement and it discounted the effect of the pricing because it recognized as had the Court in the UGI case that some of the prices in the area were obviously the result of market distortions stemming, one, from the fact that the pipeline cost -- pipeline purchases are have -- have imperfect bargaining motivations to keep the prices down and secondly that there had been some Commission action which may have tended to move up prices.","start":2920.744,"stop":2965.257,"duration":44.51},{"text":"So, on other hand, it also did not think it appropriate to base its in-line determination only on those prices to which the consumer interests had not objected because if it had done that, it would simply have been rubberstamping one individual parties or one group of parties' view as to what the market conditions should be.","start":2965.257,"stop":2988.305,"duration":23.05},{"text":"And in the Commission's view, the assessment on a balance basis should be made by the Neutral Regulatory Agency which has been assigned this task by the Congress.","start":2988.305,"stop":3002.275,"duration":13.97}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"These temporary authorizations that -- which we spoke of, these temporary certificates, they are granted on ex parte application and how much of the hearing and how much time and so on?","start":3002.275,"stop":3016.277,"duration":14}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no hearing at all.","start":3016.277,"stop":3017.669,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"None at all?","start":3017.669,"stop":3018.501,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"None at all.","start":3018.501,"stop":3019.954,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It's an ex parte application.","start":3019.954,"stop":3021.368,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"It's an application, some of which are in the record here which says we have a drainage problem.","start":3021.368,"stop":3027.675,"duration":6.31}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It's an allegation of some kind of an emergency?","start":3027.675,"stop":3029.587,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Some kind of economic emergency.","start":3029.587,"stop":3031.49,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And then, is there a price specified?","start":3031.49,"stop":3034.927,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, in the temporary (Voice Overlap).","start":3034.927,"stop":3035.913,"duration":0.99},{"text":"Well, the Commission will -- if the price is above what the Commission has said to be the guideline price, the Commission will condition it down.","start":3035.913,"stop":3046.736,"duration":10.82},{"text":"It will not mention price at all in its order if the price is within those guidelines.","start":3046.736,"stop":3054.068,"duration":7.33}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But now, which guidelines are --","start":3054.068,"stop":3055.526,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"The Policy Statement guidelines or -- well, those are the ones that have -- that would apply.","start":3055.526,"stop":3060.393,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The Policy Statement would --","start":3060.393,"stop":3061.445,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3061.445,"stop":3061.552,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- be applicable here.","start":3061.552,"stop":3062.35,"duration":0.8},{"text":"So what -- that was 18 cents?","start":3062.35,"stop":3063.389,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it was 18 cents and -- until 1962.","start":3063.389,"stop":3067.149,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":3067.149,"stop":3068.071,"duration":0.92},{"text":"So that anything 18 cents or below would have been --","start":3068.071,"stop":3073.1,"duration":5.03}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"It would --","start":3073.1,"stop":3073.308,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- approved?","start":3073.308,"stop":3073.332,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"-- have been temporary certificate.","start":3073.332,"stop":3073.955,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It would have been approved on a temporary certificate assuming that the Commission accepted the allegation of the emergency as sufficient to authorize the issuance of such temporary certificate, is that right?","start":3073.955,"stop":3084.805,"duration":10.85}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":3084.805,"stop":3085.94,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be automatically approved so far as price went if it was 18 cents and below, is that fair to say?","start":3085.94,"stop":3092.868,"duration":6.93}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3092.868,"stop":3097.5,"duration":4.63}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And that would stick to 16 cents.","start":3097.5,"stop":3100.302,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Justice White.","start":3100.302,"stop":3104.116,"duration":3.81},{"text":"The District of Columbia Circuit in holding that the Commission had improperly looked at these temporary authorizations in two of the areas involved, based its decision in good part on the view that current market conditions were simply irrelevant and it derived that interpretation from the fact that in this Court in Callery had affirmed the exclusion of cost in economic evidence.","start":3104.116,"stop":3145.63,"duration":41.51},{"text":"But it overlooked the fact that that exclusion was to permit the -- was for administrative purposes.","start":3145.63,"stop":3160.531,"duration":14.9},{"text":"That it was a matter of administrative necessity that the Commission not look at this evidence which the Commission itself after a series of hearings had concluded would not be useful unless they were expanded into full blown rate proceedings.","start":3160.531,"stop":3174.742,"duration":14.21},{"text":"Certainly nothing in the Commission's opinion or in this Court's opinion in Callery that at all suggests that the line should not be based on current conditions.","start":3174.742,"stop":3185.042,"duration":10.3},{"text":"To the contrary, this Court's opinion in Callery says that the line appropriately relates to contemporaneous sales in the area.","start":3185.042,"stop":3198.337,"duration":13.3},{"text":"The District of Columbia Circuit also based its decision in part on the fact that it thought that they would -- that even though they might be a freeze in the line under its view which it recognized that there might be, that the producers would be protected by being able to avail themselves of the right to file increased rates after the date of the Commission's order.","start":3198.337,"stop":3228.633,"duration":30.3},{"text":"But we think that this approach of the Court relying on the increased rate provisions of the Act is not only unfair to the producers for reasons that I believe the producer counsels will explain some detail.","start":3228.633,"stop":3247.574,"duration":18.94},{"text":"But that it -- this would not have implemented the interests of the consumer in the best way possible in our view.","start":3247.574,"stop":3256.644,"duration":9.07},{"text":"The one purpose of in-line pricing was to discourage the filing of increased rates.","start":3256.644,"stop":3263.284,"duration":6.64},{"text":"And the Commission experienced at the time of the decisions in these cases was that if the Commission made an in-line determination which might reasonably be expected to reflect market conditions, producers would not file for increased rates thereafter at this in-line price.","start":3263.284,"stop":3285.93,"duration":22.65},{"text":"On the other hand, if there were an artificially low in-line price, predicated solely on the fact that increased rates could be filed any event, there were the substantial chance that thereafter there would be increased rate filings even higher levels.","start":3285.93,"stop":3302.094,"duration":16.16},{"text":"And of course those would be passed on to the consumers and while there is a refund remedy under the Act and while we think this is useful, this Court has repeatedly agreed with us that the protection to consumers from refunds is far from perfect.","start":3302.094,"stop":3325.469,"duration":23.38},{"text":"Now, I want to make it very clear that the Commission in these -- making these various in-line determinations recognized that it could not simply accept the contract prices, the temporarily certificated prices at face value.","start":3325.469,"stop":3343.305,"duration":17.84},{"text":"This had been the voice of the Commission's orders in the UGI cases which had been referred.","start":3343.305,"stop":3349.054,"duration":5.75},{"text":"But the Commission in these cases did not accept them at face value.","start":3349.054,"stop":3355.425,"duration":6.37},{"text":"For example, in Amerada, the Commission found that the weighted contract average of all the post-Policy Statement prices was about 17.2 cents and it found that the much of the gas was flowing up -- at prices up to 18 cents.","start":3355.425,"stop":3378.202,"duration":22.78},{"text":"But the in-line price that the Commission determined was 16 cents.","start":3378.202,"stop":3384.519,"duration":6.32},{"text":"Again, in Texas District 3 in the Sinclair case which I may say is likely different because in that case, there were in fact substantial volumes of gas and the majority of the gas was flowing under permanent certificates.","start":3384.519,"stop":3402.821,"duration":18.3},{"text":"And the Commission's opinion shows on its face that the Commission looked principally at the permanent certificates.","start":3402.821,"stop":3410.806,"duration":7.99},{"text":"Now, on that instance, there were -- 40% of the gas flowing under permanent certificates was being sold at 18 cents.","start":3410.806,"stop":3420.316,"duration":9.51},{"text":"New York or the “seaboard interests” suggest that this 18-cent price should be suspect because it was at a level that if it had thought about it, it would have objected too, but it didn't object to it at the time that the prices were approved.","start":3420.316,"stop":3438.169,"duration":17.85},{"text":"Yet, the Commission didn't allow an 18-cent line but in this instance it allowed a 17-cent line.","start":3438.169,"stop":3446.61,"duration":8.44},{"text":"In the case where the evidence showed that looking solely at permanent certificates, the weighted average price from the period before the issuance of the Policy Statement to the period after the issuance of the Policy Statement had risen by a cent.","start":3446.61,"stop":3468.049,"duration":21.44},{"text":"Now, there is one further point that I would like to make on these cases and there has been a suggestion in the reply brief of the “seaboard interests” that in someway, the Commission has applied a different standards in the cases relating to the Texas Gulf Coast from the standards that had been applied in cases relating to South Louisiana.","start":3468.049,"stop":3494.001,"duration":25.95},{"text":"And the basis for this suggestion is that in South Louisiana, the Commission in a number of cases has found that the line which was originally determined for the period at which the sales were made in 1956, that's the CATCO sale of 20 cents, has not changed even through the end of 1962.","start":3494.001,"stop":3520.449,"duration":26.45},{"text":"This is perfectly true.","start":3520.449,"stop":3522.312,"duration":1.86},{"text":"But in the last of those cases which was called the Union Texas case before the Commission and the Pan American case in the Tenth Circuit in which is pending here on the refund question principally and also on one price element, the Commission's opinion shows that the Commission there looked at temporary authorizations.","start":3522.312,"stop":3547.668,"duration":25.36},{"text":"It compared the weighted average prices under permanent certificates from -- to the -- in the different years.","start":3547.668,"stop":3555.082,"duration":7.41},{"text":"And it also looked and examined the weighted average price of the temporary authorizations.","start":3555.082,"stop":3562.229,"duration":7.15},{"text":"On the basis of its analysis of the fact in that case, the Commission concluded that the evidence which is the same type of evidence that was considered here simply didn't show a change in the price line.","start":3562.229,"stop":3583.182,"duration":20.95},{"text":"In the Texas Gulf Coast, it's considered appraisal of the evidence there but the same of type of evidence lead it to a different result, because in fact there it concluded that the price line for the periods after the Policy Statement were with, in each of the three areas, they sent higher than the price line that it had determined for the prior period.","start":3583.182,"stop":3608.134,"duration":24.95},{"text":"But obviously, a different result resulting from a reasonable considered assessment of the record in each case doesn't show any inconsistency.","start":3608.134,"stop":3620.917,"duration":12.78}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Schiff, what are you going to do when you do have area rates as a point of reference?","start":3620.917,"stop":3629.438,"duration":8.52},{"text":"You suggested awhile ago that your in-line price should probably be the just and reasonable price?","start":3629.438,"stop":3634.863,"duration":5.42}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in the Permian Basin decision, the Commission said that the -- it would use the just and reasonable price as the in-line price.","start":3634.863,"stop":3645.285,"duration":10.42},{"text":"But also, in a case coming from the Permian Basin, and it's pending in this Court but I don't remember the number.","start":3645.285,"stop":3656.368,"duration":11.08}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, when all the -- when all the area --","start":3656.368,"stop":3657.671,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"We did the same thing.","start":3657.671,"stop":3658.94,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"When all the area rates are finally set or had been set at least initially, will this problem arise again or not?","start":3658.94,"stop":3669.725,"duration":10.78}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't believe so.","start":3669.725,"stop":3671.03,"duration":1.31},{"text":"It -- in the Commission's view, the -- if there is to be any change in the in-line price, it will have to be by showing that there had been some changes in the factors which make up the just and reasonable determination.","start":3671.03,"stop":3686.429,"duration":15.4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So they'll have to be a redetermination of the just and reasonableness before the in-line price is going to go up?","start":3686.429,"stop":3691.99,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, at least as to the prospective just and reasonable price.","start":3691.99,"stop":3695.408,"duration":3.42},{"text":"As you recall, we fixed both an old gas price and the new gas price and new certificates would presumably call for a new gas price which might be adjusted.","start":3695.408,"stop":3705.445,"duration":10.04},{"text":"But that is what the Commission contemplates doing in -- as soon the just and reasonable rates are determined.","start":3705.445,"stop":3712.755,"duration":7.31},{"text":"And in this case, or in these areas, the Commission is no longer setting down anymore in-line proceedings of the type here involved because the just and reasonable -- the cases involving just and reasonable rates relating to the Texas Gulf Coast and South Louisiana had so for advance that it would seemed to be the wise course to let our in-line determination rest on the determination in those area rate proceedings.","start":3712.755,"stop":3749.057,"duration":36.3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And that the -- and if their temporary certificates -- they will just continue in effect?","start":3749.057,"stop":3755.539,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"They will continue in effect and they will be subject to refund.","start":3755.539,"stop":3763.193,"duration":7.65},{"text":"In part, depending on this Court's decision, in part not, the -- all the sales in the South Louisiana area since about the middle of 1964 --","start":3763.193,"stop":3773.878,"duration":10.68}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Express.","start":3773.878,"stop":3774.38,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"-- express refund condition and since early 1967, all temporaries are issued with a refund condition which has a floor of 2 cents below either the guideline price or the in-line price whichever is lower.","start":3774.38,"stop":3795.258,"duration":20.88},{"text":"And the Commission has viewed that that floor would be certainly -- would tend to be low enough not to pose any problems thereafter.","start":3795.258,"stop":3804.332,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in these cases, you were discussing Mr. Justice Fortas, if -- if you're staying in this -- in setting these particular in-lines prices, and then the just and reasonable rates were established in an area proceeding, and those just and reasonable are lower than the in-line price?","start":3804.332,"stop":3827.019,"duration":22.69}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- I may have misspoken myself before you, but I think that question before related to refunds, if the --","start":3827.019,"stop":3834.32,"duration":7.3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I was --","start":3834.32,"stop":3835.232,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"-- if the just and reasonable rate --","start":3835.232,"stop":3836.802,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So does mine.","start":3836.802,"stop":3837.727,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we won't order further refunds in the cases involved here because those sales will then have been permanently certificated.","start":3837.727,"stop":3856.993,"duration":19.27},{"text":"In the Texas District 3 case, the Superior Oil Company makes a number of challenges to the Commission's price line being too high -- too low, excuse me.","start":3856.993,"stop":3873.025,"duration":16.03},{"text":"Principally, they argue that we should have relied on some high-priced gas being sold at 20 cents.","start":3873.025,"stop":3884.408,"duration":11.38},{"text":"As to that argument, the Commission said that we would give some weight to those.","start":3884.408,"stop":3889.911,"duration":5.5},{"text":"But in those cases, the “seaboard interests” I think specifically the New York Commission had been denied intervention the Commission proceedings, it then went to Court, but it chose the wrong the time to challenge its exclusion of interventions and its petition for review was dismissed by the District of Columbia Circuit.","start":3889.911,"stop":3911.862,"duration":21.95},{"text":"Nevertheless, it was apparent to the Commission that those 20-cent prices were higher than the Commission would have allowed or should've allowed at that time that what before this procedural clerk it would not have been allowed.","start":3911.862,"stop":3924.191,"duration":12.33},{"text":"And therefore those prices should certainly not betaken as reflecting the line, in other words, be given the full weight.","start":3924.191,"stop":3932.578,"duration":8.39},{"text":"The Commission gave discounted weight to that.","start":3932.578,"stop":3935.964,"duration":3.39},{"text":"I would like to say that Superior has mad a number of arguments which it did not make to the Commission and it has suggested in its reply brief but these arguments, but we weren't specific, they were generally encompassed within our arguments.","start":3935.964,"stop":3956.379,"duration":20.41},{"text":"We have suggested in our brief that under this Court's interpretation of Section 19 (b) of the Gas Act which requires objections not -- requires all objections that to be raised in Court have to be made specifically in petition for rehearing to the Commission, that in light of those cases, the Superior's objections may not be considered.","start":3956.379,"stop":3984.206,"duration":27.83},{"text":"I don't propose to go into them, as a matter of fact, the objections have far involved in a few other cases which we have referred to in our brief, some of them not considering low price sales, was specifically rejected by the Fifth Circuit.","start":3984.206,"stop":4003.946,"duration":19.74},{"text":"But I do think that -- I want to stress the fact that we think it's important that parties to Commission cases do a price the Commission specifically of the objections that they are urging so that the Commission will be given an opportunity to deal with those in the orders on rehearing and so that if cases do come to Court, the Court rather than being asked to pass on questions without any prior Commission consideration, that it have the Commission's consideration.","start":4003.946,"stop":4042.351,"duration":38.41},{"text":"Of course this Court has viewed that requirement as strict statutory bar to consideration and we would urge that that interpretation be continued.","start":4042.351,"stop":4055.024,"duration":12.67},{"text":"On the in-line question, finally, I think it is fair to say that the Commission recognized that it had a very difficult evidentiary problem.","start":4055.024,"stop":4067.614,"duration":12.59},{"text":"It's perfectly plain that the evidence that it had to consider was far from what might be ideal in showing current market conditions.","start":4067.614,"stop":4077.15,"duration":9.54},{"text":"Obviously, it did not.","start":4077.15,"stop":4078.482,"duration":1.33},{"text":"The ideal evidence has caused an economic evidence which is introduced in the just and reasonable cases if it was going to do its job, it couldn't look at that.","start":4078.482,"stop":4090.616,"duration":12.13},{"text":"But we suggest that the Commission did a careful reasonably considered assessment of the evidence at hand and since it did not consider materials which should have been excluded, we request that the Commission's in-line determination in each of these three cases -- Commission cases be sustained.","start":4090.616,"stop":4116.613,"duration":26},{"text":"Now finally, there is an issue in the two cases arising from the District of Columbia Circuit and this is the issue which has been referred to as the question of need.","start":4116.613,"stop":4133.906,"duration":17.29},{"text":"And the question specifically is whether the Commission in considering each independent producer application must specifically determine on an evidentiary basis in each instance that there is public need for the gas that each producer proposes to sell.","start":4133.906,"stop":4162.468,"duration":28.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That issue has been derived in the permanent certification?","start":4162.468,"stop":4165.483,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that -- that issue was not presented in the -- in the Tenth Circuit case.","start":4165.483,"stop":4171.276,"duration":5.79},{"text":"It has arisen in another case in the -- the Continental case decided by the Fifth Circuit, where the Fifth Circuit sustained the Commission's view that the question of need may should appropriately be considered in pipeline proceedings rather than in the individual producer proceeding.","start":4171.276,"stop":4197.934,"duration":26.66},{"text":"The District of Columbia Circuit seemed to hold that as a theoretical matter, this question of need should be disposed within the producer cases, but as a practical matter, it recognized that really, you couldn't do it in the producer cases and they said that we are not requiring an extensive hearing in each producer case, but that's the -- the Commission should make in its view, references to other cases to informal staff studies, to Policy Statements whenever it decides producer cases.","start":4197.934,"stop":4236.728,"duration":38.79},{"text":"And I may say that while -- we did not seek certiorari on the question.","start":4236.728,"stop":4242.018,"duration":5.29},{"text":"We think that the Court was wrong, but we also thought that administratively, it might be possible for the Commission to comply with what the District of Columbia Circuit had indicated.","start":4242.018,"stop":4256.577,"duration":14.56},{"text":"Although, I will be very frank in saying that we're not sure what useful public interest would be served by doing what the D.C. Circuit has said instead of the Commission's present procedures.","start":4256.577,"stop":4274.817,"duration":18.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Just what exactly did they want you to do?","start":4274.817,"stop":4279.065,"duration":4.25}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the best thing to do is read from the Court's decision which is in Volume 4 of the Joint Appendix.","start":4279.065,"stop":4301.751,"duration":22.69},{"text":"And starting at page 265 from the pagination at the bottom of the --","start":4301.751,"stop":4310.205,"duration":8.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"265?","start":4310.205,"stop":4311.641,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, this is the pagination at the bottom of the page, Justice Black.","start":4311.641,"stop":4320.561,"duration":8.92},{"text":"The Court says that, “Although we remand this case so that the FPC can consider the issue of public need, we recognize an obvious tension between the statutory requirement that it do so and administrative feasibility.","start":4320.561,"stop":4336.564,"duration":16},{"text":"The public convenience in necessity includes many considerations, but there -- if there is to be any effective certification of the producers, the FPC must sometimes stop short of the ideal.","start":4336.564,"stop":4349.659,"duration":13.09},{"text":"It is evident too that the FPC must have great latitude in its choice of procedures.”","start":4349.659,"stop":4355.919,"duration":6.26},{"text":"We are not demanding the FPC hold a long complex hearing in each case -- in each of its many producer application cases.","start":4355.919,"stop":4365.225,"duration":9.31},{"text":"But it does not seem too difficult to have the producer's customers or the pipeline's customers testified by the take-or-pay situation regarding the broader aspects of the nature of the gas business or of conservation, the FPC may consider studies of its staff, may after study issue Policy Statements.","start":4365.225,"stop":4389.628,"duration":24.4},{"text":"And it goes on a little later and says, “Then it would not be necessary to relitigate need in each issue.","start":4389.628,"stop":4395.963,"duration":6.34},{"text":"The FPC need only show that the broad statement or study covers the particular certification before it”.","start":4395.963,"stop":4403.634,"duration":7.67},{"text":"In short, we do not now prescribe any particular method for deciding need, nor, as our discussion of what public need means exhaustive.","start":4403.634,"stop":4416.039,"duration":12.4},{"text":"And it indicates that these decisions should be made before the gas starts coming into the market.","start":4416.039,"stop":4422.283,"duration":6.24},{"text":"And this seems to be -- this is an undesirable objective but the suggestions of the “seaboard interests” and I think in this instance, particularly the New York Commission that this can be met by looking at the need question with respect to producer applications, where most of the sales of previously commenced under temporary authorizations is totally unrealistic.","start":4422.283,"stop":4452.037,"duration":29.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It sounds to me is that the -- that these D.C. Circuit said there, if we're satisfied by the paragraph of the Commission's order?","start":4452.037,"stop":4460.328,"duration":8.29}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this -- yes Justice Harlan and it was for this reason that the Commission did not seek cert even though there seems to be a ostensible conflict between that decision and the decision of the Fifth Circuit which said that if the Commission consider its need, then in the producer cases, considers at the way the New York Commission was urging, that it be considered, it would have to be a full evidentiary hearing.","start":4460.328,"stop":4491.492,"duration":31.16},{"text":"Now, the Fifth Circuit sustained the Commission.","start":4491.492,"stop":4495.623,"duration":4.13},{"text":"The District of Columbia Circuit in effect said put in the paragraph in your order.","start":4495.623,"stop":4500.888,"duration":5.27},{"text":"We thought that we -- we couldn't live with that.","start":4500.888,"stop":4504.356,"duration":3.47},{"text":"And as I say, I don't think it is very useful.","start":4504.356,"stop":4508.439,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How do you view this now?","start":4508.439,"stop":4510.724,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Peter H. Schiff","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this is what I wanted to get to.","start":4510.724,"stop":4514.493,"duration":3.77},{"text":"The -- when gas is sold by producers, it of course has to be picked up by pipelines though jurisdictional facilities.","start":4514.493,"stop":4527.809,"duration":13.32},{"text":"Now, I want to make it perfectly plain at the outset because it may have been somewhat misleading in our brief not every producers sale has a corresponding pipeline certificate proceeding.","start":4527.809,"stop":4545.077,"duration":17.27},{"text":"In this case, we have examined the Hawkins and Sinclair files and I'd say that it -- in about 75% of the gas, there were actually some new pipeline facilities that were needed to pick up the gas involved.","start":4545.077,"stop":4560.253,"duration":15.18},{"text":"Now, the Commission approved gas purchasing facilities in one of several ways.","start":4560.253,"stop":4569.033,"duration":8.78},{"text":"There have -- there are many pipeline expansion cases and frequently of course, these include request to build into a particular field and to purchase particular supplies of gas.","start":4569.033,"stop":4580.826,"duration":11.79},{"text":"In addition to that, there are many -- most of these pipelines have come into the Commission and request what is known as the budget type certificate.","start":4580.826,"stop":4591.387,"duration":10.56},{"text":"Now, under the budget type certificate, the company is authorized to attach new supplies of gas in the following year provided that the facilities themselves are reasonably inexpensive.","start":4591.387,"stop":4609.638,"duration":18.25},{"text":"The -- now the -- however, the Commission's consideration of need is not restricted to these because the Commission requires detailed information to be filed by the pipeline companies with respect to what their -- what gas is being sold throughout the country.","start":4609.638,"stop":4632.968,"duration":23.33},{"text":"The deliverability under these supplies and then -- it's very detailed information which shows where the gas is coming from.","start":4632.968,"stop":4644.035,"duration":11.07},{"text":"The Commission has required this since 1964 and the staff of the Commission examines these reports and is then in the position to determine at least in its view whether the company supply is adequate or inadequate and it has advised, called in the pipelines to try to explain why isn't there enough gas here.","start":4644.035,"stop":4669.674,"duration":25.64},{"text":"In other situations, we have called the pipelines in to explain, why are you paying for gas which you are not taking.","start":4669.674,"stop":4679.17,"duration":9.5},{"text":"These are the prepayments that the New York Commission refers to.","start":4679.17,"stop":4684.101,"duration":4.93},{"text":"So that there is a continuing surveillance by the Commission, all this question of need, both inadequacy and perhaps the oversupply although in the past, to a large extent, the problems are related to insufficient supplies.","start":4684.101,"stop":4704.705,"duration":20.6},{"text":"However, in 1964, the Commission did recognize -- the Commission up to 1964 had a policy that you had to have enough deliverability, enough gas to assure that you could serve your markets for 12 years.","start":4704.705,"stop":4721.687,"duration":16.98},{"text":"This meant that the pipelines would have to go out and buy enough gas to meet this requirement even though they may -- might be taking some gas that they might not need at that particular time.","start":4721.687,"stop":4736.61,"duration":14.92},{"text":"The Commission at the same time that it imposed the reporting requirement, detailed reporting requirement with respect to gas supplies, announced that it was relaxing this firm 12-year deliverability requirement and more recently, this year, it has indicated that as a result of this realization, it appears that the prepayment problem has diminished to some extent because this gives the pipelines greater flexibility.","start":4736.61,"stop":4767.229,"duration":30.62},{"text":"But in essence then, the Commission reviews the supply problem on this informal basis and also in the formal cases and of course, in many of these pipeline expansion cases, it looks at what is needed by the ultimate market.","start":4767.229,"stop":4788.281,"duration":21.05},{"text":"It looks at questions of conservation, of end-use, increasing in the question of whether gas should be used to -- for oil or fuel by electric generation, generating plants, it's an issue which the Commission has to face up to.","start":4788.281,"stop":4808.149,"duration":19.87},{"text":"And in these formal proceedings, it is our view that there is ample opportunity for any of the parties who feel that the gas supplies either inadequate of more than adequate.","start":4808.149,"stop":4821.196,"duration":13.05},{"text":"There's ample opportunity for them to participate and request that the Commission put the consideration into a formal record and that all the parties put the matters into a formal record.","start":4821.196,"stop":4834.973,"duration":13.78},{"text":"It is also perfectly plain that even if the question of need were to be considered in a producer application, that the evidence relating to what the -- for the need for this gas would have to come from the pipelines who would know what their need is and perhaps from the pipelines customers, because plainly, this is not information which -- to which the producers themselves are previewed.","start":4834.973,"stop":4863.601,"duration":28.63},{"text":"And this seems to be conceded but, it says while this isn't too difficult, you can then -- they can call the pipeline witnesses.","start":4863.601,"stop":4873.207,"duration":9.61},{"text":"We suggest that the procedure which the distributors urge which is much broader, I may say, than the procedure which the District of Columbia Circuit seemed to envision, would enable any purchasing customer, any other interested party who would be entitled to intervene in the Commission proceeding to in effect force the Commission to convert any given producer case into what would amount to a National Gas Survey.","start":4873.207,"stop":4914.94,"duration":41.73},{"text":"It is very difficult to see how one can really draw the line once the floodgate is opened.And of course, if this were -- if this had happened in these cases, the Commission had accepted that proposition in these cases, it could not have decided the in-line question in any expeditious fashion.","start":4914.94,"stop":4936.962,"duration":22.02},{"text":"We suggest that the argument that need be considered here at the request of the consumer interest is really no different from the request which was turned down in the Callery cases that the producers are entitled to demonstrate the supply and demand situation by extensive evidence.","start":4936.962,"stop":4955.717,"duration":18.75},{"text":"These are the opposite sides of the coin and it seems to us that the Fifth Circuit is completely correct in saying that the decision in Callery approving the Commission's administrative judgment as to in-line cases should also be followed here.","start":4955.717,"stop":4978.624,"duration":22.91},{"text":"Perhaps one word should be said about what these prepayments are.","start":4978.624,"stop":4985.78,"duration":7.16},{"text":"There's been a -- before the Commission, the only specific question of with respect to need that was raised by the consumer interest was the allegation that some of the pipelines involved had large prepayment balances.","start":4985.78,"stop":5006.741,"duration":20.96},{"text":"Producers sell to pipelines under long term contracts and they are normally obligations under which the pipelines must take a certain amount of gas which is usually related to the reserves underlying the contract or else pay for it.","start":5006.741,"stop":5026.643,"duration":19.9},{"text":"However, this doesn't mean that if -- if you pay for some gas not taken, that there's an immediate forfeitures.","start":5026.643,"stop":5035.41,"duration":8.77},{"text":"As a matter of fact, the Commission has had virtually no situations of any forfeiture.","start":5035.41,"stop":5041.417,"duration":6.01},{"text":"And there is a period in which the pipelines can make up the gas previously paid for and not taken.","start":5041.417,"stop":5049.307,"duration":7.89},{"text":"During this period of make up, the amount of money that has been paid out is included in the pipelines rate face, essentially its working capital so that there is then -- a return would be earned on that and this could have some consequence in the event of a rate case.","start":5049.307,"stop":5074.807,"duration":25.5},{"text":"However, as the Commission pointed out and it is really quite in the nature of the gas producing business that at times, a pipeline will have to buy gas a little bit before it needs all of that to assure that it has the adequate deliverability when its existing reserves start declining.","start":5074.807,"stop":5099.47,"duration":24.66},{"text":"In addition to that, most pipelines have had rapid expansion and they have to go out and buy gas to make sure that they will be able to meet their commitments in the future, because gas unlike staple products, has to be bought when it can be found and at particular location.","start":5099.47,"stop":5126.294,"duration":26.82},{"text":"And of course, some gas supplies are much better than other gas supplies because they are near existing pipelines and can be utilized more efficiently.","start":5126.294,"stop":5136.683,"duration":10.39},{"text":"So in these circumstances, it is not surprising that the Commission said that there are sometimes some slight prepayment situations.","start":5136.683,"stop":5145.744,"duration":9.06},{"text":"In some instances, although in only one instance here, a pipeline has a substantial prepayment situation and that's United Gas Pipeline Company.","start":5145.744,"stop":5156.121,"duration":10.38},{"text":"And most of the gas which was being sold that it involved in these cases, is no longer being sold.","start":5156.121,"stop":5164.938,"duration":8.82},{"text":"And then an authorization was approved for that, so very little gas to that pipeline company is now at issue here.","start":5164.938,"stop":5174.108,"duration":9.17},{"text":"But however that may be, an in depth study of the question of whether a pipeline needs the gas to meet its actual delivery requirements, a question which is not directly related to whether or not its -- in the past for example, it has had to pay for some gas it couldn't use.","start":5174.108,"stop":5195.868,"duration":21.76},{"text":"In itself would present a complex problem which would greatly complicate -- would have complicated these in-line proceedings.","start":5195.868,"stop":5205.972,"duration":10.1},{"text":"And we think that the Commission's view that questions this type are appropriately to be considered in pipeline proceedings both to the informal methods I've described and through formal hearing procedures is plainly reasonable in the proper exercise of the Commission's regulatory functions.","start":5205.972,"stop":5230.688,"duration":24.72},{"text":"For these reasons, we asked that all the Commission orders here under review be affirmed by this Court.","start":5230.688,"stop":5240.187,"duration":9.5},{"text":"Thank you.","start":5240.187,"stop":5252.209,"duration":12.02}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Coleman.","start":5252.209,"stop":5253.396,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Good afternoon Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":5253.396,"stop":5257.846,"duration":4.45},{"text":"My client, the United Gas Improvement Company sells gas to the ultimate consumer in Philadelphia and elsewhere in Pennsylvania.","start":5257.846,"stop":5269.653,"duration":11.81},{"text":"It's petitioner -- it is a petitioner in number 61 and 97.","start":5269.653,"stop":5276.441,"duration":6.79},{"text":"In each case, it seeks to reverse the judgments of the Tenth Circuit which one, affirm the Commission decision, that the public interest and necessity price for 1960 through 1962 sales of natural gas in Railroad District Number 4 was 16 cents per Mcf, the so called in-line issue, but the same decision reversed the Commission decision that it had the power to and should order refunds in these proceedings.","start":5276.441,"stop":5313.342,"duration":36.9},{"text":"In other words, UGI supports the Commission's argument on the refund issue but disagrees with its argument with attempts to justify the change from a 15-cent line to a 16-cent line.","start":5313.342,"stop":5328.303,"duration":14.96},{"text":"And exercising that restraint which most lawyers can't do, I've decided to leave to Mr. Simons who is petitioner -- who represents the petitioners in numbers 62 and the respondents in numbers 111, 143 and 144 to cover in the main, the in-line issue and I will direct my argument principally unless the Court wishes questions on the other issues to the refund issue.","start":5328.303,"stop":5359.214,"duration":30.91},{"text":"With respect to the refund issue, the basic issue is whether the Natural Gas Act provides authority for the Commission to require the producers to refund the amounts collected above the public interest and necessity price during the protracted period in which said producers and consumers were litigating that question, that is, what is the appropriate price?","start":5359.214,"stop":5388.179,"duration":28.97},{"text":"The producers would deny such power where the excessive amounts were collected.","start":5388.179,"stop":5394.42,"duration":6.24},{"text":"While the sales were made by the producers operating under the informal, temporary, ex parte letter which according to the producers did not -- in haec verba specifically say that they would have to refund the amount.","start":5394.42,"stop":5413.314,"duration":18.89},{"text":"Actually, as we view it, the issue is even more narrow.","start":5413.314,"stop":5417.492,"duration":4.18},{"text":"For Section 7 (e) of the Act which we set forth on page 4 of our brief, provides that the Commission should have the power to attach to the issuance of permanent certificates such reasonable terms and conditions as the public convenience and necessity may require.","start":5417.492,"stop":5440.116,"duration":22.62},{"text":"Thus as we view it, the narrow question is, is there anything the Natural Gas Act which would make the refund conditions here imposed unreasonable as a matter of lore?","start":5440.116,"stop":5452.071,"duration":11.95},{"text":"Now, this Court's decision in the Callery case which interprets the same language that I've just read and on this point, the Court was unanimous, held that the Commission had such power.","start":5452.071,"stop":5466.402,"duration":14.33},{"text":"And the Fifth Circuit just nine months ago in Continental Oil Company read the statute in the same way.","start":5466.402,"stop":5474.718,"duration":8.32},{"text":"And three years earlier, in the Skelly case, the D.C. Circuit which didn't have the benefit of your decision the Callery case also read the statute in the same way.","start":5474.718,"stop":5486.598,"duration":11.88},{"text":"And the decision of the Tenth Circuit which reached -- which reaches a different result interestingly enough, never cites, quotes nor discusses this statutory language that I referred to.","start":5486.598,"stop":5500.523,"duration":13.93},{"text":"Now, I would appreciate it if the Court would indulge with me for just a moment in a bit of history.","start":5500.523,"stop":5505.348,"duration":4.82},{"text":"And you will recall that for the last five years, at least once a term, you've had before you a case dealing with the Commission's regulatory problem including the terms and condition under which the initial sale of gas could be made in interstate commerce.","start":5505.348,"stop":5524.3,"duration":18.95},{"text":"And in each case, even though it's the pipeline who's the buyer and therefore should be the one in contesting whether this price is too high never appears before you but actually it's the distribution companies, the New York Commission, the California Commission and other persons representing the consumers.","start":5524.3,"stop":5544.82,"duration":20.52},{"text":"Now, the sure reason for this absent -- absence is at least twofold.In the first place, a lot of these pipeline companies also produce natural gas, so they -- therefore they have an interest to say the price isn't high as possible.","start":5544.82,"stop":5560.199,"duration":15.38},{"text":"And secondly, whatever the pipeline pays the producer for this gas gets put in the cost of service and therefore they can pass it on to the local distribution companies who've been -- would have to charge the consumer.","start":5560.199,"stop":5577.004,"duration":16.81},{"text":"Now, when the local distribution company began to apply upon interstate natural gas for their gas supply and the early cases show that the pipelines were able to buy gas as low as 2 to 4 cents per Mcf.","start":5577.004,"stop":5593.29,"duration":16.29},{"text":"But by 1956, as this Court knows from the CATCO case, the unregulated price had gone up to approximately 23.8 cents per Mcf.","start":5593.29,"stop":5604.196,"duration":10.91},{"text":"And therefore, this Court in the CATCO case said, that you could not issue a permanent certificate until after there had been a hearing and a determination as to whether the price was the appropriate price.","start":5604.196,"stop":5621.733,"duration":17.54},{"text":"Now, once this was done, the UGI along with the New York Public Service Commission established the litigation throughout the various Circuits that the Commission had a responsibility to see that the price charge was no greater than other prices which had been certificated.","start":5621.733,"stop":5641.874,"duration":20.14},{"text":"Now, this approach and these decisions were eventually approved by this Court in the Callery dealing with permanent certificates.","start":5641.874,"stop":5648.663,"duration":6.79},{"text":"These decisions certainly kept the price of natural gas down.","start":5648.663,"stop":5653.526,"duration":4.86},{"text":"But it also meant that the producer could not introduce a gas into interstate commerce, commence a sale until after there's been a hearing and a finding as to what was the appropriate price.","start":5653.526,"stop":5666.613,"duration":13.09},{"text":"And even though the Commission had decided that the appropriate price for example was 22 cents, if the distributors and the New York Commission then took it to the Court and got a reversal, this Court in Callery held that when you get around to making the final certificate, you can impose a refund condition.","start":5666.613,"stop":5685.103,"duration":18.49},{"text":"As the result of these decisions, the battleground between the consumer and the producers shifted.","start":5685.103,"stop":5691.865,"duration":6.76},{"text":"The producers began to attach to their application for permanent certificate or they would file it shortly thereafter, a request for temporary authorization to commence the sale of gas immediately and they could do this because Section 7 (c) says that in the emergency situation, you can ex parte without a hearing, without any evidence, without any finding get this temporary relief.","start":5691.865,"stop":5722.336,"duration":30.47},{"text":"Now, at this point, I'd like to direct the Court's attention to Volume 1 of the record, pages 78 and 79.","start":5722.336,"stop":5737.193,"duration":14.86},{"text":"And you will note that in their finding, the application of Sunray Mid-Continent for the temporary authorization.","start":5737.193,"stop":5746.612,"duration":9.42},{"text":"And as you read this, you will note that there is no allegation that this is the in-line price.","start":5746.612,"stop":5753.762,"duration":7.15},{"text":"There is no request for a hearing, there is no evidence attached to it.","start":5753.762,"stop":5757.276,"duration":3.51},{"text":"This is the application.","start":5757.276,"stop":5761.351,"duration":4.07},{"text":"You will also note that the reason given for the request is not that they want to help the consumer, not that they want to help the pipeline but they have a problem peculiar to themselves.","start":5761.351,"stop":5773.73,"duration":12.38},{"text":"Namely, that they had built a well right next to another well.","start":5773.73,"stop":5777.367,"duration":3.64},{"text":"The other well had been certificated on behalf of another producer and if these people couldn't turn that gas on, this first producer would take the gas.","start":5777.367,"stop":5787.332,"duration":9.97},{"text":"So this was an economic detriment to the -- to the Sunray, not to anyone else.","start":5787.332,"stop":5796.745,"duration":9.41},{"text":"You will note that that letter was received by the Commission on January 23rd, 1961.","start":5796.745,"stop":5803.589,"duration":6.84},{"text":"And then when you turn to page 80 and 81, you will see what is here called a temporary certificate.","start":5803.589,"stop":5812.024,"duration":8.44},{"text":"It is merely a letter from the Commission which went out on February 14th, 21 days.","start":5812.024,"stop":5818.544,"duration":6.52},{"text":"The consumers never notified, no hearing, no contest.","start":5818.544,"stop":5822.556,"duration":4.01},{"text":"It says that we accept your request for temporary authorization but acceptance of the rates schedule for temporary service is no assurance that it will be accepted by the Commission for permanent service.","start":5822.556,"stop":5837.16,"duration":14.6},{"text":"The Commission then specifically points out that the acceptance for filing should not be construed as constituting approval of any rate, charge, classification or any rule, regulation or practice affecting such rate of service.","start":5837.16,"stop":5851.468,"duration":14.31},{"text":"And then in the last paragraph and if you indulge me just to read this, this constitutes all requisites, temporary authorization to commence the sale of gas.","start":5851.468,"stop":5862.146,"duration":10.68},{"text":"But such authorization and acceptance of the rate schedule are without prejudice to such final disposition of certificate application as the record may require.","start":5862.146,"stop":5872.791,"duration":10.65},{"text":"Now, there's some statement that the producer wasn't on warning but I think that as I read that language, it certainly to the best of all human possibility, tried to tell the producer, you can turn this gas on stream, but when we finally get around to the hearing, this -- you may well be affected.","start":5872.791,"stop":5891.922,"duration":19.13},{"text":"And to answer -- to answer your question Mr. Justice White, I do feel that if the certificate had said that the Commission denied that it had the authority on permanent certification to order the refund, that that would have been contrary to your decision in CATCO and that decision certainly if we gotten to the D.C. Circuit would have been reversed.","start":5891.922,"stop":5916.221,"duration":24.3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, with these -- with these initial prices under the temporary certificate guideline pricing?","start":5916.221,"stop":5920.883,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They were -- they were not more than the guideline price, Your Honor, that that's true Mr. Justice White.","start":5920.883,"stop":5926.432,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commission had set the guideline prices for initial sales?","start":5926.432,"stop":5930.309,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you mean by set, that the Commission had issued --","start":5930.309,"stop":5933.618,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"May have suggested them?","start":5933.618,"stop":5934.875,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- suggested them, and that -- those guideline prices are reproduced in the Sunray brief in the appendix in 7 (a).","start":5934.875,"stop":5944.939,"duration":10.06},{"text":"I wish you would read about seven lines from the bottom which says that this is well affecting the substantive right of any party.","start":5944.939,"stop":5953.512,"duration":8.57},{"text":"Now, if you're going to hold that somehow that guideline price changes what would otherwise be the consumer's right, you, by definition saying that it affects our substantive right.","start":5953.512,"stop":5964.193,"duration":10.68},{"text":"And I think that that was the suggested price and what the administrative, the Commission was saying is as far as the Commission was concerned, if you did at this price, we will issue the temporary letter.","start":5964.193,"stop":5974.982,"duration":10.79},{"text":"But it was also clear that the consumer who weren't permitted to intervene would attack that price which we did and by a trial before the Commission, we demonstrated that the 18 cent was too high and it should not be more than 16-cents and in fact we argue it should not be more than 15.","start":5974.982,"stop":5992.478,"duration":17.5},{"text":"And when we really get around the litigation, it was determined that the consumer was right and therefore, if you hold that merely because the Commission mentioned certain figures, that that affects our right, and I think you're doing contrary to what the public --","start":5992.478,"stop":6005.2,"duration":12.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the question I asked earlier was -- if the permission in this case had said in its certificate, these initial prices shall not be subject to refund.","start":6005.2,"stop":6017.414,"duration":12.21},{"text":"My question was whether the Commission had the power to say -- not only to say that but to act in accordance with it.","start":6017.414,"stop":6023.998,"duration":6.58}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I would -- I would take the position that the Commission would not have such power and that type of certificate would have been reversed by the Court.","start":6023.998,"stop":6032.666,"duration":8.67},{"text":"That's -- that's our position.","start":6032.666,"stop":6035.024,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- don't you -- don't you really just about you have to get to that in this case --","start":6035.024,"stop":6039.103,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":6039.103,"stop":6039.135,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- where the --","start":6039.135,"stop":6039.876,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":6039.876,"stop":6040.266,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- where the Commission has -- has turned down a request to expressly condition the temporary on refunds?","start":6040.266,"stop":6052.062,"duration":11.8}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'd like to answer that question right now, Your Honors, if you will give about a minute and half to answer it, because I have to give you a better history, that contrary to what the producers say, the producers claim that from 1956 until the D.C. Circuit reversed in the Skelly Oil case that there was announced Commission, a policy that they would not impose such refunds.","start":6052.062,"stop":6078.918,"duration":26.86},{"text":"Now, the only case that they cite and this is on page 50 of Sunray's brief, in the Signal Oil case which went up to the Third Circuit.","start":6078.918,"stop":6090.486,"duration":11.57},{"text":"Now, despite the fact in their brief they claim that the Third Circuit had made the decision that they could not order the refund.","start":6090.486,"stop":6097.005,"duration":6.52},{"text":"I read that opinion five times, there is no such a language in the case that all the -- that case dealt with whether if you issue the temporary certificate at there at 12 cents, and then when you got around to the permanent hearing, you reduced it to 10 cents, could you do that without having a just and reasonable finding?","start":6097.005,"stop":6118.597,"duration":21.59},{"text":"The Commission said you could.","start":6118.597,"stop":6120.032,"duration":1.44},{"text":"The Third Circuit said you could.","start":6120.032,"stop":6122.402,"duration":2.37},{"text":"And the producer somehow, because the Commission didn't also say in refund in the 2 cents difference, that nobody asked them to do, the consumers weren't involved in that case, the point wasn't litigated, they say that that is the decision which demonstrates that this was an announcement of Commission policy.","start":6122.402,"stop":6141.496,"duration":19.09},{"text":"Now, certainly, the absence of one swallow to change the metaphor doesn't make a winner.","start":6141.496,"stop":6148.312,"duration":6.82},{"text":"And the fact is that in January 1962, in the CATCO case on remand, and we reproduce this on page 18 of our brief, the Commission specifically holds that in unconditioned temporary certificates with didn't have the refund provision that you still could order the refunds.","start":6148.312,"stop":6170.405,"duration":22.09},{"text":"So in 1962, you have this -- you have the Signal Oil case where the issue was not argued.","start":6170.405,"stop":6176.076,"duration":5.67},{"text":"It was not passed upon, there was no such decision, no language, then you have the CATCO on remand.","start":6176.076,"stop":6182.448,"duration":6.37},{"text":"The next case is the Skelly Oil case.","start":6182.448,"stop":6185.605,"duration":3.16},{"text":"We, the consumer interest urged in Skelly Oil that even though the words weren't in the temporary, you still could impose a condition.","start":6185.605,"stop":6194.514,"duration":8.91},{"text":"The Commission in August 1962 decided the case against us.","start":6194.514,"stop":6199.916,"duration":5.4},{"text":"We then took the only relief we can do other than go to the corner bar where you lose the case, we took an appeal.","start":6199.916,"stop":6206.135,"duration":6.22},{"text":"And that appeal was pending in the D.C. Circuit.","start":6206.135,"stop":6209.278,"duration":3.14},{"text":"Then as cautious lawyers, because the Commission has said that we had no authority to do this, or at least we shouldn't do it, unless the condition is in there, we then asked the condition to do it.","start":6209.278,"stop":6221.93,"duration":12.65},{"text":"And the Commission said that they were not in the midst of a hearing before the evidence was in, it was not going to put in the condition.","start":6221.93,"stop":6230.161,"duration":8.23},{"text":"We then won the case in the D.C. Circuit which says that from the beginning, even without imposing such a condition, we had this power.","start":6230.161,"stop":6237.495,"duration":7.33},{"text":"Now, I think under those circumstances, it's kind of difficult to say that the consumer now should be estopped from claiming that the Commission does have the authority and they should exercise the power.","start":6237.495,"stop":6252.752,"duration":15.26},{"text":"I would next like -- and I'd also like to point out that the language that I read is as clear a warning as people could give that there was no finality to this right.","start":6252.752,"stop":6268.333,"duration":15.58},{"text":"And I certainly would say as a lawyer, I would advise my client that there was more finality to the Callery property.","start":6268.333,"stop":6276.141,"duration":7.81},{"text":"The final decision of the Commission which held what the rights should be, nobody asked for a stay and that was the rate -- it was a final order subject only to appeal and this Court had no problem there saying that if it turned out you were wrong, you could impose the condition.","start":6276.141,"stop":6293.329,"duration":17.19},{"text":"I would next like to turn to another point in the case which is a -- which arises from the fact that before the Commission, this case was decided in two parts.","start":6293.329,"stop":6307.669,"duration":14.34},{"text":"In opinion 422, the Commission held that they had the power but left to a later hearing whether there were any -- there was any reason why as a matter of equity, the power should not be exercised.","start":6307.669,"stop":6321.045,"duration":13.38},{"text":"An appeal was taken to the Tenth Circuit.","start":6321.045,"stop":6323.05,"duration":2.01},{"text":"The Tenth Circuit decided that there was no power.","start":6323.05,"stop":6328.002,"duration":4.95},{"text":"Thereafter, the Commission decided that on the equities, the consumers were entitled to the refund.","start":6328.002,"stop":6334.039,"duration":6.04},{"text":"When that case was appealed to the Tenth Circuit, the Tenth Circuit said, “Well, we already said you had no power, so we never get to the equity question”.","start":6334.039,"stop":6342.086,"duration":8.05},{"text":"Now, both points were then brought to this Court and I'd like to urge that this Commission should affirm the decision of the Commission in its entirety rather than holding that the Tenth Circuit was incorrect as a whole, on the question of power, and then sending it back to the Tenth Circuit to pass on the equity questions.","start":6342.086,"stop":6361.144,"duration":19.06},{"text":"Now, the reasons for asking for this is in one, that there are a lot of precedents of this Court where you've done it, or you've done just this.","start":6361.144,"stop":6370.921,"duration":9.78},{"text":"Particularly, when you're dealing with the Federal Power Commission because by time these cases get to you the first time, there's such a long time and these contracts are only 20-year contract and seven years have gone by already.","start":6370.921,"stop":6382.816,"duration":11.89},{"text":"So we do think that you ought to decide it now.","start":6382.816,"stop":6385.093,"duration":2.28},{"text":"You do have the full case here.","start":6385.093,"stop":6388.019,"duration":2.93},{"text":"And as I said, one third of the time is already gone by.","start":6388.019,"stop":6394.444,"duration":6.43},{"text":"Now, the only reason why the Commission -- the producers and on this point, what the Commission said that we will accept all of your factual allegations in your brief and whatever you claim on the facts, we will decide the issue on that basis.","start":6394.444,"stop":6409.144,"duration":14.7},{"text":"So the producers can't complain that they could put in more evidence because they said, “Well, whatever you said and represented in your brief, we will decide on that basis”.","start":6409.144,"stop":6417.822,"duration":8.68},{"text":"But their first reason is that they relied upon the absence of the expressed provision.","start":6417.822,"stop":6423.979,"duration":6.16},{"text":"I'd like to recall your attention again, the CATCO on remand case were held that they did have the authorities, so it seems to me that they ought not to be relying upon that.","start":6423.979,"stop":6434.855,"duration":10.88},{"text":"Secondly, we submit that the temporary authorization did contain such a warning and thirdly, that the producers had executed these contracts before they received any type of authorization.","start":6434.855,"stop":6448.551,"duration":13.7},{"text":"So if you execute a contract in 1960, you then file it and you apply for temporary authority in 1961.","start":6448.551,"stop":6457.295,"duration":8.74},{"text":"I failed to see how and what you did in 1961 can affect the situation.","start":6457.295,"stop":6465.778,"duration":8.48},{"text":"The second reason they gave was that -- that during the time when they thought that they would not have to make these refunds --","start":6465.778,"stop":6475.603,"duration":9.82}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"They wouldn't have made the sales, Mr. Coleman, would they?","start":6475.603,"stop":6478.577,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What's that?","start":6478.577,"stop":6479.514,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"They wouldn't have made the sales before they got the temporary authorization?","start":6479.514,"stop":6483.187,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they couldn't do that, Your Honor.","start":6483.187,"stop":6484.73,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, so that the sales that they made we made pursuant to the temporary authorization --","start":6484.73,"stop":6491.108,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":6491.108,"stop":6491.838,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- although they were under the terms of a prior contract?","start":6491.838,"stop":6495.623,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":6495.623,"stop":6496.136,"duration":0.51},{"text":"And also, they were made under temporary authorization which represented that if you don't give it to us, we're going to lose our gas.","start":6496.136,"stop":6505.216,"duration":9.08},{"text":"It's going to be flared.","start":6505.216,"stop":6506.351,"duration":1.13},{"text":"It's going to be drained.","start":6506.351,"stop":6508.544,"duration":2.19},{"text":"So, it seems to me that the business decision was between whether for the next seven years, they were going to get zero or were they're going to get 16 or 18 cents because that's the allegation on which the Commission issued the temporary authorization.","start":6508.544,"stop":6526.55,"duration":18.01}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Wasn't there a -- wasn't there a -- didn't the Commission turned down a request for a provision in the temporary authorization explicitly reserving the power for you to make refunds?","start":6526.55,"stop":6539.733,"duration":13.18}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I -- I answer that question with respect to Mr. Justice White.","start":6539.733,"stop":6542.386,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon.","start":6542.386,"stop":6543.088,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the order of February 5th, 1963.","start":6543.088,"stop":6547.523,"duration":4.44},{"text":"And that was done after we had lost Skelly before the Commission but taken an appeal to the D.C. Circuit.","start":6547.523,"stop":6554.856,"duration":7.33},{"text":"And then out of fondness of cautions, the lawyers say, “Well, if we're wrong there we're going to try to at least cut down on losses.","start":6554.856,"stop":6563.052,"duration":8.2},{"text":"Why don't you do it now?”","start":6563.052,"stop":6564.514,"duration":1.46},{"text":"The Commission said they would not do it in the interim because they were still holding the hearing, but then we won the first case which said that ab initio we had the power even though there was not such condition.","start":6564.514,"stop":6576.64,"duration":12.13}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't think that goes -- you don't think that history goes to the equities of the situation at all?","start":6576.64,"stop":6581.309,"duration":4.67}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, because I just don't think that by reading the temporary authorization language, reading CATCO on remand, reading the general history here that the producer could reasonably say that he could keep this money.","start":6581.309,"stop":6598.925,"duration":17.62},{"text":"Now, the one reason they gave which appealed to the Commission was that -- that while they were collecting the higher amount, they were paying royalties and taxes to the -- royalties to the owner and taxes to the State of Texas and since they paid it not under protest, they may not be able to get it back.","start":6598.925,"stop":6620.752,"duration":21.83},{"text":"So the Commission took care of that saying, during the interim before -- from the time you started until Skelly was decided, we will let you deduct the taxes.","start":6620.752,"stop":6630.528,"duration":9.78},{"text":"The third reason they gave and only two of them gave this reason, namely Humble and Texas Oil was that by collecting these amounts, thinking that they were not subject to refund, that they took budgetary positions and financing which they otherwise would not have done.","start":6630.528,"stop":6652.182,"duration":21.65},{"text":"And the Commission there found that involved with Humble Oil was only $1500 of refund and involved with Texas was only $25,000 and since that these are both multimillion, if not billion dollar corporation, it would beyond comprehension that that amount of money could really affect their planning.","start":6652.182,"stop":6675.177,"duration":22.99},{"text":"The other reason given was that there was no proof to these refunds would go to the ultimate consumer and the Commission has followed the policy there of saying that we will direct this money as far down the chain as we under our power can do.","start":6675.177,"stop":6692.557,"duration":17.38},{"text":"Also, the New York Commission and the other Commissions have been very active in seeing that this money did go to the ultimate consumers.","start":6692.557,"stop":6701.266,"duration":8.71},{"text":"Now, the fifth and last reason was that you should wait until the just and reasonable hearing before you order the refund.","start":6701.266,"stop":6710.668,"duration":9.4},{"text":"Now, if the opinion of Mr. Justice Harlan in the Callery case had prevailed, perhaps that would make some sense.","start":6710.668,"stop":6719.388,"duration":8.72},{"text":"But once this Court in Callery said that you measure it by the in-line price rather than by the just and reasonable price and I think that reason goes by the Board.","start":6719.388,"stop":6731.304,"duration":11.92},{"text":"As I said at the beginning on my argument, the basic issue here is having one CATCO, having finally decided the proposition that gas could not go into interstate commerce at any price higher than the public convenience and necessity price, does the consumer now lose the ball -- lose the ballgame by saying that when you are able to block the producer, because they couldn't get a permanent certificate which required a hearing that he can get a greater rate by coming back the next day, asking for temporary relief under a letter, which letter the consumers never got served with -- didn't know anything about it, there was no hearing, and that that letter agreement has greater validity, more power and more significance than the permanent certificate would have had without a hearing.","start":6731.304,"stop":6790.413,"duration":59.11}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what do you --","start":6790.413,"stop":6790.834,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean --","start":6790.834,"stop":6790.903,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"say about the effect, if any, of the guideline prices?","start":6790.903,"stop":6797.027,"duration":6.12}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the guideline prices ought to have no effect whatsoever Your Honor because they were issued without a contest and they were strictly the suggestion of the Commission as to how it would act internally pending the resolution of the area rate case, pending the resolution of the in-line cases.","start":6797.027,"stop":6823.649,"duration":26.62}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose, but it's possible that you take a producer who operating under a temporary certificate and he sold his gas at the guideline price, a guideline price being the Commission price -- there was no reservation -- expressed reservation in the -- or explicit or specific reservation in the temporary certificate, his feelings might be hurt if the Commission later ordered a refund cutting back behind the guideline price.","start":6823.649,"stop":6860.189,"duration":36.54}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they -- they should not be hurt Your Honor and I assure you they won't be hurt -- more hurt than that of the consumer who has litigated, has had a finding that he is right, and then finds out because it took him seven years to get here, that that the producer by a letter which nobody contested gets rights that he wouldn't have gotten if he'd asked for a permanent certificate, if the Commission had wrongly issued the permanent certificate and would gotten here by way of the Callery rule.","start":6860.189,"stop":6894.72,"duration":34.53},{"text":"And I would like Your Honor or this -- I think it's the brief for respondents Sunray DX, it's the green one, on 7 (a) when the Commission made these announcements.","start":6894.72,"stop":6906.912,"duration":12.19},{"text":"And it says, “These price levels as announced by Appendix A attached to this statement are for the purpose of guidance and initial action by the Commission and they're used to not deprived any party of substantive rights or fix”, repeat “or fix the ultimate justness and reasonableness of any rate level”.","start":6906.912,"stop":6928.989,"duration":22.08},{"text":"And actually, I think the producers attempted to take the guidelines to Court and the Court held that it was not an appealable order because it was just a policy announcement.","start":6928.989,"stop":6940.966,"duration":11.98},{"text":"It's just as though a Commission may say, “Well, as far as we're concerned, if you do A, B and C, we will not do anything.","start":6940.966,"stop":6949.313,"duration":8.35},{"text":"But if some litigant comes in and he makes a protest, we will then hear it.”","start":6949.313,"stop":6953.768,"duration":4.45},{"text":"We did come in, we made the protest we want.","start":6953.768,"stop":6956.779,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You referred several times to the fact that this producer's letter was not served on the consumer, would it make any difference to your argument if it had been?","start":6956.779,"stop":6966.734,"duration":9.95}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think not, Your Honor for this reason, after these cases got into the Commission and the consumer's custody said, “Well, certainly you can't continue to issue these ex parte orders because we don't know about them and if these are going affect our rights, we should know about them”.","start":6966.734,"stop":6986.441,"duration":19.71},{"text":"By this time, we had lost Skelly so we thought -- we thought we were right, but we had to go the Court to have our rights vindicated if we did.","start":6986.441,"stop":6994.443,"duration":8},{"text":"The Commission then for the first time began to take the letter and put it in the public reference office.","start":6994.443,"stop":7004.776,"duration":10.33},{"text":"And the New York Commission by great diligence, by going there everyday, going through every document, finally found one which is the J. Ray McDermott which had been issued.","start":7004.776,"stop":7017.444,"duration":12.67},{"text":"The Commission then appealed that to the D.C. Circuit and the D.C. Circuit held that the Commission could not be reversed because the order was tentative and when you get around to the hearing on the permanent certificate at that point, the Commission could order that the difference between the price charge in the temporary and the actual public convenience and necessity price should be charged.","start":7017.444,"stop":7048.351,"duration":30.91},{"text":"So, the D.C. Circuit which is the only Circuit that has really looked at all aspects of this problem had made it clear that that -- you're in a dilemma here, that if you hold that the temporary certificate has this great substantive effect that the producers would have, then you certainly have to give the consumer an opportunity to contest it.","start":7048.351,"stop":7071.943,"duration":23.59},{"text":"Now, if you're going to contest it before the Commission, you have to have the same hearing that you -- that you said you had to have in CATCO.","start":7071.943,"stop":7078.99,"duration":7.05},{"text":"Now, if you had that hearing, it's going to take you a year or two to get it resolved.","start":7078.99,"stop":7084.603,"duration":5.61},{"text":"Now, if the producer in the meantime is losing its gas to the drainage or flaring, he can't afford to wait two years.","start":7084.603,"stop":7092.345,"duration":7.74},{"text":"So the only alternative is to issue an ex parte, to issue it without a hearing, without a contest and then when the parties have the contest, determine that you have to refund the difference between what you were charging and what is determined as the public convenience and necessity price.","start":7092.345,"stop":7112.839,"duration":20.49},{"text":"That's what the D.C. Circuit did.","start":7112.839,"stop":7114.616,"duration":1.78},{"text":"McDermott and Skelly Oil and we submit that that's the appropriate way that this matter should be handled.","start":7114.616,"stop":7119.804,"duration":5.19}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Coleman, at what price is it does the producers has been selling gas since the in-line price determination?","start":7119.804,"stop":7126.549,"duration":6.74}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they have been selling it -- because I don't think there's been a stay -- they would be selling it at --","start":7126.549,"stop":7134.006,"duration":7.46}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"At the in-line?","start":7134.006,"stop":7134.248,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the 16 cents.","start":7134.248,"stop":7135.523,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"At the in-line prices?","start":7135.523,"stop":7136.481,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":7136.481,"stop":7136.836,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Which is set in this case?","start":7136.836,"stop":7138.416,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh!","start":7138.416,"stop":7139.607,"duration":1.19},{"text":"I -- pardon me.","start":7139.607,"stop":7140.487,"duration":0.88},{"text":"The stays had been granted --","start":7140.487,"stop":7142.21,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh!","start":7142.21,"stop":7142.334,"duration":0.12},{"text":"I see.","start":7142.334,"stop":7142.639,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So they still are selling it at the 18 cents.","start":7142.639,"stop":7146.245,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but if -- if they had done -- if they hadn't been selling at the in-line price, but it was determined in this proceeding, that the in-line price was set to high, then under Callery, they would have to make a refund back to the --","start":7146.245,"stop":7159.196,"duration":12.95}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they could have been doing that, Your Honor.","start":7159.196,"stop":7161.397,"duration":2.2},{"text":"You can only fix an in-line price after you had a litigated hearing.","start":7161.397,"stop":7167.446,"duration":6.05}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand, which there has been in this case?","start":7167.446,"stop":7170.327,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's -- that's the issue this here before you now.","start":7170.327,"stop":7173.836,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I know, but you're claiming for example, in-line price that was set is too high.","start":7173.836,"stop":7178.213,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":7178.213,"stop":7179.334,"duration":1.12},{"text":"That's a direct appeal, we tell you.","start":7179.334,"stop":7180.59,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, let assume you won --","start":7180.59,"stop":7182.834,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We hope we do --","start":7182.834,"stop":7183.045,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on that.","start":7183.045,"stop":7183.699,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on that point.","start":7183.699,"stop":7184.698,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Assuming then that -- and the producers had been charging the higher in-line price meanwhile, there would be a refund.","start":7184.698,"stop":7193.663,"duration":8.96}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":7193.663,"stop":7194.432,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Under -- under Callery?","start":7194.432,"stop":7195.904,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":7195.904,"stop":7196.432,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":7196.432,"stop":7197.021,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no doubt.","start":7197.021,"stop":7197.699,"duration":0.68},{"text":"And what we are saying is that where they were charging 18 cents under a letter, at which we couldn't contest --","start":7197.699,"stop":7207.881,"duration":10.18}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":7207.881,"stop":7209.59,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And we by contesting could convince even the Taft Commission that it should be 16 cents, that we ought to get the 2 cents back.","start":7209.59,"stop":7221.203,"duration":11.61},{"text":"Now, if we are successful in this Court, it rolls back to 15 cents and I think if Callery means anything, it means that we get that one penny back, and it seems to me that if after a full hearing and a trial, you -- you get the one cent back under the permanent certificate, and it seems to me that it follows as night as the day although in the law, a lot of times, you can't be this confident that you have to give us back the three cents and that's what we submit is the issue here.","start":7221.203,"stop":7253.224,"duration":32.02},{"text":"And therefore we urge that --","start":7253.224,"stop":7254.831,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What you're saying is that they've collected more than the Commission has now held, for the fair and reasonable rate, that you've been denied a refund of this difference.","start":7254.831,"stop":7265.566,"duration":10.73}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":7265.566,"stop":7266.23,"duration":0.66},{"text":"Well, it's not -- it's the public convenience --","start":7266.23,"stop":7269.201,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":7269.201,"stop":7269.382,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and necessity pricing.","start":7269.382,"stop":7270.106,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Whatever you want to call it.","start":7270.106,"stop":7271.17,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":7271.17,"stop":7271.897,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Public convenience and necessity.","start":7271.897,"stop":7273.154,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":7273.154,"stop":7273.464,"duration":0.31},{"text":"And also --","start":7273.464,"stop":7274.058,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"They've collected a rate above that.","start":7274.058,"stop":7276.048,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":7276.048,"stop":7276.488,"duration":0.44},{"text":"Yes sir.","start":7276.488,"stop":7276.878,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And that you're insisting that you have the right to recover it.","start":7276.878,"stop":7279.829,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's a reason --","start":7279.829,"stop":7280.137,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The refund.","start":7280.137,"stop":7280.942,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's a reasonable condition under Section 7 (a) in a permanent certificate that where a producer interjects gas in interstate commerce before he gets a final certificate and he does it under representation that if you don't let me do it, I'm going to lose my gas forever, that is a reasonable condition for the Commission to say that now that we've determined, you should have been charging only 16 cents if they're right, or 15 cents if we're right, you also have to pay back the additional two or three cents depending upon what --","start":7280.942,"stop":7316.087,"duration":35.15}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Should you win, no further hearings would be necessary?","start":7316.087,"stop":7319.442,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If we win, no further hearings would be necessary.","start":7319.442,"stop":7322.869,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's already been computed.","start":7322.869,"stop":7324.815,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's already been -- well, it's been -- it's been computed in the sense that that -- that anyone who can read can make the computation and then I think I under the order --","start":7324.815,"stop":7335.141,"duration":10.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Three cents.","start":7335.141,"stop":7336.235,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What's that?","start":7336.235,"stop":7336.821,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Three cents.","start":7336.821,"stop":7337.607,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Three cents, and under the order you could -- you have to know how many volumes they sold.","start":7337.607,"stop":7343.623,"duration":6.02},{"text":"The order says within 30 days, they have to come in and file what the figure is and then they file it and then they pay it back.","start":7343.623,"stop":7351.009,"duration":7.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's good theoretically or maybe theoretical or not, so far on the question of equity --","start":7351.009,"stop":7358.013,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no Your Honor.","start":7358.013,"stop":7358.529,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- will going to be interpreted.","start":7358.529,"stop":7359.765,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought that the second half of my argument was --","start":7359.765,"stop":7363.286,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You are --","start":7363.286,"stop":7363.586,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- determine --","start":7363.586,"stop":7364.166,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- going to determine that up here?","start":7364.166,"stop":7365.634,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Up here and that if you send it back -- just look at the dates, these contracts executed 1960-62.","start":7365.634,"stop":7375.532,"duration":9.9},{"text":"They had got the temporary authorization in 1961.","start":7375.532,"stop":7380.652,"duration":5.12},{"text":"The Commission 422 I think is 1964, by the time they get around to 501, you're in 1966, you then go to the Court of Appeals, it's 1968 now, and these contracts are only 20-year contracts Your Honor, at some point, I think the Court ought to decide it and decide it finally --","start":7380.652,"stop":7399.607,"duration":18.95}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you asking --","start":7399.607,"stop":7399.858,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and not send it back.","start":7399.858,"stop":7400.559,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you asking for interest?","start":7400.559,"stop":7402.468,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What's that?","start":7402.468,"stop":7402.96,"duration":0.49},{"text":"Oh yes.","start":7402.96,"stop":7403.868,"duration":0.91},{"text":"I -- well, only -- what Callery says, Your Honor, that to -- if the producers have been unjustly enriched that the remedy is that the Commission also impose interest and I think that right now is 7%.","start":7403.868,"stop":7421.091,"duration":17.22},{"text":"And therefore --","start":7421.091,"stop":7421.85,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the -- what's the approximate amount in case that your company will get if you prevail.","start":7421.85,"stop":7429.669,"duration":7.82}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's hard to tell you, Your Honor, because our company is really divided into two parts in the sense that we operate on behalf of the City of Philadelphia, the Philadelphia Gasworks.","start":7429.669,"stop":7445.965,"duration":16.3},{"text":"We also own as a normal public utility upstate companies.","start":7445.965,"stop":7451.582,"duration":5.62},{"text":"I would say, if you don't hold me to the figure, it's about a $150,000 or $200,000.","start":7451.582,"stop":7458.138,"duration":6.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What would you do with that refund?","start":7458.138,"stop":7459.394,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What do we do with it?","start":7459.394,"stop":7461.628,"duration":2.23},{"text":"That which goes the upstate companies, would go back to the consumers by way of a rate reduction.","start":7461.628,"stop":7473.057,"duration":11.43},{"text":"That which comes to the City of Philadelphia because the City of Philadelphia has an operating agreement with the UGI which says that for $800,000 regardless of the profit is, that's all the UGI gas.","start":7473.057,"stop":7487.936,"duration":14.88},{"text":"Any excess goes into the City Treasurer and that there are two or three cases in the Seventh or Eighth Circuit which I think in the Natural Gas case which is the whole -- and as a matter of law that when you can demonstrate, the money goes back into the general public treasure, that's the same as if you paid it to the consumer.","start":7487.936,"stop":7503.843,"duration":15.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Producer's taxes?","start":7503.843,"stop":7505.362,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What's that?","start":7505.362,"stop":7506.06,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Producer's taxes.","start":7506.06,"stop":7506.744,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"William T. Coleman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not only that, but it helps us to begin to solve some of the tremendous problems of the urban community, so we'd very much liked it to go back.","start":7506.744,"stop":7514.016,"duration":7.27},{"text":"Thank you.","start":7514.016,"stop":7515.919,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now.","start":7515.919,"stop":7523.789,"duration":7.87}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Jan  22 - 23, 1968","petitioner":"Federal Power Commission","respondent":"Sunray DX Oil Company","docket":"60","citation":"391 US 9 (1968)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/391/9","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"May 6, 1968"}